[White "Introduction"]
[Black "About The Author"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Hello everyone! My name is Benjamin Gledura, and I am a Grandmaster from Hungary. I was a top junior player for a long time, and since then, I have continued playing chess as a professional. My peak rating was 2654, and with that, I was in the Top 90 in the world. This is my first Chessable course, so bear with me. The Queen's Gambit Accepted is an opening that mainly teaches you principled chess, and by principled, I mean healthy positions that arise from logical moves.One of the first top-level Queen’s Gambit Accepted games was between Steinitz and Blackburne in 1899. That was the era when people started to understand the purpose of the Queen’s Gambit Accepted. Black wants to make an isolated d4-pawn for White by playing c5 and cxd4. At least that was the original concept of this opening. In modern days, most top-level grandmasters employ the Queen’s Gambit Accepted. For example, World Champion Magnus Carlsen, Hikaru Nakamura, and Leinier Dominguez are some of the many players who play the Queen’s Gambit Accepted from time to time. It is a very well-established and respected opening amongst all levels. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course, you will not only learn move-by-move opening theory but middlegame plans and ideas as well. One of my strong beliefs is that when you first learn about an opening, you have to understand the spirit of the opening. For example, where to put your pieces in general in the opening/middlegame, and what you should play for. I believe this course can make your chess better. It is not only about the Queen’s Gambit Accepted opening but also how to play chess in general, and I am here to show you that. At least I will do my best. Now, let’s make some moves on the board! }
1. d4 d5 2. c4
{ 2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Bf4  I have analyzed the London System a lot. This is one of the main sidelines that people employ against 1...d5.   3.e3  A very solid setup. White's idea is to develop with b3-Bb2-Nbd2-Bd3-O-O and Ne5.  3...e6  I recommend following what White does. I think it gives relatively easy equality for Black.   3.g3  This is a very common move. I don't consider it a critical move, but it is definitely a move that should be analyzed. White wants to develop with healthy moves, Bg2-O-O, and c4.  3...Bf5  I recommend the Bf5 setup. Next is ...e6-h6, Be7, and castle.   3.c3  e6  4.Bf4  c5  We will eventually transpose to the London System.  3...c5  4.e3  e6  I recommend a very principled setup. Next is Bd6-b6-Bb7-Qc7-Nbd7-O-O and later play for e5.   2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  . The Jobava London is a popular blitz/rapid opening. Therefore I paid quite a bit of attention to this line.   3.Bg5  h6  The Veresov Attack.   2.e4  The Blackmar Diemer Gambit. It is worth knowing how to handle this line as well after  2...dxe4  . }
2... dxc4
{ We have arrived at the Queen's Gambit Accepted opening. There are three main moves according to the opening theory here.  3.Nf3  and  3.e3  are very similar and they will transpose to each other, and the most critical line is  3.e4  . }
3. e4
{ This is the move that scares away most of the top grandmasters. This move often leads to a very complicated middlegame position. According to the opening theory, 3. e4 promises an advantage for White. However, not anymore! In this course, you will find the solution against 3. e4! At the end of 2021, some people found a fresh, rarely played idea that gives equality!   3.Nf3  Nf6  4.e3  e6  5.Bxc4  c5  6.O-O  a6  .   6.Qe2  is a slightly tricky move to avoid the mainline and can easily be met with  6...a6  .  This is the initial position of the Queen's Gambit Accepted 'classical' line. White has several moves here, and in this course, I will go through them all. Black has kind of an easy job here when it comes to choosing a plan. The main plan is to develop the minor pieces with ...b5-Bb7-Nbd7-Be7 and castle. If White decides to stop the b5-Bb7 plan, then we oftentimes have to play ...cxd4 and after exd4, play against the isolated d4-pawn.  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4  ,  7.Be2  ,  7.Nc3  ,  7.Qe2  ,  7.b3  , and  7.Nbd2  are all the possible moves White can play.   3.e3  Nf6  4.Bxc4  e6  5.Nf3  c5  Transposition. }
3... b5
{ This move itself is not a new idea. People have been trying to find interesting, new ideas in this line. However, the engines used to say that b5 was an advantage for White. }
4. a4 c6 5. axb5
{ 5.Nc3  A very serious move, but not the most critical.  5...b4  I believe this line gives equality for Black.   5.b3  It is not a good idea to open the position like this.  5...e5!  Black is in good shape here. }
5... cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6
{ This queen move is a fresh idea! I believe this line will encourage a lot of people to play the Queen's Gambit Accepted. The reason for that is that it is not only an 'interesting line,” but also proven to be good by the engines as well.   6...a6  This move used to be very popular at some point, however, engines show that White has a stable advantage.  7.Nxb5  axb5  8.Rxa8  Bb7  9.Ra2  . }
7. Nd5 { 7.b3!?  A sideline that needs attention.  7...e6  8.bxc4  Bb4 } 7...
Qb7 8. Bf4
{ White seems to have a devastating threat of Nc7. However, Black can create counterplay. }
8... e5 9. Bxe5 Nd7 { Attacking the great dark-squared bishop. } 10. Bf4
{ 10.Nc7+?  White cannot go for the fork here because of tactical reasons. This is one of the tricks of 6...Qb6.  10...Kd8  11.Nxa8??  Bb4+!  12.Ke2  Qxe4  Mate on the board on move 12! }
10... Ngf6
{ This is the main idea. Black sacrifices the exchange in order to get a great deal of compensation. }
11. Nc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8 Qxe4+ 13. Ne2 Qxa8
{ This is one of the critical positions of the fresh 6...Qb6 move. In this course, you will find a great deal of explanation about these middlegame positions.   I hope you will like my course, as I have really worked hard on it. I have analyzed for months to deliver good, and fresh ideas to you. I believe that Lifetime Repertoires: Gledura's Queen's Gambit Accepted gives you a lot of confidence to face the move 1. d4. I also think that this course is not only good for advanced players but for all kinds of levels, as my explanations are very detailed. Enjoy! }
