[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4
{ This is called the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG@@EndBracket@@. White is trying to unbalance the center by offering a pawn. However, this sacrifice is inappropriate, and if Black knows how to deal with this gambit, then it's relatively easy to get an advantage.  You are most likely to encounter  2.e4  in online games. }
2... dxe4 { Black accepts the sacrifice. } 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ This is White's main idea, giving up the pawn completely to get some development advantage in exchange.  After  4.Bg5?!  Bf5  5.Nge2  e6  6.Ng3  Bb4∓  Black would end up being a healthy pawn up. }
4... Bf5
{ Black usually responds with  4...exf3  and that would make the position more complicated than it needs to be. The move that I'm recommending gives Black an advantage without having to worry about development disadvantages. }
5. fxe4 Nxe4 6. Qf3
{ White has no real other option than to make this double-attacking move. Otherwise White would be just simply a pawn down. Fortunately, this also fails to... }
6... Nxc3 7. Qxb7 Be4 { White loses a piece here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
