[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Jobava London #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This move was picked up by Rapport and Jobova a few years back, and it has been quite popular since then. White's main idea is oftentimes to quickly develop the queenside pieces and go for the long castle. }
3... c5 4. Nb5
{ Premature attack. White wants to highlight the fact that the c7 square is undefended, but luckily Black has a move that punishes this move. }
4... Qa5+ { Giving a check which forces White to retreat its knight. } 5. Nc3
cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 { Developing with a tempo. } 7. Qa4 Qxa4 8. Nxa4 e5
{ White's position is very difficult due to the powerful center that Black possesses. Also, the knight on a4 is misplaced. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Jobava London #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This move was picked up by Rapport and Jobova a few years back, and it has been quite popular since then. White's main idea is oftentimes to quickly develop the queenside pieces and go for the long castle. }
3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. Nb5
{ At first sight, this move might look dangerous, but if Black knows what to do, then it does not work out well for White. The solution to this is very straightforward. }
5... Qa5+ 6. c3
{ 6.b4  Qxb4+  7.c3  dxc3  8.Nc7+  is a transposition to the mainline, which we will examine thoroughly in the main course. }
6... dxc3 7. Nc7+ Kd8 8. b4 { 8.Nxa8?  cxb2+  is easily winning for Black. }
8... Qxb4 9. Nxa8 c2+ 10. Qd2 e5 { Bringing the f8-Bishop into the game. } 11.
Bxe5 Nc6 12. Bxf6+ gxf6
{ Despite being a rook down, Black is totally winning with the threats of ...Bf5-Qb1-Bb4. White's knight on a8 is essentially trapped, so losing the rook wasn't for nothing. }
