[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In the recent World Championship match, Magnus Carlsen employed this system against Ian Nepomniachtchi in the crucial game 6, which he won.   White wants to develop with Bg2 and O-O and then usually go for c4. But first, Black has to choose from several options. }
3... Bf5
{ I recommend this move, because this is a pretty straightforward setup with Black, and I believe the easiest way to equalize. Black simply wants to develop with moves like - e6, c6, h6, Nbd7, Be7, and O-O. }
4. c4 e6 5. Qb3
{ This move was played by Mamedyarov in an online rapid game against Nakamura. So online players, watch out, because you may face this😀.   However, the next moves show that Black is better after executing the appropriate moves. }
5... Nc6
{ A very common idea. Oftentimes Black's best response is to defend the b7-pawn is to play Nc6 which threatens Nb4-Nc2. }
6. a3 { Preventing Nb4, but weakening the b3-square. } 6... Be7
{ Simply developing, since White has no real threat now. } 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Bd2
{ After  8.O-O?  Na5  , Black wins a pawn. } 8... dxc4
{ A very common way to deal with the center. Black wants to play Be4 and thus put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
9. Qxc4 Be4 { Black is threatening ...Nxd4. } 10. e3 e5
{ Black uses the momentum and highlights the pinned Knight on f3.  White cannot take on e5 for tactical reasons  11.dxe5  Nxe5  , and otherwise Black is threatening to play exd4 to destroy the White pawn structure in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In the recent World Championship match, Magnus Carlsen employed this system against Ian Nepomniachtchi in the crucial game 6, which he won.   White wants to develop with Bg2 and O-O and then usually go for c4. But first, Black has to choose from several options. }
3... Bf5
{ I recommend this move, because this is a pretty straightforward setup with Black, and I believe the easiest way to equalize. Black simply wants to develop with moves like - e6, c6, h6, Nbd7, Be7, and O-O. }
4. c4 e6 5. Nc3
{ This move order is the core idea of 4.c4 and why it is better than 4.Bg2.   Now if Black would just simply play the usual setup move c6, then White has an extra opportunity with Nh4. I believe that that would lead to a slightly worse position for black. Therefore }
5... h6
{ Important to remember to start with h6, to make space for the Bishop on h7 if White plays Nh4. }
6. Bg2
{ Now that White can never exchange the f3-Knight for the f5-Bishop, Black can continue the usual development. }
6... c6 7. Qb3
{ This is a slightly tricky move order. Playing Qb3 before castling gives White some extra opportunities compared to the main lines  7.O-O  which we will examinehere.  Black has to respond with accurate moves here to equalize. }
7... Qb6 8. c5 Qxb3 9. axb3 Na6
{ This move is the right response here! Black could not play its solid setup conveniently with Nbd7-a6-Rc8 @@StartBracket@@as in the main line@@EndBracket@@, because after  9...Nbd7  10.b4  a6  11.b5  gives White an advantage. The Knight is heading towards b4. }
10. Ne5 { White is threatening to take on c6 here. } 10... Nb4
{ Continuing with Nb4-a5, which will give the Black Knight a nice outpost. }
11. Ra4 a5
{ This endgame is equal with chances for both sides. Next is Nd7 to exchange the strong e5-Knight. Note that Black oftentimes has an idea with Bc2 to bother the b3-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 { White chooses a solid setup this time. } 3... e6 4.
Bd3
{ This setup is mainly employed in blitz/rapid games because this is very easy for White to play. White's main plan is to go O-O, b3, Bb2, Nbd2, and eventually Ne5 or c4.   I believe my recommendation is the easiest way to achieve equality with Black. Black basically just has to copy what White does.   Note that  4.c4  dxc4  would transpose to the main lines. }
4... Be7
{ Black places the Bishop on e7, because later on when White plays Ne5, Black will be able to exchange that attacking Knight, which would give White the comfort to attack. }
5. O-O
{ The following moves are quite logical and useful for both sides -- It is hard to imagine another logical alternative for any side.   Note that after  5.Nbd2  Black just copies White with  5...Nbd7  and eventually we will transpose to the main lines. }
5... O-O 6. b3 b6 { Black simply copies White, next up Bb7, Nbd7, and c5. } 7.
Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ Now, we have reached the position where White has to create some play, otherwise, the position would become very drawish. Black would like to play c5 if White does not do anything concrete now. }
9. Ne5
{ The most typical attacking move for White in this opening. White wants to play f4, Qf3 and start attacking the Kingside. Luckily, Black has a rather comfortable solution. }
9... Nxe5
{ Remember, that it's important that the Bishop now stands on e7. Otherwise Black could not take on e5. }
10. dxe5 Ne4
{ Black employs the same idea as White did with playing Ne5. The only difference here is that White cannot really exchange that knight on e4 since dxe4 would come with a tempo.   Also, it is very important to stand in the way of the d3-Bishop, so it's no longer eying the Black King. }
11. f4 g6
{ Stopping f5, and pretty much the attack on the Kingside. Black has several plans here depending on White's moves: c5, a5-a4, and at the right moment f5 is also in the air. }
*

