[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Torre Attack #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Torre Attack. It is often time employed even by super grandmasters. White's main idea is to threaten with Bxf6 in certain moments and to simply develop with Nbd2-e3-c3. }
3... Ne4
{ Black takes immediate action. Now White has to decide where to put the Bishop since giving the dark-squared Bishop away would be inappropriate. }
4. Bh4
{ It is not the main move, since the bishop on h4 is a little bit misplaced. Black now has the opportunity to take advantage of that misplaced bishop. }
4... Qd6
{ At first sight, it may seem odd, but it is an extremely interesting and clever move. Its main idea is to play Qh6 and then g5-g4. }
5. c4
{ White is trying to point out that it's bad to develop the queen early on by opening up the position. However, Black has a very nice way to refute that.   After  5.c3?!  Qh6⩱  Black has achieved what it wanted, to put the Queen on h6. Now, White has serious problems to face as Black wants to play g5, and then after Bg3, Nxg3 would damage the White pawn structure. }
5... Qb6 6. Qc1 e5
{ Opening up the way for the bishop with a tempo. Now, Black points out why the bishop on h4 is misplaced. }
7. dxe5 { There was nothing better that White could do. } 7... Bb4+ 8. Nbd2 Qh6
{ The knight on f3 will be overworked. } *

