[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The London System #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This is called the London system. I call it the good version of the London system since it is better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  when  2...c5  would be a better version for Black. In that case oftentimes Black can develop the Knight to e7, as the example variations show as well.  This move order is I believe well-known to be the best for White, at least amongst the London experts. White wants to develop the same way as after 2.Bf4 with e3, Nbd2, c3, Bd3, and O-O. Luckily, the text moves still promise Black a rather safe way to equalize. }
3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Bb5+
{ This move leads to a very tricky variation. Black has to know exactly what the moves are, otherwise White could easily get an advantage. You may face this move in an online game since this line is easy and fast for White to play. However, I believe the text moves can promise Black an equal game. }
6... Nc6 7. Bxc6+
{ White is giving up the Bishop in hope of long-term positional play. The main idea is to make Black's pawn structure unusual and to create a post for the Knight on c5 later on. }
7... bxc6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The only problem that Black has is the doubled pawns. If White were to let Black get rid of them, then Black would be happier than ever. }
9. Qa4
{ The key point of 6. Bb5. White is now threatening to go Qa3 pinning the pawn and will try to develop with Nbd2-Nb3. Black has to solve this issue. }
9... O-O { It is inevitable for Black to make sure that the king is safe. } 10.
O-O
{ This is not in the spirit of the position. If White lingers and does not act fast, then Black can equalize with the mentioned plan. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 c5
{ Black finally gets rid of the double c-pawn, which solves all the issues. }
12. Rc1 cxd4 13. Qxd4 Bd7 { Connecting the rooks. } 14. Nbd2 Rfb8
{ Black has a pretty straightforward plan here as shown: a5-a4, ...Qb6 putting pressure on the b2-pawn. }
*

