[Black "The London System #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This is called the London system. I call it the good version of the London system since it is better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  when  2...c5  would be a better version for Black. In that case oftentimes Black can develop the Knight to e7, as the example variations show as well.  This move order is I believe well-known to be the best for White, at least amongst the London experts. White wants to develop the same way as after 2.Bf4 with e3, Nbd2, c3, Bd3, and O-O. Luckily, the text moves still promise Black a rather safe way to equalize. }
3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Bb5+
{ This move leads to a very tricky variation. Black has to know exactly what the moves are, otherwise White could easily get an advantage. You may face this move in an online game since this line is easy and fast for White to play. However, I believe the text moves can promise Black an equal game. }
6... Nc6 7. Bxc6+
{ White is giving up the Bishop in hope of long-term positional play. The main idea is to make Black's pawn structure unusual and to create a post for the Knight on c5 later on. }
7... bxc6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The only problem that Black has is the doubled pawns. If White were to let Black get rid of them, then Black would be happier than ever. }
9. Qa4
{ The key point of 6. Bb5. White is now threatening to go Qa3 pinning the pawn and will try to develop with Nbd2-Nb3. Black has to solve this issue. }
9... O-O { It is inevitable for Black to make sure that the king is safe. } 10.
Qa3
{ This pin is the core idea of the opening. White has a simple target, which is the c5-pawn or square. Black has to solve this problem. }
10... Ne4
{ A very logical move that protects both the queen and the pawn. Now, White's only good plan is to exchange the Black piece that holds the Black center together. }
11. Nbd2
{ There is a big difference between the moves Nbd2 and Nfd2 and the main reason is that the White knight on f3 has no real asset in this position - whereas the knight on b1 gives extra protection to the queen on a3, plus potentially it could develop to c3 and then Na4 would target the very important c5-square. }
11... cxd4
{ Now Black has a nice opportunity to solve their doubled pawn issue and go for a comfortable endgame. }
12. Qxd6 Nxd6 13. cxd4 Rb8
{ A very important move, which puts pressure on the b2-pawn immediately. Now White has to choose between b3 or Nb3. Generally speaking, White would like to play Nb3-Nc5, but it does not work out well. }
14. b3
{ After this move, White cannot really employ the plan with Nb3-Nc5 or Na5 ever again in the game. }
14... Ba6
{ Cutting the king from castling, so the h1-rook will have difficulties coming into play. }
15. Rc1 Rfc8
{ Now that all Black pieces are in play and developed. Black can slowly start preparing the move ...c5, for example with ...Nb7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London System 5.c3 Sidelines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3
{ This is the most played move, and for a good reason. White would like to keep the bishops on the board since oftentimes they serve in White's attack by either supporting the White knight to play Ne5 or sometimes playing Bh4 which could cause an unpleasant pin for Black. }
6... O-O { As usual, Black makes the king safe. } 7. Nbd2
{ A good developing move and the right place for the knight. } 7... Qc7
{ The main purpose of this move is to enable Black develop the knight to d7. Also, later on, Nbd7-e5 will be a possibility. }
8. Ne5
{ This is a very typical move in the London system. White wants a setup with f4-Bd3-O-O to have a strong center and attack against the Black king. }
8... Nbd7
{ Generally speaking, the knight stands better on d7 in these structures, because later when Black develops its c8 bishop to b7, the knight will not stand in its way on c6. It also supports the c5-pawn and key dark squares. }
9. f4
{ White follows its clear plan with Bd3 and O-O. Black has to come up with the right plan. }
9... b5
{ A novelty. I think this is a creative way to make White's position unusual. Black wants to get counterplay on the queenside, and it is coming fast. White does not have too much time to set up its pieces, because the Black pawns are rolling on the queenside. }
10. Bd3
{ White disregards the pawn sacrifice and simply wants to continue with the normal plan of O-O. }
10... b4 { Black keeps rolling the pawns to weaken the white queenside. } 11.
O-O bxc3 12. bxc3 a5
{ Preparing ...Ba6 to exchange the powerful bishop on d3. } 13. Qe2 Qa7
{ Black will play ...Ba6 to exchange White's powerful light-squared bishop. The counterplay is clear on the queenside. I think Black has a rather comfortable middlegame here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London System 5.c3 Sidelines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. c3 Bd6 6. Nbd2
{ A normal developing move that gives Black the chance to take on f4, and thus gives White doubled pawns, but I suggest waiting for one more move with that. I believe that making the Black king safe is the priority. }
6... O-O
{ Now that the Black king is totally safe, Black only needs to finish development. }
7. Bd3
{ The most human move in the position. Every London system player would put the bishop on d3. Now the best way for Black to equalize is to act fast. }
7... Bxf4
{ Damaging White's pawn structure. However, the following pawn structure could be dangerous for Black, since after exf4, White will have a pretty nice outpost for the knight on e5. Therefore, Black's best option is to act quickly in the center. }
8. exf4 Qb6
{ A nice developing move with a tempo. Now, the b2-pawn is under pressure and so is the center. }
9. Rb1 cxd4
{ Eliminating all the dxc5 ideas for White. Now the very natural move would be cxd4 for White, however, the d4-pawn would be very weak. }
10. Nxd4
{ 10.cxd4?  Nc6∓  White has too many weaknesses here. The d4-pawn is under attack, and Black is also threatening to play ...Nb4 to attack the d3-bishop and the a2-pawn at the same time. }
10... Qc7
{ The queen was no longer useful on b6. Now the f4-pawn is under attack, and Black also has a great plan in mind in the center. }
11. g3 e5
{ I believe this is the clearest way to equalize with Black. Since White has not yet fully finished developing, it is a great time to sharpen the position a little bit. }
12. fxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Qe2 Qc7
{ It is important to keep the queens on the board when Black has an isolated pawn. I believe that Black has a very good version compared to a typical slightly worse isolated-pawn position. The d3-bishop is a little bit odd, since it would stand much better on g2. Black will now finish developing with ...Re8-Nc6-Bg4, or Bh3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London System 5.Nbd2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2
{ I believe that this move leaves White with more options than  5.c3  , which kind of fixes the pawn structure. Here, White will often play for c4 to unbalance the center. }
5... Qb6
{ Black grabs the opportunity and puts pressure on the b2-pawn immediately. White cannot play the typical response with Qb3, which gives White a problem to solve. }
6. Rb1
{ White had to defend the pawn on b2. Advancing the pawn to b3 would create weaknesses on the dark squares, like b4 and c3. }
6... Bd7
{ It may look a little bit odd, but I believe that this is the best way for Black to play. This move oftentimes gives Black the opportunity to play ...Bb5, which would exchange the good attacking light-square bishop. }
7. c4 { Since White is not developed enough, this move is too early. } 7...
cxd4 { Opening the way for the f8-bishop to land on b4 later on. } 8. exd4 dxc4
{ Leaving White with an isolated pawn. } 9. Nxc4 Bb4+
{ It's always nice to develop with a tempo. } 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qa6 12.
Qb4
{ It does not work out for White, since Black has a very good counter-attacking move. }
12... Nc6 13. Nd6+
{ It seems that White's attack is dangerous, but luckily, Black has enough good pieces to defend the position. }
13... Ke7 14. Qc5 Qa5+
{ Black is right on time to exchange queens, and go for a better endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 Nc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. g3
{ This is a tricky opening move. White kind of wants to trick Black here. If Black were to play  4...e6  , which is a typical move in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, then after  5.Bg2  , the opening would transpose to the Catalan, and that is not what Black wants. }
4... Nc6
{ Since White is not planning to capture the c4-pawn back any time soon, Black grabs the momentum. The main idea of this move is to play ...e5 next. }
5. Bg2 { This is the most played move, but not the best! } 5... e5
{ Since Black is a pawn up in the position, 'sacrificing' one pawn back is not really an issue. Furthermore, White cannot grab the e5-pawn here, since it would run into ...Ng4 ideas after exchanging pieces. }
6. Qa4
{ A typical Catalan move to pin the c6-knight, but it does not work out well for White. The following moves are quite forced for both sides.   6.Nxe5  Nxe5  7.dxe5  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Ng4∓  This is a double-attack that forces White to give up the e5-pawn, hence Black is much better. }
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Qxd4 8. Bxc6+ Nd7 { The best way to get an advantage. } 9.
Bg2 c6
{ Black is much better thanks to the material advantage. Next is to finish development with moves like ...Nb6,...Be6,...Be7, and ...O-O. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 3.c4 dxc4 4.Na3 e5"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. Na3
{ It is definitely a surprising way to win back the c4-pawn. You will most likely encounter this in rapid/blitz games, since if Black knows how to handle this move, then Black is better. }
4... e5
{ A very important move. Black immediately highlights the strangely placed knight on a3. }
5. Nxe5
{ The best option for White.  5.Nxc4?  looks logical but surprisingly, Black is much better here  5...e4!  6.Nfe5  b5∓  The knights cannot coordinate well, therefore eventually White will lose material. }
5... Bxa3 { The cleanest way to get an advantage. } 6. bxa3 b5
{ Usually, in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, the c4-pawn is a weakness, however here it is an asset. }
7. e3 a6
{ Black has a very stable position and is better. The plan is the following: ...Bb7, ...O-O, and ...Nbd7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4.Qa4+ Nc6 5.Qxc4 e5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. Qa4+
{ This is a serious sideline that Black has to know how to handle. There are a couple of ways to handle this, for example,  4...c6  which would transpose to the Slav defense @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Qc2  dxc4  5.Qxc4  @@EndBracket@@, but Black does not want to transpose to the Slav, therefore I believe that the best way to equalize is to play ...Nc6. }
4... Nc6
{ As you can see, sometimes Nc6 is the way to handle the sidelines like after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nc6  . The knight sometimes pressures the d4-pawn and it also gives Black the opportunity to play ...e5 in certain positions. }
5. Qxc4 e5
{ This idea was introduced by Dominguez Perez a few months ago and will be discussed more thoroughly in the main course. }
6. dxe5 Be6
{ An incredibly important in-between move, before Black moves the knight from f6. }
7. Qh4
{ This move is less likely to happen than  7.Qa4  since it does not pin the c6-knight, Black will be able to go for the e5-pawn. }
7... Nd7 8. Bg5 { The only way not to be worse. } 8... Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10.
Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ Black has no problem in this endgame. The position is equal if White plays some accurate moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "3.e4 b5 4.a4 c6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ This move is supposed to be the sharpest and most challenging move against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. I believe that some Grandmasters stopped playing the QGA because of  3.e4  . However, there is a fairly new line that I'm recommending here in this course, which I believe gives equality for Black. }
3... b5 4. a4
{ 4.Nc3  is a rare move that transposes into the mainlines. And after  4...c6  , White must now play a4, otherwise Black will keep the extra pawn on c4. }
4... c6
{ Black has to keep the strong pawn structure as long as White lets us. Now, White has three moves that I consider playable which are covered in the main course - 5.axb5, the mainline, 5. Nc3 , and 5. b3. }
5. Nc3 { Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. } 5... b4
{ I think this is the best move for Black. This position will go into an interesting middlegame which is worth studying with both colors. Now White has several alternatives with the knight. }
6. Nce2
{ I believe that this is the trickiest line of all the knight moves, but not the best. White wants to transfer the knight to g3, so it potentially could create an attack on the kingside later in the middlegame. }
6... e6
{ An important move which immediately threatens to break the White center with ...c5. }
7. Ng3 Ba6
{ Black has to defend the c4-pawn first, and then break the center with ...c5. }
8. Be3 { This move would not prevent the move c5. } 8... c5 9. dxc5 Nd7
{ Black will capture the White c-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 6.Nb1 Ba6 7.Qc2 e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. Nc3 b4 6. Nb1
{ I believe that this move gives White the best chance to fight for the advantage. If we compare the moves  6.Na2  and  6.Nb1  , I mentioned that one of the main ideas of Na2 is that later White can transfer the knight to b3 via c1, whereas Nb1 could come even faster to b3 via d2, when White does not even need to move the c1-bishop. However, the b4-pawn is not under attack like it would be after  6.Na2  , so now Black can defend the c4-pawn. }
6... Ba6 { Protecting the pawn, and developing at the same time. } 7. Qc2
{ This is the most played move, and I believe it gives the best chance for White to create an interesting game. It looks like White is giving up a free pawn on d4, but I think it would be not wise to take it. }
7... e5
{ Black uses the fact that White has not yet developed the knight to f3. As in other certain lines, this e5 breakthrough in the center is a common idea. }
8. dxe5
{ Not the best move. This leads to a position where Black dictates the moves. }
8... Qa5
{ The best possible developing move with the queen. It not only threatens to capture the e5-pawn, but also the b3 move is in the air. }
9. Bd2
{ 9.f4?  White would be foolish to protect the e5-pawn here.  9...b3+!  10.Qd2  Bb4!  Very important to keep the queens on the board!  11.Nc3  Nd7-+  The position is winning for Black because of the attack that will come after Rd8. }
9... Nd7
{ It is better to develop than grab the e5-pawn. After  9...Qxe5  White would have gotten a great deal of compensation after  10.Nf3  . Black now wants to capture on e5 with the knight. }
10. Nf3 Nxe5 { It's time to capture the pawn. } 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Be3
{ This is the best move for White. The idea is to prepare Bxc4, so Black does not have ...Qc5. }
12... b3 { Forces White to go for an endgame. } 13. Qc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3
{ White now wants to play Nd2 and win a pawn back with Bxc4.After  14.Nxc3  , White will not be able to win the c4-pawn back as after  14...Bb4∓  , Black's material advantage rules here. Next is ...Nf6. }
14... f5 { Sacrificing the pawn back to open the position. } 15. exf5 Nf6
{ Now the Black knight will have a square on d5 where it will put pressure on the c3-pawn. }
16. Nd2 { White is continuing with the plan of targeting the Black pawns. }
16... Nd5 17. Bd4 Be7
{ An important move! Black prepares to short castle, so then ...Rxf5 will be possible. }
18. Bxg7 { It would be too greedy for White to take another pawn. } 18... Rg8
19. Bd4 Rg4
{ Threatening to sacrifice the rook on d4, and then use the queenside passed pawns. Black has a great deal of compensation for the pawn. }
*

