[Black " 6.Nb1 Ba6 7.Qc2 e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. Nc3 b4 6. Nb1
{ I believe that this move gives White the best chance to fight for the advantage. If we compare the moves  6.Na2  and  6.Nb1  , I mentioned that one of the main ideas of Na2 is that later White can transfer the knight to b3 via c1, whereas Nb1 could come even faster to b3 via d2, when White does not even need to move the c1-bishop. However, the b4-pawn is not under attack like it would be after  6.Na2  , so now Black can defend the c4-pawn. }
6... Ba6 { Protecting the pawn, and developing at the same time. } 7. Qc2
{ This is the most played move, and I believe it gives the best chance for White to create an interesting game. It looks like White is giving up a free pawn on d4, but I think it would be not wise to take it. }
7... e5
{ Black uses the fact that White has not yet developed the knight to f3. As in other certain lines, this e5 breakthrough in the center is a common idea. }
8. Nf3
{ A great developing move that attacks the e5-pawn. It seems that Black could be two pawns up temporarily after  8....exd4  , but it would lead to a terribly unpleasant position after  9.Bxc4  since the light squares would be too weak for Black. Therefore I suggest playing for forcing lines with Black here. }
8... b3
{ The main idea is to chase the queen away from c2 so it will no longer defend the e4-pawn. Black will be able to develop the knight to f6 with a tempo.   8...exd4?!  Do not go for this, because this leads to a very uncomfortable position.  9.Bxc4  Bxc4  10.Qxc4  White has very easy plans with O-O, Nbd2-Nb3, and attacking the Black pawns on d4-b4-c6. }
9. Qc3 exd4
{ Now Black takes since White cannot capture the c4-pawn as in the line after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/p4ppp/b1p5/4p3/PppPP3/5N2/1PQ2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...exd4  . }
10. Nxd4
{ Keeping the queens on the board definitely makes White's compensation more dangerous for Black. }
10... Nf6
{ As I mentioned earlier, the move 8...b3 supports the Nf6 developing move as it comes with a tempo. Now White has two logical ways to protect the e4-pawn, f3, and Nd2. Let's take a look at both. }
11. f3
{ This makes White's pawn structure very stable, but since White has kept the queens on the board, this f3 move could also weaken the White king. }
11... Nbd7
{ Black is developing the knight so it can join the action in the center. It also gives space to develop the queenside pieces. Now White has several options, but surprisingly, none of the pawn grabbing is good. }
12. Be3
{ I think that out of the three moves  @@StartBracket@@  12.Nd2  ,  12.Be3  ,  12.Bf4  @@EndBracket@@ this move is the most logical. White simply wants to execute the plan as after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/p4ppp/b1p5/8/P1ppP3/1pQ2N2/1P3PPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Qxd4  Qxd4  11.Nxd4  Nf6  12.f3  Nfd7  13.Be3  , so just Nd2 Rc1 and target the c3-pawn. }
12... Ne5
{ Black defends the pawn on c4 and also on c6. Also, it enables Black to play ...Nfd7 with the plan of ...Nc5-Nd3. }
13. Nd2
{ Black can now employ the plan that should be known to us by now with developing the f8 bishop to b4. }
13... Qb8 14. Qa5 Bc8 15. Bf4 Nfd7
{ Black is better since ...Bb4 is unstoppable. } 16. Bxe5 Nxe5 17. f4 Bd6 18.
fxe5 Bb4
{ White must give back the piece now after  19.Nxc6  Bxa5  20.Nxb8  Rxb8  . } *

