[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5.axb5 cxb5 6.b3 e5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. b3
{ This is the only move that makes sense for White to play other than  6.Nc3  , which is the mainline. Here, White wants to win the pawn back on c4. Luckily, Black has a great response to this. }
6... e5
{ If you looked at other sidelines that I have covered in this course, then the e5 breakthrough should not come as a surprise. Black makes use of the material advantage at the moment, as this move is not really a sacrifice when you are a pawn up anyway. It is a great idea to unbalance the center. }
7. Nf3
{ The knight seems to keep the center together, but it does not help White to get anything good out of this. }
7... exd4
{ Simply exchanging the pawns. White now needs to decide whether they want to go to an endgame or play more ambitiously. }
8. bxc4 b4
{ The same idea as in the line of  8.Qxd4  . Black creates connected pawns. }
9. Nxd4
{ It would even be worse for White to keep the queens on the boards.  9.Qxd4  Nc6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p4ppp/8/1p6/2ppP3/1P3N2/5PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qxd4  . }
9... Bc5 10. Be3 Nf6
{ The last two moves came with tempi, which also contributes to the fact that Black is better. Connected pawns and better development grant Black a better position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.Nc3 Qb6 7.Be2 e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. Be2
{ This move has been recently played by a very strong super GM, Jan-Krzysztof Duda. Its idea is that when Black plays ...e6, then the White knight can be developed to h3, which will lead to a very creative position. }
7... e6 { Black stops White from playing Nd5 for the rest of the game. } 8. Nh3
{ This move may seem odd at first, as it is quite unusual to develop the knight to h3, but it is a very creative move. The h3-knight can oftentimes go to f4 which will help White to play d5 with more strength. }
8... Bb4 9. O-O Ne7
{ It is better to develop the knight to e7 than to f6, because in the case of ...Nf6, White often has the move e5 which could be very strong. }
10. Be3 { White logically develops the dark-squared bishop and threatens d5. }
10... Qb7
{ Now the queen takes the bishop's role. This move not only steps out of the d5-tempo but also eyes the long diagonal. }
11. Bf3
{ White places its other bishop to face the Black queen too. Now Black has an idea which makes the position more straightforward. }
11... e5
{ A very nice move that blocks the f3-bishop and also highlights the strangely placed knight on h3. }
12. dxe5 Bxh3 13. gxh3 Nbc6
{ The position is roughly equal, but I prefer Black's position with the following moves like ...Bxc3, ...O-O, and ...Nxe5. }
