1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3
{ We have arrived at the main move Nc3. This line is one of the main reasons that people are afraid to play the Queen's Gambit Accepted, especially the move 3...b5. This line is supposed to give White an advantage. However, not anymore! I believe that the next moves that I'm recommending here for Black solve the problems in this line. }
6... Qb6
{ A very fresh move! If you check the database, you will see that there are only a handful of games that have been played after this move. It is not surprising, since this queen move looks a little bit suspicious. It seems to run into Nd5 with a tempo. On the other hand, Black simply defends the b5-pawn and tries to claim material advantage. There are four logical moves here that White can play  @@StartBracket@@  7.Nd5  ,  7.Be3  ,  7.Be2  ,  7.b3  @@EndBracket@@, and I will cover them all in the main course. }
7. Nd5
{ A logical move which tries to highlight the strangely placed queen on b6. }
7... Qb7 8. Bf4
{ At first sight this looks very powerful for White, as Nc7 seems to be unstoppable. However, here comes a very strong, typical idea for Black. }
8... e5
{ Sacrificing a pawn to get a tempo in exchange. It also opens up the way for the f8-bishop. }
9. Bxe5
{ White is still threatening to play Nc7, but here comes Black's idea. } 9...
Nd7
{ Developing and attacking the e5-bishop. It also prevents White from playing Nc7. It is a very sharp position, so it is very easy to make mistakes with both sides. Therefore, it is very important to memorize all the moves here. }
10. Nc7+ { The punishment for White's greediness is severe. } 10... Kd8 11.
Nxa8 Bb4+ 12. Ke2 Qxe4# { What a nice mate! } *

