[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.O-O a6 7.Nc3 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3
{ This move also leads to one of the mainlines in the QGA. Other than developing a piece, White wants to eventually use its c3-knight to help the e4/d5 breakthrough in the center. }
7... b5
{ As often, Black wins a tempo like this, to help develop their pieces on the queenside. }
8. Be2
{ I believe this is the best place for the bishop. I think this position requires some explanation. If you study the QGA middlegame positions carefully, you will notice that White frequently takes on c5 and exchanges the queens to have a safe, slightly more comfortable endgame. }
8... Nbd7
{ A very important move, as here White does not have the opportunity to exchange the queens with dxc5. }
9. d5
{ This is the critical move of the whole line. White unbalances the central pawns and tries to open the position, as it favors White because of the development advantage. }
9... exd5
{ Black has to take, otherwise White would damage the Black pawn structure with dxe6. }
10. Nxd5 Bb7 { Placing the bishop on the long diagonal with a tempo. } 11.
Nxf6+ { White has to take and start opening the position more. } 11... Qxf6
{ It is important not to trade queens with  11...Nxf6  because after  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.a4  Black would be underdeveloped, and therefore White would have the advantage. }
12. a4
{ This is the spirit of the position. White has to go and weaken the Black queenside. }
12... b4
{ The only way to a balanced middlegame. Black has to keep the queenside closed here. Unfortunately, Black is not able to hold their nice pawn structure on the queenside for concrete reasons.  12...Qc6  defending the b5-pawn would not work out well because of the development disadvantage.  13.axb5  axb5  14.Rxa8+  Bxa8  15.Qd3±  Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. The position is too open, and therefore Black is worse. }
13. Qc2
{ A solid approach. This move has two ideas, one is that it prepares the move e4 and the second is that b3-Bb2 is going to be a serious possibility from now on. There was a game between Gledura, B - Bacrot, E, European Team 2021, where I successfully won the game. Super GM Wesley, So introduced me to this move, as he won a very nice game in 2018. }
13... Bd6
{ This is a very logical developing move. The Black bishops are now eyeing the White king, which is ideal. }
14. Rd1
{ Initially, when I prepared this line with the White side, this Rd1 move was my idea. Now White puts pressure on the d6-bishop and the d7-knight. }
14... Qe7
{ Black has to retreat its queen, so its pieces are defended against the Qd2/Qd3 threats. ...Qe7 also steps out of the b2-Bb2 tempo. }
15. Nd2
{ Transferring the knight to c4 may look logical, but it's slightly slow and gives Black time to conveniently finish development. Also, note that the white king can become vulnerable. }
15... O-O 16. Nc4 Bc7
{ The two bishops are excellently placed and they put pressure on the white king. }
17. b3 Ne5
{ Exchanging the well-placed knight on c4 benefits Black a great deal. Black is better because of the follow-up attack on the White kingside. Next is ...Qg5 or ...Qh4. }
