17. Bc4
{ A nice place for the bishop. We can see that both of the White bishops are pretty well placed, as they are eying the Black kingside. However the bishop leaves the White kingside, therefore it can become vulnerable. }
17... Rad8
{ Black logically develops their rook to the d-file. Sooner or later, the black pieces would create an attack against the White king. Therefore, White has to solve their kingside issues. }
18. Qf5
{ An interesting move, which protects the f3-knight and also threatens Bxf6. }
18... Ne4
{ Black had to move the knight so White cannot damage their kingside with Bxf6. Now the f5-queen is slightly misplaced, and Black can make use of that. }
19. Be5
{ The only move which saves the f5-queen from trouble, otherwise, the move g6 would come with more force. }
19... g6 { Opening the back rank for the king, and chasing the queen away. }
20. Qf4 Rfe8 { Putting pressure on the e5-bishop. } 21. Bxd6 Rxd6
