{  } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ We have arrived at the endgame line. White's intention is to play a solid, long game and try to claim that the upcoming endgame is better for them. This line has been quite popular amongst super GMs, therefore a lot of people started to go for this endgame. However, I believe that if Black makes a couple of accurate moves, the endgame should be equal. }
7... Bxc5
{ I recommend this move over  7...Qxd1  because I believe that bringing the White rook to d1 is not ideal. I would rather have White trade queens, because in an endgame the fact that Black will not be able to castle is not very important, since the king on e7 will be perfectly safe. }
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Now White has a couple of possibilities. The only thing that is certain for White is to move the c4-bishop, as Black threatens to play ...b5-Bb7, which would significantly help Black's position. Generally speaking, Black wants to place their pieces like this - ...Ke7-Nbd7-b5/b6 and Bb7. White has to create an unbalanced game, otherwise, the position would be too drawish. }
9. Be2
{ A logical move that steps out of the b7-b5 tempo. If Black would want to develop with  9...b5  , @@StartBracket@@10...Bb7@@EndBracket@@ then  10.a4  would weaken the Black queenside. }
9... Ke7
{ Black has to first put their king on e7, so White can no longer play Rd1 with a tempo, and then start developing their queenside pieces. }
10. Rd1 { This is a logical move, as it takes over the open d-file. } 10... Rd8
{ I believe that fighting for the d-file is the best way for Black to play. }
11. Nbd2
{ This is the best way for White to keep the rooks on the board. The knight often goes on b3 to bother the c5-bishop. }
11... Nc6
{ The knight finds a better square on c6 here than on d7, because now the d8-rook has an open file. }
12. Ne1
{ A fairly typical idea in this opening. In these endgames, the moves Ne1/Ne5 all serve the same purpose, which is to transfer the f3-knight to the queenside, and put pressure on the c5-bishop. }
12... e5
{ Black's best option is to play active moves here since the White pieces are slightly passive. }
13. Nd3 Bg4
{ Black again plays an active move that mainly targets the d3-knight. } 14.
Bxg4 Rxd3 15. Be2
{ White has to chase the rook away and get out of the Nxg4 threat. } 15... Rd7
16. Nb3
{ A natural move that eases the pressure on the d-file and wins a tempo on the c5-bishop. }
16... Rxd1+ 17. Bxd1 Rd8 { A very important tempo for Black. } 18. Be2 Bd6
{ Despite the fact that White has the bishop pair, the position is too simplified, and therefore Black equalizes. Black also has a slight space advantage, which makes White's development harder. }
