1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This move was picked up by Rapport and Jobova a few years back and it has been quite popular since then. White's main idea oftentimes is to quickly develop the queenside pieces and go for the long castle. }
3... c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 a6
{ In this pawn structure, Black will always benefit from the move a6, since now Nb5 is no longer an option. }
6. Nf3 Nc6
{ Now White has to take the moment and play aggressively. If White would just simply try to finish the development with moves like Be2 and O-O, then Black would have a quite easy position with Bf5-e6-Bd6, and eventually, the white Knight on c3 will be misplaced. }
7. Be2 Bf5 8. O-O e6
{ Black has no issues in this position. The plan is to simply develop the bishop to d6 @@StartBracket@@possibly exchanging the dark-squared bishops@@EndBracket@@, and then play short castle.   Eventually, White will have difficulties with the knight on c3, as it seems to find no good square. Note, that Black can always think about advancing the pawns on the queenside with a move like b5. }
