[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 The Veresov Attack"]
[Black "3.Bg5 h6 4.Bxf6 exf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Veresov Attack. This move is popular, especially in online games. However, I believe the text move gives Black a relatively easy solution. }
3... h6
{ This move may look surprising at first since it could seem that White plays Bg5 so they can take on f6 and with that damage Black's pawn structure. However, that is not the case here.  If we look at the Trompowksy opening @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  , then White's best plan is to go c4 at some point. Hence, if we compare that opening with this one then we can see that the white Knight will be misplaced on c3 since it's blocking the c-pawn. }
4. Bxf6 exf6 5. e3
{ After  5.e4  dxe4  6.Nxe4  f5  Black is better thanks to the bishop-pair. Next is Bd6 and O-O. }
5... c6 6. Bd3 g6
{ Black has a very comfortable position and can choose between several plans as shown. The most important is to place the pawn on f5 and push the pawns to h5-h4, so White will always have to watch out on the kingside. }
*

