[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bg5 The Veresov Attack"]
[Black "3.Bg5 h6 4.Bh4 c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Veresov Attack. This move is popular, especially in online games. However, I believe the text move gives Black a relatively easy solution. }
3... h6
{ This move may look surprising at first since it could seem that White plays Bg5 so they can take on f6 and with that damage Black's pawn structure. However, that is not the case here.  If we look at the Trompowksy opening @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  , then White's best plan is to go c4 at some point. Hence, if we compare that opening with this one then we can see that the white Knight will be misplaced on c3 since it's blocking the c-pawn. }
4. Bh4 c5 5. Bxf6
{ Interestingly, this is a better version for White than 4. Bxf6, because now ...exf6 would not be as effective since Black already played c5. Therefore, the d5-pawn can no longer be defended by a pawn, making it a target for the rest of the game.   Note that after  5.dxc5?  Black is better after  5...d4∓  . }
5... gxf6 6. e4
{ This is the way for White to play, otherwise the c3 knight would be misplaced. }
6... dxe4
{ Generally speaking, it is good to open up the position for the side that has the bishop pair. }
7. dxc5
{ After  7.d5?  f5∓  Black is simply a pawn up, with ...Qb6 or ...Bg7 next. }
7... f5
{ Simply defending the pawn on e4, plus later on Black also has the possibility to play ...Bg7 and rule the long diagonal. }
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. O-O-O+
{ White won a tempo by long castling with a check. However, White had to exchange the Queens in order to get that tempo, which resulted in a long-term slightly worse endgame. }
9... Bd7
{ Black simply wants to play e6 to stabilize the position, and possibly target the c5-pawn, therefore White has to act immediately. }
10. g4
{ The best way to spice things up in the position. White is trying to use their development advantage. }
10... fxg4
{ Grabbing the pawn. White now has to play accurately in order to avoid big troubles. }
11. Nxe4
{ It would not be good to capture the pawn, because of concrete reasons. }
11... Kc7
{ White has captured the e4-pawn, so the long diagonal is open. Bc6 comes next and then after Bg2, f5 would win material, therefore White has serious issues to solve. }
*

