[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Torre Attack. It is often time employed even by super grandmasters. White's main idea is to threaten with Bxf6 in certain moments and to simply develop with Nbd2-e3-c3. }
3... Ne4
{ Black takes immediate action. Now White has to decide where to put the Bishop since giving the dark-squared Bishop away would be inappropriate. }
4. Bh4
{ This is not the main move, since the bishop on h4 is a little bit misplaced. Black now has the opportunity to take advantage of that misplaced bishop. }
4... Qd6
{ At first sight, it may seem odd, but it is an extremely interesting and clever move. The main idea is to play ...Qh6 and then g5-g4. }
5. Nbd2
{ A logical developing move. Black now needs to show why Qd6 was a good idea, otherwise White would just simply develop with e3-Bd3. }
5... Qh6
{ Black is putting pressure on the h4-bishop, giving White a problem to solve. }
6. Qc1
{ The only move that would not give Black a big advantage. The idea of this move is to prevent Black from playing g5. }
6... Nc6
{ Threatening ...Nxd4. As I mentioned in earlier games, developing a piece with a tempo is always a very nice way to play chess. }
7. c3 Qh5
{ Black must keep the queen on the board, thus leaving the h6-c1 diagonal is the right way to play. }
8. h3
{ A very hard move to make. White had no real choices other than developing a plan with h3-g4. }
8... Bd7
{ The best move. Black simply wants to play ...O-O-O and then play on the kingside and in the center. }
9. g4 Qg6 10. Bg2 h5
{ A very good move that forces White to create a weakness. } 11. g5 Bf5
{ Black is better due to their better pieces. As shown, Black's simple plan is to finish the development with ...O-O-O, ...e6, and ...Bd6. }
