[White "4) 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 The Torre Attack"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 Ne4 4.Bh4 Qd6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Torre Attack. It is often time employed even by super grandmasters. White's main idea is to threaten with Bxf6 in certain moments and to simply develop with Nbd2-e3-c3. }
3... Ne4
{ Black takes immediate action. Now White has to decide where to put the Bishop since giving the dark-squared Bishop away would be inappropriate. }
4. Bh4
{ This is not the main move, since the bishop on h4 is a little bit misplaced. Black now has the opportunity to take advantage of that misplaced bishop. }
4... Qd6
{ At first sight, it may seem odd, but it is an extremely interesting and clever move. The main idea is to play ...Qh6 and then g5-g4. }
5. c4
{ White is trying to point out that it's bad to develop the queen early by opening up the position. However, Black has a very nice way to refute that.   After  5.c3?!  Qh6⩱  Black has achieved what they wanted, by placing their queen on h6. Now, White has serious problems to face as Black wants to play g5, and then after Bg3, Nxg3 would damage the White pawn structure. }
5... Qb6 6. Qc2
{ Is a logical move since White now put pressure on the e4 knight in certain variations. }
6... Bf5
{ Black puts pressure on the queen on c2.  Note that  6...e5  would not work as effectively as it did after 6.Qc1, since  7.cxd5  gives White a clear advantage. }
7. cxd5
{ This is a trap. It seems that White blundered, but no! After  7...Ng3?  White plays the stunning  8.e4!  this is the main idea of 6.Qc2. It is easy to miss, especially in an online game  8...Bxe4  9.Qa4+  and White is clearly better in this position. }
7... e6
{ Black start its attack. The following moves are forced for pretty much both sides. }
8. dxe6 fxe6 9. Qb3 Bb4+ 10. Nc3 a5
{ White cannot do anything against a4-a3, which will enhance the pin on the c3-knight. }
