[White "4) 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 The Torre Attack"]
[Black "3.Bg5 Ne4 4.Bf4 c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is called the Torre Attack. It is often time employed even by super grandmasters. White's main idea is to threaten with Bxf6 in certain moments and to simply develop with Nbd2-e3-c3. }
3... Ne4
{ Black takes immediate action. Now White has to decide where to put the Bishop since giving the dark-squared Bishop away would be inappropriate. }
4. Bf4
{ The most commonly played move. White would like to employ their usual developing plan with e3-Nbd2-c3-Bd3. }
4... c5
{ A very common move in this opening. It simply gives Black the comfort to develop more freely with ...Nc6/Qb6. }
5. e3 Qb6
{ A typical way to tickle the b2-pawn. Now White has to respond to this threat. }
6. dxc5
{ This move does not solve the issue that White has faced with the b2 pawn. }
6... Qxb2 7. Be5 Qb4+ 8. Nbd2 Nc6
{ Black will eventually capture the c5-pawn and will be a healthy pawn up. White has no compensation for it. }
