[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In the recent World Championship match, Magnus Carlsen employed this system against Ian Nepomniachtchi in the crucial game 6, which he won. White wants to develop with Bg2 and O-O and then usually go for c4. But first Black has to choose from several options. }
3... Bf5
{ I recommend this move, because this is a pretty straightforward setup with Black, and I believe it is the easiest way to equalize.   Black simply wants to develop with moves like - ...e6, ...c6, ...h6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7, and ...O-O. }
4. c4 e6 5. Qb3
{ This move was played by Mamedyarov in an online rapid game against Nakamura. So online players, watch out, because you may face this😀.   However, the next move shows that Black is better after executing the appropriate plan. }
5... Nc6
{ A very common idea. Oftentimes Black's best response to defend the b7-pawn is to play Nc6 threatening Nb4-Nc2. }
6. a3 { Preventing Nb4, but weakening the b3-square. } 6... Be7
{ Simply developing, since White has no real threat now. } 7. Qxb7 Na5 8. Qb5+
{ After  8.Qa6  c5=  Black has a great deal of compensation for the pawn. }
8... c6 { Closing the a4-e8 diagonal and chasing away the Queen. } 9. Qa4 dxc4
{ Black is better here thanks to their better development. The b3-square is weak as Black is threatening with ...Nb3. If White were to defend the b3-square with  10.Nbd2  then  10...Qd5  would be the right response, as White can not chase the Queen away with Nc3 anymore. }
