1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In the recent World Championship match, Magnus Carlsen employed this system against Ian Nepomniachtchi in the crucial game 6, which he won. White wants to develop with Bg2 and O-O and then usually go for c4. But first Black has to choose from several options. }
3... Bf5
{ I recommend this move, because this is a pretty straightforward setup with Black, and I believe it is the easiest way to equalize.   Black simply wants to develop with moves like - ...e6, ...c6, ...h6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7, and ...O-O. }
4. c4 e6 5. Nc3
{ This move order is the core idea of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p1b2/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.c4  and why it is better than  4.Bg2  .   Now if Black would just simply play the usual setup move  5...c6  , then White has an extra opportunity with  6.Nh4  . I believe that would lead to a slightly worse position for Black, therefore... }
5... h6
{ It is important to start with ...h6, making space for the Bishop on h7 if White plays Nh4. }
6. Qb3 Nc6
{ Black would employ the same idea as in the line @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p1b2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  Nc6  . The threat is ...Nb4 and ...Na5. }
7. a3
{ 7.Qxb7?  would not stop Black from playing  7...Nb4  and now White is having a lot of trouble with the c2-square, and the queen on b7 can also be bothered with Rb8. }
7... Na5 { Double attack. } 8. Qa4+
{ Luckily, White has an opportunity to get away with a check, but it does not grant equality. }
8... c6 9. c5 Be7
{ Black simply completes development and can start to play on the queenside. }
10. Bg2 O-O
{ Black has nothing to worry about here. The light squares on the Queenside are vulnerable and the Queen on a4 is misplaced. Next is ...b5 or ...b6. }
