{ Here in this position there are two typical plans for White.  8.Qb3  and  8.Nd2  , let's look at both. }
8. Nd2
{ Clearly, White wants to play e4 and claim that the space advantage will promise a better game for them. However, Black will enter into a Caro-Kann-like pawn structure where the d4-pawn will be a target, as it commonly is in the Caro-Kann Defense. }
8... Be7 { Simply finishing development. } 9. e4 dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4
{ The exchange of the knights is not by any means mandatory, but I believe the fewer pieces there are on the board, the less complicated the position is. }
11. Nxe4 O-O 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Nc3
{ If White wants to play for a slight advantage then it's a  must to keep the knights on the board. }
13... Qb6
{ The position is roughly equal, and it varies depending on the players who would prefer which side. I believe that Black has to always watch out for the d5-breakthrough in this structure, and in general, try to put pressure on the d4-pawn.   Black's plan is the following: ...Rfd8-Rd7-Rad8. In the case of Be3, usually Black responds with ...Qa6 if ...Ng4 is no longer possible. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3"]
[Black "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 Bf5 4.Bg2 e6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ In the recent World Championship match, Magnus Carlsen employed this system against Ian Nepomniachtchi in the crucial game 6, which he won. White wants to develop with Bg2 and O-O and then usually go for c4. But first Black has to choose from several options. }
3... Bf5
{ I recommend this move, because this is a pretty straightforward setup with Black, and I believe it is the easiest way to equalize.   Black simply wants to develop with moves like - ...e6, ...c6, ...h6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7, and ...O-O. }
4. Bg2
{ The most common move. White will eventually have to play c4, and then we will transpose. }
4... e6
{ The following moves are normal for both sides. There are no other real alternatives. Just simple development of pieces. }
5. O-O h6 6. c4 c6 7. Nc3 Nbd7
{ Here in this position there are two typical plans for White.  8.Qb3  and  8.Nd2  , let's look at both. }
8. Qb3 Qb6
{ A very common idea. Simply stopping the white queen, so the b7-pawn is no longer attacked. The following moves are a typical way to play for both sides. }
9. c5
{ 9.Qxb6?  It's almost always bad for White to exchange Queens on b6, after  9...axb6  Black has a pleasant position thanks to their good pawn structure. }
9... Qxb3
{ The safest choice to equalize with Black.  9...Qa6  is the other move that Black can play but that could lead to complications after  10.Nd2  and e4-ideas. }
10. axb3 a6
{ It is very important that right after exchanging the Queens on b3, Black has to play ...a6 and after b4, Black must get out of the pin with ...Rc8! After  10...Be7?  11.b4  a6  12.b5!  cxb5  13.Nxb5⩲  White would achieve what they wanted. The Knight will go back to c3 and then b4-b5 will cause serious pressure on Black's queenside. }
11. b4 Rc8
{ Now that the Queenside is closed, White has two ideas remaining. A very typical idea is to try to get the f3-Knight all the way to a5, so it can bother the b7-pawn. The second idea is to play in the center, usually with f3-e4. The next moves show how to eliminate both of White's ideas. }
12. Nd2 Bc2
{ This is a very important move! Its purpose is dual-fold. Firstly, it prevents the whole Nb3-Na5 maneuver, and secondly, it doesn't allow f3-e4 to come with tempo. }
13. f3 g5 14. e4 Bg7
{ With a similar position to 13.Re1. The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. Black's plan is to transfer its Knight to e7 and then pressure the d4-pawn. }
*

