1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 { White chooses a solid setup this time. } 3... e6 4.
Bd3
{ This setup is mainly employed in blitz/rapid games because this is very easy for White to play. White's main plan is to go O-O, b3, Bb2, Nbd2, and eventually Ne5 or c4. I believe my recommendation is the easiest way to achieve equality with Black. Black basically just has to copy what White does.   Note that  4.c4  dxc4  would transpose to the mainline. }
4... Be7
{ Black places the Bishop on e7, because later on when White plays Ne5, Black may be forced to capture the attacking Knight, which many times give White some comfort to attack. }
5. O-O
{ The following moves are quite logical and useful for both sides. It is hard to imagine another logical alternative for any side.   Note that after  5.Nbd2  Black just copies White with  5...Nbd7  and eventually we will transpose to the main lines. }
5... O-O 6. b3 b6
{ Black simply copies White, next up ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5. } 7. Bb2 Bb7
8. c4
{ White chooses a setup with c4-Nc3. The most common move is to play  8.Nbd2  with the plan of Ne5-f4 rather than  8.c4  because the position could become drawish very fast. }
8... dxc4
{ Black fixes the pawn structure immediately. If White wants to have a complicated middlegame then there is no other option than taking back with the pawn on c4. }
9. bxc4 c5 { Black wants to weaken the white center with ...cxd4. } 10. Nc3
{ The right square for the Knight, as it oftentimes supports White to play d5 later on in the middlegame. For example, after Qe2 and Rad1, d5 becomes a threat. }
10... cxd4 11. exd4 Nbd7
{ This is the ideal setup for Black. All the pieces are on healthy squares, which gives Black a very stable position. }
12. Re1 Rc8 { Both sides place their rooks on the right semi-opened files. }
13. Qe2 { Threatening d5. } 13... Re8
{ This is where the rook usually belongs, as it stops the d5-breakthrough. }
14. Rad1 Nf8
{ Transfering the knight to g6. The position is equal with chances for both sides. I think these kinds of 'hanging pawns' @@StartBracket@@the d4- and c4-pawns@@EndBracket@@ positions are usually easier to play with Black. Upcoming moves are ...Ng6, ...a6, and ...Qc7. }
