1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 { White chooses a solid setup this time. } 3... e6 4.
Bd3
{ This setup is mainly employed in blitz/rapid games because this is very easy for White to play. White's main plan is to go O-O, b3, Bb2, Nbd2, and eventually Ne5 or c4. I believe my recommendation is the easiest way to achieve equality with Black. Black basically just has to copy what White does.   Note that  4.c4  dxc4  would transpose to the mainline. }
4... Be7
{ Black places the Bishop on e7, because later on when White plays Ne5, Black may be forced to capture the attacking Knight, which many times give White some comfort to attack. }
5. O-O
{ The following moves are quite logical and useful for both sides. It is hard to imagine another logical alternative for any side.   Note that after  5.Nbd2  Black just copies White with  5...Nbd7  and eventually we will transpose to the main lines. }
5... O-O 6. b3 b6
{ Black simply copies White, next up ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5. } 7. Bb2 Bb7
8. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ Now, we have reached the position where White has to create some play, otherwise, the position would become very drawish. Black would like to play ...c5 if White does not do anything concrete now. }
9. Ne5
{ The most typical attacking move for White in this opening. White wants to play f4, Qf3 and start attacking the Kingside. Luckily, Black has a rather comfortable solution. }
9... Nxe5
{ Remember, that it's important that the Bishop now stands on e7. Otherwise Black wouldn't be able to take on e5. }
10. dxe5 Ne4
{ Black employs the same idea as White did with playing Ne5. The only difference here is that White cannot really exchange that Knight on e4 since dxe4 would come with a tempo.   Also, it is very important to stand in the way of the d3-Bishop, so it's no longer eyeing the black king. }
11. f4 g6
{ Stopping f5, and pretty much the attack on the kingside. Black has several plans here depending on White's move: c5, a5-a4, and at the right moment f5 is also in the air. }
