7... bxc6 8. Qa4 { A novelty, which immediately attacks the c6-pawn. } 8... O-O
9. Qxc6
{ Taking the pawn would be too greedy. Black will get too much activity in exchange. Note that  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  would transpose to the variation that we will examinehere. }
9... Bxf4 10. exf4
{ Please keep in mind that  10.Qxa8?  would lose because of  10...Qb6-+  and Black traps the white queen after moving the c8-bishop on the next move. }
10... Ne4
{ Activating the knight and also protecting the c5-pawn. Note that the a8-rook is still not hanging, as after  11.Qxa8?  Qb6  and the white queen would be trapped. }
11. Qxa8
{ After  11.O-O  Rb8  Black is better thanks to its better development. The b2-pawn is hanging, and Bd7 is also a threat to win material. }
11... Qb6 12. Nbd2 Ba6
{ Leaving White no other choice than to give up the Queen. } 13. Qxf8+ Kxf8
{ Black is winning here! The black queen is worth much more than the two rooks, as it can attack the white king. }
*

