{ The key point of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . White is now threatening to go Qa3 pinning the pawn and will try to develop with Nbd2-Nb3. Black has to solve this issue. }
9... O-O { It is inevitable for Black to make sure that the king is safe. } 10.
Qa3
{ This pin is the core idea of the opening. White has a simple target, which is the c5-pawn or square. Black has to solve this problem. }
10... Ne4
{ A very logical move that protects both the queen and the pawn. Now, White's only good plan is to exchange the black piece that holds Black's center together. }
11. Nbd2
{ There is a big difference between this move and  11.Nfd2  , the main reason is that the White knight on f3 has no real asset in this position - whereas the knight on b1 gives extra protection to the queen on a3, plus potentially it could develop to c3 and then Na4 would target the very important c5-square. }
11... cxd4
{ Now Black has a nice opportunity to solve their doubled pawn issue and go for a comfortable endgame. }
12. Qxd6 Nxd6 13. exd4
{ This is not really in the spirit of the position. In this case, White has no open c-file which could give a target on c6 after Rc1. }
13... f6
{ Preventing White from playing Ne5. Black is better with the plan of ...a5-Ba6-Rfb8. }
