1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This is called the London System. I call it the good version of the London System since it is better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  when  2...c5  would be a better version for Black. In that case oftentimes Black can develop the knight to e7, as the example variations show as well.   This move order is, I believe, well-known to be the best for White, at least amongst the London experts. White wants to develop the same way as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  with e3, Nbd2, c3, Bd3, and O-O. Luckily, the text moves still promise Black a rather safe way to equalize. }
3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Bb5+
{ This move leads to a very tricky variation. Black has to know exactly what the moves are, otherwise White could easily get an advantage. You may face this move in an online game since this line is easy and fast for White to play. However, I believe the text moves can promise Black an equal game. }
6... Nc6 7. Bxc6+
{ White is giving up the Bishop in hope of long-term positional play. The main idea is to make Black's pawn structure unusual and to create a post for the Knight on c5 later on. }
7... bxc6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The only problem that Black has is the doubled pawns. If White were to let Black get rid of them, then Black would be happier than ever. }
9. Qa4
{ The key point of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . White is now threatening to go Qa3 pinning the pawn and will try to develop with Nbd2-Nb3. Black has to solve this issue. }
9... O-O { It is inevitable for Black to make sure that the king is safe. } 10.
Qa3
{ This pin is the core idea of the opening. White has a simple target, which is the c5-pawn or square. Black has to solve this problem. }
10... Ne4
{ A very logical move that protects both the queen and the pawn. Now, White's only good plan is to exchange the black piece that holds Black's center together. }
11. Nfd2 e5
{ Once, one of my good friends, Zoltan Almasi who is one of the best chess players in the world taught me that I should always check what squares my opponent no longer controls after each move. Now, we can see that with @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p4ppp/2pqp3/2pp4/3Pn3/Q1P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN2K2R w KQ - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Nfd2  , White no longer has jurisdiction over the e5-square. This move's main idea is that it opens the way for the Black queen to go to g6, which will put pressure on White's kingside. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxc5
{ 13.dxc5?  This would leave the a3-queen excluded.  13...Qg6  The white kingside becomes too weak, and the Black queen becomes too powerful. White has to deal with the g2-pawn now. }
13... Qg6
{ Now we can see that White's disadvantage in development is showing. Black is threatening to take on g2. However, White is pretty much forced to give up the pawn, since they should solve their development first. }
14. Nd2
{ 14.g3  Ba6⩱  Black has a great deal of compensation. Next is ...exd4 and then ...Bd3 will make White's position very unpleasant. }
14... Qxg2 15. O-O-O
{ This is the best option for White. Now the white king is safe and a lot of Black pawns are under attack. }
15... Qxf2
{ Black has to collect one pawn. Now Black is also threatening to take another one on e3. }
16. Qxe5
{ White tries to capture the pawns back in a way that their pawn structure would remain healthy. However, now the e3-pawn is not protected. }
16... Qxe3
{ Black is taking a pawn and waiting for White to show compensation. } 17. Rhg1
Qh6
{ The best square for the queen. It not only protects the g7-pawn, but keeps the d2-knight pinned. }
18. Qxe4 f5
{ Pushing the only passed pawn on the board, and also taking away the e4-square from White. }
19. Qe7 Be6
{ An equal position with chances for both sides. Black has to use the f-pawn as a weapon in the near future. Black's plan is the following: ...Rf7-f4-Bd5. }
*

