[White "7) The London System"]
[Black "6.Bg3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This is called the London System. I call it the good version of the London System since it is better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  when  2...c5  would be a better version for Black. In that case oftentimes Black can develop the knight to e7, as the example variations show as well.   This move order is, I believe, well-known to be the best for White, at least amongst the London experts. White wants to develop the same way as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  with e3, Nbd2, c3, Bd3, and O-O. Luckily, the text moves still promise Black a rather safe way to equalize. }
3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Bg3
{ This is the most played move, and for a good reason. White would like to keep the bishops on the board since oftentimes they serve in White's attack by either supporting the white knight to play Ne5 or sometimes playing Bh4 which could cause an unpleasant pin for Black. }
6... O-O { As usual, Black makes the king safe. } 7. Nbd2
{ A good developing move and the right place for the knight. } 7... Qc7
{ The main purpose of this move is to enable Black develop the b8-knight to d7. Also, later on, ...Nbd7-e5 will be a possibility. }
8. dxc5
{ I believe that this is the critical move. White prevents Black from simply completing development with ...Nbd7-b6-Bb7. }
8... Qxc5 9. Bd3
{ There is no logical move for White other than this. White's main plan is to go e4 here. }
9... Nbd7
{ A logical developing move. If White does not take immediate action, then Black will simply finish development with ...b6-Bb7 and will have no problem in the position. }
10. e4
{ This is in the spirit of the position. Now, Black has to solve this issue. White is simply threatening e5 now. }
10... dxe4
{ I believe that this is the cleanest way to equalize for Black. The following moves are pretty straightforward for both sides. }
11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxg3
{ Even though it does not look ideal for Black to open up the h-file for White, this is the best move for Black. }
13. hxg3
{ It seems White has achieved their goals by opening the file for the h1-rook, however, Black can quite easily solve the issue of the king. }
13... Nf6 { It not only defends the h7-pawn, but also comes with a tempo. } 14.
Qe2
{ A logical move that keeps options open for White with castling short or long. It also gives White the opportunity to play Ne5.   The queen is better placed on e2, because the bishop has a square on c2 later on. After  14.Qc2  h6  , the e4-bishop would be in some trouble. }
14... Rd8
{ It has rarely been played, but I believe this is the best way to equalize. Black now has control over the d-file. It seems that White's attack is not so dangerous after this move. }
15. Ne5
{ If not for White's Ne5, Black would have just simply finished developing with ...h6-Bd7. }
15... Nxe4 { Getting rid of the attacking bishop. } 16. Qxe4 h6
{ Black simply solves the issues on the h-file, and White is too late to play g4-g5 anymore, for several reasons, like Qd5 or Qb5. }
17. O-O Bd7
{ A very important final move that completes Black's development. The b7-pawn is not hanging since the knight on e5 would fall. Next is ...Bc6. }
*

