3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Bg3
{ This is the most played move, and for a good reason. White would like to keep the bishops on the board since oftentimes they serve in White's attack by either supporting the white knight to play Ne5 or sometimes playing Bh4 which could cause an unpleasant pin for Black. }
6... O-O { As usual, Black makes the king safe. } 7. Nbd2
{ A good developing move and the right place for the knight. } 7... Qc7
{ The main purpose of this move is to enable Black develop the b8-knight to d7. Also, later on, ...Nbd7-e5 will be a possibility. }
8. Ne5
{ This is a very typical move in the London System. White wants a setup with f4-Bd3-O-O to have a strong center and attack against the Black king.   8.Bd3  A logical move, but not the most critical, since it lets Black finish developing without any problems.  8...Nbd7  The right square for the knight. It supports the e5 breakthrough, and later, when Black develops with ...b6-Bb7, then the knight will not stand in the way of the bishop. Also, White no longer has the opportunity to play Ne5-f4.  9.O-O  b6=  Black is completely fine here. There is no weakness in Black's position. The plan is to simply finish development with ...Bb7 and then the e5-breakthrough will always be a possibility. }
8... Nbd7
{ Generally speaking, the knight stands better on d7 in these structures, because later, when Black develops the c8-bishop to b7, the knight will not stand in its way on c6. It also supports the c5-pawn and key dark squares. }
9. f4
{ White follows a clear plan with Bd3 and O-O. Black has to come up with the right plan. }
9... b5
{ A novelty. I think this is a creative way to make White's position unusual. Black wants to get counterplay on the queenside, and it is coming fast. White does not have too much time to set up its pieces, because the Black pawns are rolling on the queenside. }
10. Bd3
{ White disregards the pawn sacrifice and simply wants to continue with the normal plan of O-O. }
10... b4 { Black keeps rolling the pawns to weaken White's queenside. } 11. O-O
bxc3 12. bxc3 a5 { Preparing ...Ba6 to exchange the powerful bishop on d3. }
13. Qe2 Qa7
{ Black will play ...Ba6 to exchange White's powerful light-squared bishop. The counterplay is clear on the queenside. I think Black has a rather comfortable middlegame here.  After  14.f5  Black can play  14...Qc7  to target the now weaker e5-knight. Once we remove the knight from e5, Black will have a much easier position }
