3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. c3 Bd6
{ Black is trying to keep it simple. Now White has to create some play, otherwise Black will finish development with ...O-O and then equalize the game with ...Qc7, ...Nbd7, and ...e5. }
6. Nbd2
{ A normal developing move that gives Black the chance to take on f4, and thus gives White doubled pawns, but I suggest waiting for one more move with that. I believe that making the black king safe is the priority. }
6... O-O
{ Now that the black king is totally safe, Black only needs to finish development. }
7. dxc5
{ An interesting possibility, but Black has a relatively easy way to equalize. }
