1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ This is called the London System. I call it the good version of the London System since it is better than @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  when  2...c5  would be a better version for Black. In that case oftentimes Black can develop the knight to e7, as the example variations show as well.   This move order is, I believe, well-known to be the best for White, at least amongst the London experts. White wants to develop the same way as after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  with e3, Nbd2, c3, Bd3, and O-O. Luckily, the text moves still promise Black a rather safe way to equalize. }
3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. Nbd2
{ I believe that this move leaves White with more options than  5.c3  , which kind of fixes the pawn structure. Here, White will often play for c4 to unbalance the center. }
5... Qb6
{ Black grabs the opportunity and puts pressure on the b2-pawn immediately. White cannot play the typical response with Qb3, which gives White a problem to solve. }
6. Rb1
{ White had to defend the pawn on b2. Advancing the pawn to b3 would create weaknesses on the dark squares, like b4 and c3. }
6... Bd7
{ It may look a little bit odd, but I believe that this is the best way for Black to play. This move oftentimes gives Black the opportunity to play ...Bb5, which would exchange the good attacking light-squared bishop. }
7. c4 { Since White is not developed enough, this move is too early. } 7...
cxd4 { Opening the way for the f8-bishop to land on b4 later on. } 8. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Black has no problem here whatsoever. Black just has to finish developing with ...Bb4 and ...O-O. }
