3... c5 4. e3 e6
{ This setup for Black is one of the most common, and for good reasons. It is quite easy to understand how Black should play in these structures. }
5. Nbd2
{ I believe that this move leaves White with more options than  5.c3  , which kind of fixes the pawn structure. Here, White will often play for c4 to unbalance the center. }
5... Qb6
{ Black grabs the opportunity and puts pressure on the b2-pawn immediately. White cannot play the typical response with Qb3, which gives White a problem to solve. }
6. Rb1
{ White had to defend the pawn on b2. Advancing the pawn to b3 would create weaknesses on the dark squares, like b4 and c3. }
6... Bd7
{ It may look a little bit odd, but I believe that this is the best way for Black to play. This move oftentimes gives Black the opportunity to play ...Bb5, which would exchange the good attacking light-squared bishop. }
7. c3
{ I believe it is worth mentioning this move. It is the typical pawn structure to have for White. However, I believe that combining the two moves Rb1 and c3 is a little odd. Black now has a great opportunity to show the essence of the ...Bd7 move. }
7... cxd4 { Black fixes the pawn structure first, and then plays ...Bb5. } 8.
exd4 Bb5
{ Here we go! Black is offering the exchange of the bishops. This trade is very good for Black since the c8-bishop often has trouble developing, while the f1-bishop is oftentimes the core piece in White's attack on the kingside. }
9. h4
{ This move may seem a little bit odd, but it could be a fairly typical move in the London System. White wants to play h5-Rh3-Rg3 and Ne5, which could look scary from Black's perspective. Therefore, the following moves are for stabilizing Black's position against White's future attack. White has to play actively, otherwise Black is completely fine. }
9... Nbd7 { A logical developing move. } 10. h5
{ White is gaining space on the kingside. } 10... h6
{ It is usually a good idea to fix the White pawn on h5, so sometimes it can be a target later on. }
11. Rh3
{ White is bringing up the rook so it can put pressure on the g7-pawn via g3. }
11... Be7
{ Despite the scary-looking rook move that White just made, Black will have a quite solid kingside after finishing development. }
12. Ne5 { White can not play  12.Rg3  since  12...Nxh5  wins a pawn. } 12...
O-O
{ Luckily, Black has enough defensive pieces on the kingside, so the king will not be in real trouble. }
13. Rg3 Kh8
{ Getting out of the rook's way. I believe that this position should not be frightening for Black, since the king on h8 is safe. Black's plan is the following: ...Bxf1, ...Qa6, ...Rac8. What Black should look out for in this position is the h6-pawn, because oftentimes Bxh6 could lead to a very dangerous attack for White. Thus, ...Ng8 defending the h6-pawn could be a smart move to hold the position together. }
