7. c3
{ I believe it is worth mentioning this move. It is the typical pawn structure to have for White. However, I believe that combining the two moves Rb1 and c3 is a little odd. Black now has a great opportunity to show the essence of the ...Bd7 move. }
7... cxd4 { Black fixes the pawn structure first, and then plays ...Bb5. } 8.
exd4 Bb5
{ Here we go! Black is offering the exchange of the bishops. This trade is very good for Black since the c8-bishop often has trouble developing, while the f1-bishop is oftentimes the core piece in White's attack on the kingside. }
9. h4
{ This move may seem a little bit odd, but it could be a fairly typical move in the London System. White wants to play h5-Rh3-Rg3 and Ne5, which could look scary from Black's perspective. Therefore, the following moves are for stabilizing Black's position against White's future attack. White has to play actively, otherwise Black is completely fine. }
9... Nbd7 { A logical developing move. } 10. h5
{ White is gaining space on the kingside. } 10... h6
{ It is usually a good idea to fix the White pawn on h5, so sometimes it can be a target later on. }
11. Ne5
{ White is preparing the attack either with Rh3-Rg3 or perhaps Qf3-Qg3. } 11...
Be7
{ Simply developing the bishop and planning to castle short.  White has to stop that. }
12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Qg4
{ The best way to attack the black kingside. The g7-pawn is under attack, and therefore Black cannot go for the short castle. }
13... Bxf1 14. Nxf1 { 14.Qxg7??  loses to  14...Bf6! } 14... Bf8
{ This move looks a little bit strange as Black just played ...Be7 and now retreats to f8. The point is that the bishop on f8 stops the whole White attack, and ...Nf6 will come with a tempo. }
15. Nd2
{ White puts the knight on d2, so after Black plays ...Nf6, the e4-square will be under control. }
15... Nf6 16. Qg3 Qa6 { The best square for the queen on the board. } 17. a3
Rc8
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I think that White is in a little bit of trouble making plans here. The black queen on a6 is very powerful as it cuts the white king from castling, and it also eyes the d3 and a2-squares. Black's plan is to sit and wait for White to do something. The white knight cannot move from d2, just like the queen on g3 as it puts pressure on the g7-pawn. The only 'attacking' move that White could make is Be5, but Black could simply easily disregard it with a waiting move like ...Qb5. }
