[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 & Na3"]
[Black " 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. g3
{ This is a tricky opening move. White kind of wants to trick Black here. If Black were to play  4...e6  , which is a typical move in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, then after  5.Bg2  , the opening would transpose to the Catalan, and that is not what Black wants. }
4... Nc6
{ Since White is not planning to capture the c4-pawn back any time soon, Black grabs the momentum. The main idea of this move is to play ...e5 next. }
5. Bg2 { This is the most played move, but not the best! } 5... e5
{ Since Black is a pawn up in the position, 'sacrificing' one pawn back is not really an issue. Furthermore, White cannot grab the e5-pawn here, since it would run into ...Ng4 ideas after exchanging pieces. }
6. Qa4
{ A typical Catalan move to pin the c6-knight, but it does not work out well for White. The following moves are quite forced for both sides.   6.Nxe5  Nxe5  7.dxe5  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  Ng4∓  This is a double-attack, that forces White to give up the e5-pawn, hence Black is much better. }
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Qxd4 8. Bxc6+ Nd7 { The best way to get an advantage. } 9.
Bg2 c6
{ Black is much better thanks to the material advantage. Next is to finish development with moves like ...Nb6,...Be6,...Be7,...O-O. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 & Na3"]
[Black " 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 Nc6  #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. g3
{ This is a tricky opening move. White kind of wants to trick Black here. If Black were to play  4...e6  , which is a typical move in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, then after  5.Bg2  , the opening would transpose to the Catalan, and that is not what Black wants. }
4... Nc6
{ Since White is not planning to capture the c4-pawn back any time soon, Black grabs the momentum. The main idea of this move is to play ...e5 next. }
5. Nc3
{ This is the critical move, and it has been played by Hans Niemann a few months ago. The idea behind this move is that after Black plays e5, White will have the option to take on e5 in some form since the d1 queen is protected by the knight as well. }
5... e5
{ Black goes e5 nonetheless. It complicates the position, but I believe that Black has no problems in the following lines. }
6. Nxe5
{ The best option for White. The following lines are forced for both sides.   6.d5?!  Nb4  7.e4  Bg4∓  White will have difficulties protecting the c2 and d3 squares.   6.dxe5  is a worse option for White.  6...Qxd1+  7.Nxd1  Nb4⩱  White has serious problems with holding the position together. Eventually, White will have to give up material, thus Black is better. }
6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1
{ This is the core idea of the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/8/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  .   8.Kxd1  would fail to  8...Ng4  . }
8... Ne4 9. a3
{ White prevents the move ...Bb4, but this move makes a new target for Black. }
9... Nc5
{ The b3-square was weakened by the move 9. a3, therefore Black is better. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 & Na3"]
[Black " 3.c4 dxc4 4.g3 Nc6  #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. g3
{ This is a tricky opening move. White kind of wants to trick Black here. If Black were to play  4...e6  , which is a typical move in the Queen's Gambit Accepted, then after  5.Bg2  , the opening would transpose to the Catalan, and that is not what Black wants. }
4... Nc6
{ Since White is not planning to capture the c4-pawn back any time soon, Black grabs the momentum. The main idea of this move is to play ...e5 next. }
5. Nc3
{ This is the critical move, and it has been played by Hans Niemann a few months ago. The idea behind this move is that after Black plays e5, White will have the option to take on e5 in some form since the d1 queen is protected by the knight as well. }
5... e5
{ Black goes e5 nonetheless. It complicates the position, but I believe that Black has no problems in the following lines. }
6. Nxe5
{ The best option for White. The following lines are forced for both sides.   6.d5?!  Nb4  7.e4  Bg4∓  White will have difficulties protecting the c2 and d3 squares.   6.dxe5  is a worse option for White.  6...Qxd1+  7.Nxd1  Nb4⩱  White has serious problems with holding the position together. Eventually, White will have to give up material, thus Black is better. }
6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1
{ This is the core idea of the move @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp1pppp/2n2n2/8/2pP4/5NP1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nc3  .   8.Kxd1  would fail to  8...Ng4  . }
8... Ne4 9. Bg2 { White has to tickle the strong e4-knight. } 9... Bb4+
{ A very important developing move that blocks the white king from castling. }
10. Kf1 Nd2+
{ It certainly looks unusual to place the knight on d2, but it is the best move. It not only gives a check, but makes the c1-bishop's development harder. }
11. Kg1
{ Giving up the bishop pair with  11.Bxd2  is not really a good idea, since it would lead to an unpleasant endgame in the long term. }
11... O-O { Black castles, so the rook can come into play with ...Rd8. } 12.
Nc3 { White immediately attacks the knight on d2. } 12... Rd8
{ Black simply defends the knight on d2, and so it seems that White has difficulties with development. }
13. Nd5 { The only way to not be worse. } 13... Bh3
{ A very important tactical move, which sets up a trap! If not for this move, Black would have problems. }
14. Bxd2
{ This exchange will lead to a position that is pretty drawish, as opposite-colored bishop endgames usually are.  14.Nxb4??  This would fail to a beautiful tactic.  14...Nf3+!  15.exf3  Rd1+  16.Bf1  Rxf1#  . }
14... Bxd2 15. Nxc7 { Grabbing the pawn but losing some tempi. } 15... Rac8 16.
Nb5
{ I believe that keeping the bishop pair on the board only benefits Black. }
16... Be6 { Now Black has a long-term compensation with the bishop pair. } 17.
Nd6 Rc7
{ The position is roughly equal, but I prefer Black. The plan is to chase the d6-knight away with ...Bb4 or ...f6, and play on the queenside. }
*

