[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. Qa4+
{ This is a serious sideline that Black has to know how to handle. There are a couple of ways to handle this, for example,  4...c6  which would transpose to the Slav defense @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Qc2  dxc4  5.Qxc4  @@EndBracket@@, but Black does not want to transpose to the Slav, therefore I believe that the best way to equalize is to play ...Nc6. }
4... Nc6
{ As you can see, sometimes ...Nc6 is the way to handle the sidelines like after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nc6  . The knight sometimes pressures the d4-pawn and it also gives Black the opportunity to play ...e5 in certain positions. }
5. e3
{ This is a logical move to make with White, since it could seem like the knight on c6 is misplaced, which might be true, but so is the queen on a4. Black now highlights why Qa4 is not the right place for the queen. }
5... Nd7
{ It is as simple as it looks, Black wants to play ...Nb6 to win a tempo or two. }
6. Bxc4
{ 6.Qxc4  e5!  Black would have no problem here. Next ...Bd6, ...O-O would promise a comfortable position. }
6... Nb6 { Getting the bishop pair. } 7. Qc2 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 Be6
{ Black wins as much time as possible. The white queen has moved too much, which is why Black can equalize comfortably. }
9. Qa4 Bd5 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e6
{ It is a fairly unclear position, but I believe that after ...Be7, ...O-O, Black is fine. White will probably play O-O-O, which will give Black the chance to play ...Rb8, ...b5, or ...a6, ...b5 attacking the king. }
