1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. Qa4+
{ This is a serious sideline that Black has to know how to handle. There are a couple of ways to handle this, for example,  4...c6  which would transpose to the Slav defense @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Qc2  dxc4  5.Qxc4  @@EndBracket@@, but Black does not want to transpose to the Slav, therefore I believe that the best way to equalize is to play ...Nc6. }
4... Nc6
{ As you can see, sometimes ...Nc6 is the way to handle the sidelines like after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/8/2pP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  Nc6  . The knight sometimes pressures the d4-pawn and it also gives Black the opportunity to play ...e5 in certain positions. }
5. Qxc4 e5
{ This idea was introduced by Dominguez Perez a few months ago. I believe that this idea comes from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Qc2  dxc4  5.Qxc4  Bg4  6.Nc3  Nbd7  7.e4  e5  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.dxe5  Be6  , which equalizes for Black 5...e5 is a very concrete idea, and people are required to know the moves afterwards. }
6. dxe5 Be6
{ An incredibly important in-between move, before Black moves the knight from f6. }
7. Qa4 Nd7
{ We can see that despite being a pawn down, Black's position is attractive with a lead in development and potentially targets the weakened e5-pawn. }
8. Bd2
{ The only move that makes the position equal. It prevents Black from playing ...Bb4 or ...Nb4. }
8... Nc5 { Winning a tempo and preparing to go for long castling. } 9. Qd1 Qd7
{ I believe that White has to be very careful here not to be much worse. Black has simple moves ahead. }
10. g3 { The only way to finish developing and put the king to safety. } 10...
O-O-O 11. Bg2 Bd5 { Threatening ...Nxe5. } 12. O-O Bxf3
{ Giving up the bishop but getting a good attack in exchange. } 13. exf3
{ 13.Bxf3?  Would be bad for specific reasons.  13...Nxe5  If White moves the bishop, then ...Nc4 would win the game. }
13... h5
{ A very important move, which is not easy to find. Black gives up the chance to ever capture back the e5-pawn, but gets a very good attack against the white king. }
14. f4 h4
{ Black has full compensation for the pawn. Black's attack may not look dangerous at first since the g2-bishop seems to protect the white king, but Black has very concrete plans in mind with ...Nd4, ...hxg3, ...Qf5, ...Nd3, and ...Qh7. }
