{ Black does not need to throw in ...Be6 now, as it was required in the other line , since the knight has been removed from c6. }
8. Bf4
{ The most logical way to defend the pawn, just like Rapport did.   8.f4?  A logical way to protect the e5-pawn forever, but it makes White's position too vulnerable.  8...c6∓  Black has more than enough compensation. The plan is to play ...Qb6, ...Bc5, ...Be6, ...O-O-O and start attacking White's king. Luckily, White cannot chase the g4 knight away with h3, since Black has Qh4. }
8... c6
{ Again a very important move, that opens the door for the queen on d8 to play either ...Qa5 or ...Qb6. It also prevents all kinds of queen checks like Qb5 or Qa4. }
9. e3
{ 9.h3?  fails to an immediate resource -  9...Qb6!  10.hxg4  Qxb2-+  Black is winning, since there is no way to defend the a1-rook or trap the queen on a1. }
9... g5
