[Black "4.Nc3 a6 5.e3 b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. Nc3
{ White would like to occupy the center with e4. Black has a couple of possibilities here like  4...c6  which would transpose to The Slav @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  @@EndBracket@@ or  4...e6  which would transpose to the Vienna @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  @@EndBracket@@  . I would not recommend doing any of these, because they would require you to know completely different openings. I believe the text move gives a fairly simple solution. }
4... a6
{ The idea of this move could not be more simple. Black wants to protect the c4-pawn with ...b5. }
5. e3
{ I believe that this move is more serious than  5.a4  , since it does not let Black protect the pawn on c4 with Nc6-Na5.   Black could kind of transpose to the mainlines with  5...e6  6.Bxc4  c5  , however, I believe that  5...b5  promises a comfortable position. }
5... b5 6. a4
{ White has to take immediate actions on the queenside, otherwise Black would simply be a pawn up. }
6... b4
{ 6...c6  would have failed to a tactical resource with  7.axb5  cxb5  8.Nxb5  axb5  9.Rxa8  , therefore 6...b4 is a must. }
7. Nb1 Bb7 { A healthy square for the bishop. } 8. Bxc4 e6 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Black is completing development. I believe that this position is very easy to play for Black. Next is ...Bd6, ...c5, and ...O-O. }
10. b3 Bd6 { Black has much better bishops than White. } 11. Nbd2 c5
{ I think that Black has absolutely no problem in this position. All the pieces are healthily placed, and Black will soon finish development. Next is ...O-O, ...Rc8, ...Qc7, ...Qb8. }
