[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 3.e4 Sidelines"]
[Black "3.e4 b5 4.a4 c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ This move is supposed to be the sharpest and most challenging move against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. I believe that some Grandmasters stopped playing the QGA because of  3.e4  . However, there is a fairly new line that I'm recommending here in this course, which I believe gives equality for Black. The three main moves here for Black are  3...e5  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...b5  which is our mainline. I have analysed all the mentioned moves for quite a long time, and I believe that the only road to equality is  3...b5  . }
3... b5 4. a4
{ 4.Nc3  is a rare move that transposes into the mainlines. And after  4...c6  , White must now play a4, otherwise Black will keep the extra pawn on c4. }
4... c6
{ Black has to keep the strong pawn structure as long as White lets us. Now, White has three moves that I consider playable.  5.axb5  which is the mainline,  5.Nc3  , and  5.b3  . I will cover all the moves, but I believe that the critical move is  5.axb5  . }
5. Nc3 { Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. } 5... b4
{ I think this is the best move for Black. This position will go into an interesting middlegame which is worth studying with both colors. Now White has several alternatives with the knight. }
6. Na2
{ This is the most played move in the position, but I think it does not cause any serious problems for Black to solve. It is quite clear that White now threatens to take the b4-pawn, but more importantly White will take on c4 with the bishop and then later transfer the knight to b3 via c1. On b3, the knight would have a very nice outpost and it would control the two very important c5 and a5 squares. Black has to prevent that from happening. }
6... Nf6
{ Highlighting the fact that the c3-knight is not protecting the e4-pawn anymore. }
7. f3
{ It would not work out well for White, because it takes away squares from White to develop its pieces. }
7... b3 8. Nc3 Ba6
{ Black is much better, since there seems to be no way to win the material back for White. }
*

