1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ This move is supposed to be the sharpest and most challenging move against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. I believe that some Grandmasters stopped playing the QGA because of  3.e4  . However, there is a fairly new line that I'm recommending here in this course, which I believe gives equality for Black. The three main moves here for Black are  3...e5  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...b5  which is our mainline. I have analysed all the mentioned moves for quite a long time, and I believe that the only road to equality is  3...b5  . }
3... b5 4. a4
{ 4.Nc3  is a rare move that transposes into the mainlines. And after  4...c6  , White must now play a4, otherwise Black will keep the extra pawn on c4. }
4... c6
{ Black has to keep the strong pawn structure as long as White lets us. Now, White has three moves that I consider playable.  5.axb5  which is the mainline,  5.Nc3  , and  5.b3  . I will cover all the moves, but I believe that the critical move is  5.axb5  . }
5. Nc3 { Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. } 5... b4
{ I think this is the best move for Black. This position will go into an interesting middlegame which is worth studying with both colors. Now White has several alternatives with the knight. }
6. Na2
{ This is the most played move in the position, but I think it does not cause any serious problems for Black to solve. It is quite clear that White now threatens to take the b4-pawn, but more importantly White will take on c4 with the bishop and then later transfer the knight to b3 via c1. On b3, the knight would have a very nice outpost and it would control the two very important c5 and a5 squares. Black has to prevent that from happening. }
6... Nf6
{ Highlighting the fact that the c3-knight is not protecting the e4-pawn anymore. }
7. e5
{ White's best chance to create an unbalanced position is to push the e- pawn, but it does give a very important square away. }
7... Nd5 { Now Black has a nice outpost on d5 for the rest of the game. } 8.
Bxc4 e6
{ Black has to develop quickly and prevent the issues that would come after White transfers the knight to b3. }
9. Nf3 Be7
{ Simply developing the bishop, which prevents White from playing Ng5.   10.Bd2  a5  11.O-O  Nd7  Would transpose to the mainlines - @@StartFEN@@ rnbqk2r/p3bppp/2p1p3/3nP3/PpBP4/5N2/NP3PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Nd7  11.Bd2  a5  . }
10. O-O
{ The white king is all safe now, thus White is ready to start transferring the knight to b3 with Bd2-Nc1-Nb3. Black has to respond to this plan. }
10... Nd7
{ Black is in no hurry to castle. It is more important to develop all the pieces and execute the right plans on the queenside before the white knight gets to b3. Next is ...a5, ...N5b6, ...c5 which White cannot really prevent. }
11. Bd2
{ White makes the logical move which not only threatens Nc1-Nb3 but also after Bxd5 the b4-pawn would hang. }
11... a5 { Fixing the pawns. } 12. Nc1 N5b6
{ A very nice retreat for the knight, which comes with a tempo. Black wants to breakthrough in the center with c5, thus ...N5b6 allows Black to use the d7-knight to capture the c5-pawn back. It also opens up the long diagonal for the b7-bishop later on. }
13. Be2 c5 { Just before White could play Nb3-Rc1. } 14. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The position is roughly equal, but I prefer Black. I believe that Black has a lot of ideas in this position, but I would just keep making simple moves like ...O-O, ...Bb7-Rc8-Qc7-Rfd8-Qb8. A final note is that the pawn on a4 could become weak, so Black can target that pawn in certain positions. }
