[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 3.e4 b5 5.Nc3 b4 6.Nb1"]
[Black "6.Nb1 Ba6 7.Nf3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4
{ This move is supposed to be the sharpest and most challenging move against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. I believe that some Grandmasters stopped playing the QGA because of  3.e4  . However, there is a fairly new line that I'm recommending here in this course, which I believe gives equality for Black. The three main moves here with Black are  3...e5  ,  3...Nf6  , and  3...b5  which is our mainline. I have analysed all the mentioned moves for quite a long time, and I believe that the only road to equality is  3...b5  . }
3... b5 4. a4
{ 4.Nc3  is a rare move that transposes into the mainlines. And after  4...c6  , White must now play a4, otherwise Black will keep the extra pawn on c4. }
4... c6
{ Black has to keep the strong pawn structure as long as White lets us. Now, White has three moves that I consider playable.  5.axb5  which is the mainline,  5.Nc3  , and  5.b3  . I will cover all the moves, but I believe that the critical move is  5.axb5  . }
5. Nc3 { Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. } 5... b4
{ I think this is the best move for Black. This position will go into an interesting middlegame which is worth studying with both colors. Now White has several alternatives with the knight. }
6. Nb1
{ I believe that this move gives White the best chance to fight for the advantage. If we compare the moves  6.Na2  and  6.Nb1  , I mentioned that one of the main ideas of Na2 is that later White can transfer the knight to b3 via c1, whereas Nb1 could come even faster to b3 via d2, when White does not even need to move the c1-bishop. However, the b4-pawn is not under attack like it would be after  6.Na2  , so now Black can defend the c4-pawn. }
6... Ba6 { Protecting the pawn, and developing at the same time. } 7. Nf3
{ I think this is not the best move in the position, but it makes sense. White simply develops and prevents Black from employing a breakthrough in the center with e5 in certain positions.   7.Be3?!  former World Champion, Anand employed this move once, but I think it is not the right way to go for White.  7...Nf6!  Putting pressure on the e4-pawn.  8.f3  e6  Black simply develops and claims that the material advantage matters here.  9.Nd2  c3!  Opening the position works out well for Black here.  10.bxc3  bxc3  11.Nb3  Bb4⩱  Black has the better development and the material advantage. Next comes castling and playing for the c5-breakthrough. }
7... Nf6
{ Black again uses the fact that the e4-pawn is not under protection. White is now pretty much forced to push the e-pawn which gives the d5-square to Black. }
8. e5 Nd5
{ Now Black has kept the material advantage and taken the d5-square, therefore White has to try to create some sort of counterplay. }
9. e6
{ The best chance to make the position complicated and unbalanced. It is also quite a typical idea to try to weaken the black king. }
9... f6
{ A very important move that prevents White from playing Ne5, which would cause a great deal of problems for Black.  9...fxe6  would have damaged the pawn structure for Black, plus after  10.Ne5  White would have had a great compensation for the material. }
10. Nh4
{ A tricky move that threatens Qh5, but Black can easily defend against this. }
10... Qd6 { This leads to a forced line where Black will come out on top. } 11.
Qh5+ g6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Qxh8 Qxe6+
{ There are too many Black pieces attacking the white king. } *

