{ I believe that this move gives White the best chance to fight for the advantage. If we compare the moves  6.Na2  and  6.Nb1  , I mentioned that one of the main ideas of Na2 is that later White can transfer the knight to b3 via c1, whereas Nb1 could come even faster to b3 via d2, when White does not even need to move the c1-bishop. However, the b4-pawn is not under attack like it would be after  6.Na2  , so now Black can defend the c4-pawn. }
6... Ba6 { Protecting the pawn, and developing at the same time. } 7. Qc2
{ This is the most played move, and I believe it gives the best chance for White to create an interesting game. It looks like White is giving up a free pawn on d4, but I think it would be not wise to take it. }
7... e5
{ Black uses the fact that White has not yet developed the knight to f3. As in other certain lines, this e5-breakthrough in the center is a common idea.   7...Qxd4?!  8.Nf3!  Qb6  9.Be3!  Qc7  10.Nbd2  White has gotten two tempi and will capture the c4-pawn. I believe that the middlegame is going to be very unpleasant to play for Black. Despite the fact that the engine says that the position is roughly equal, it is hard to play from a human perspective. }
8. Nf3
{ A great developing move that attacks the e5-pawn. It seems that Black could be two pawns up temporarily after  8....exd4  , but it would lead to a terribly unpleasant position after  9.Bxc4  since the light squares would be too weak for Black. Therefore I suggest playing for forcing lines with Black here. }
8... b3
{ The main idea is to chase the queen away from c2 so it will no longer defend the e4-pawn. Black will be able to develop the knight to f6 with a tempo.   8...exd4?!  Do not go for this, because this leads to a very uncomfortable position.  9.Bxc4  Bxc4  10.Qxc4  White has very easy plans with O-O, Nbd2-Nb3, and attacking the Black pawns on d4-b4-c6. }
9. Qc3 { 9.Qd2  exd4  10.Qxd4  Transposes to the line explored here. } 9...
exd4
{ Now Black takes since White cannot capture the c4-pawn as in the line after @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/p4ppp/b1p5/4p3/PppPP3/5N2/1PQ2PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...exd4  . }
10. Nxd4
{ Keeping the queens on the board definitely makes White's compensation more dangerous for Black. }
10... Nf6
{ As I mentioned earlier, the move 8...b3 supports the Nf6 developing move as it comes with a tempo. Now White has two logical ways to protect the e4-pawn, f3, and Nd2. Let's take a look at both. }
11. Nd2
{ The most challenging move. White immediately gets to the point, as its plan is to take the c4-pawn, and then the b3-pawn as well. Black has to react to this accurately. }
11... Bc5
{ Making use of the fact that White cannot play Be3 to protect the knight anymore. }
12. N4xb3
{ White tries to make a point of the bishop being pinned on c5. It leads to a forced line that neither side can deviate from. }
12... Bxf2+
{ The only way to make the position balanced, other moves would give White an advantage. }
13. Kxf2 cxb3 14. Bxa6 Qb6+
{ Important to remember not to capture the bishop with the knight, which would lose a piece. }
15. Kf3
{ There is no better square for the White king, because White wants to bring the h1-rook into the game, and Ke1 would block the rook.   15.Kg3?!  Would not be a good idea due to -  15...Qc7+!  16.Kf3  Nxa6⩱  This is a big improvement to the game since White does not have Qe5 check anymore. }
15... Qxa6 16. Qe5+ Kd8
{ A very important move that keeps equality. Interestingly enough, the black king is pretty safe, because of the knights' control of the d7-square which will defend adequately. }
17. Qd4+ { White has to cover the d3-square. } 17... Nbd7 18. Nxb3 Qb6
{ The position is roughly equal. I believe that the best White move @@StartBracket@@Qxb6@@EndBracket@@ will lead to an equal endgame, which should end in a draw. }
