{ The best move in the position. It simply protects the e4-pawn, so finally, White will be able to grab the b3-pawn.   16.Qxb3  Ideally White would like to take on b3 with a knight, but since the e4-pawn would hang then Qxb3 is logical. However, it makes White's position underdeveloped.  16...Ne5=  . @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p2n1ppp/2p2n2/2b2N2/P3P3/1Q6/1P1N1PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nxe4  would have led to a slightly worse pawn structure, therefore  16...Ne5  is better. Black has full compensation for the pawn, because of their better-placed pieces. Next is ...Nd3, ...Rb8, and eventually taking the e4-pawn if possible. }
16... Rb8
{ As Black has put the rook on b8 in other lines, it is also a good square to prepare for Nxb3. }
17. Nxb3 Bf8
{ Again, the f8-square is an appropriate place for the Bishop. Now Black threatens a lot of moves like ...Rb4, ...Ne5, ...Qb6, highlighting the weak knight on b3. }
18. Be3 Rb4 19. Qc2 Ne5
{ I think that Black has enough compensation for equality here. Black is controlling the b-file, which is one of the key factors that make the position roughly equal. Next is most likely ...Qb8, to put pressure on the knight and the pawn on b2. }
