1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. b3
{ This is the only move that makes sense for White to play other than  6.Nc3  , which is the mainline. Here, White wants to win the pawn back on c4. Luckily, Black has a great response to this. }
6... e5
{ If you looked at other sidelines that I have covered in this course, then the e5-breakthrough should not come as a surprise. Black makes use of the material advantage at the moment, as this move is not really a sacrifice when you are a pawn up anyway. It is a great idea to unbalance the center. }
7. Nf3
{ The knight seems to keep the center together, but it does not help White to get anything good out of this. }
7... exd4
{ Simply exchanging the pawns. White now needs to decide whether they want to go to an endgame or play more ambitiously. }
8. Qxd4
{ Black could avoid trading queens here, but I believe that the easiest play is to go for the endgame. }
8... Nc6 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. bxc4 b4
{ I think that this endgame is much more pleasant for Black to play. Black's connected pawns could become very dangerous later on. Next is ...Nf6, ...a5. }
