{ I believe that the moves are fairly logical and straightforward up to this point. This position could look daunting as it may be hard to assess who is better and why. Black has a knight and a pawn for the rook, and the king on d8 is cut off from castling. However, we can observe that the black pieces are well placed, or will be well placed. Black is planning to go ...Bb4, developing with a tempo and then ...Re8 will bother the e1-king. But most importantly, Black has the very lovely d5-square. Black will surely place the knight on d5 at some point, which will also highlight the fact that White has to deal with an isolated d4-pawn. }
14. f3
{ White closes the long diagonal, which is essential in order to develop the kingside pieces. It also potentially gives an escape opportunity for the white king on the f2-square. }
14... Nd5
{ Placing the knight on d5 is the right way to play, as it's controlling a lot of squares in the center. }
15. Bd2
{ This is the best square for the bishop, as it controls both the e3 and b4-square. }
15... Bd6
{ A healthy developing move. This is the ideal setup for the black pieces. }
16. Ng3
{ White is planning to put their king to safety with Be2 and O-O. Black has to stop that!  16.Kf2  Re8=  Black brings the last piece into play. I think Black has full compensation for the exchange here because the white pieces and the king are awkwardly placed. }
16... Qb8
{ The bishop and the queen are powerful together, and put a lot of pressure on White's kingside, especially the knight on g3. }
17. Kf2
{ White tries to solve their king and knight problems at the same time, but it does not work out well. }
17... Bc7
{ Black has this incredibly important move to transfer the bishop to d6 and put pressure on the d4-pawn. If White has to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Ba5, then the dark squares will become vulnerable for White. }
