{ It is better to develop the knight to e7 than to f6, because in the case of ...Nf6, White often has the move e5 which could be very strong. }
10. Na2
{ White is trying to make use of the fact that the knight on c3 is no longer pinned. Also, there are limited options for Black here. }
10... Ba5
{ It is better to place the bishop on a5 than d6, because on d6, it could always run into e5, which is unpleasant to deal with. }
11. b4
{ White plays creatively here. It is quite obvious that White has the development advantage, therefore opening up the position is usually a good idea. }
11... cxb3 12. Qxb3
{ Now I believe this position requires quite a bit of explanation. As I mentioned earlier, White is better developed, therefore the open position benefits White. In other words, White has compensation for the pawn. However, we can observe that White has two very awkwardly placed pieces, the h3 and a2-knights. Those pieces will require some tempi to be better placed. It is also worth mentioning that Black is still a pawn up, thus making some defensive moves could be very beneficial for the future. }
12... O-O 13. Be3
{ 13.Qxb5?!  It is not a good idea for White to exchange queens.  13...Qxb5  14.Bxb5  Rd8⩱  Black has a very pleasant endgame. The d4-pawn can become very weak. }
13... a6 { Simply defending the b5-pawn. } 14. Nc3
{ White slowly makes its pieces better. White's plan is to play moves like Nf4-d5, and Rfc1. }
14... Qd8
{ A very important retreat! Black had to avoid White playing d5 with a tempo. }
15. Rfd1 { White has to play d5, otherwise, the compensation would evaporate. }
15... Bb7 16. d5
