{ A more simple choice, but I believe not as demanding as  17.Nf4  . Black now needs to handle White's main plan, which is d6. }
17... Bxc3 { Black wants to solve the problems with concrete moves. } 18. Qxc3
Nxd5
{ Now Black is two pawns up, but the position is not easy, because Black has to deal with the d-file pin. }
19. Qb3
{ White is simply threatening Bf3 to win the piece. Luckily, Black has a very nice move to stop that. Can you find it? }
19... Qf6
{ This steps out of the d-file pin, and also attacks the a1-rook, so White cannot take on d5. }
20. Bd4
{ Despite the fact that Black has stepped out of the pin, there are still some issues to solve.  20.Rxd5??  White is abandoning the a1-rook.  20...Bxd5  21.Qxd5  Qxa1+-+  . }
20... Qf5 21. Bf3
{ Another pin which Black has to deal with. White is threatening to use the f3-b7 pin by just moving its d4-bishop. }
21... Nd7
{ The best move, which leads to a forced variation after  22.Bxg7!  White has to take action, otherwise Black would have time to regroup their pieces, and then the material advantage would prevail.  22...Kxg7  23.Bxd5  Now, White has won one pawn back, and weakened the black king. Therefore, it is a very important moment. Black has to find the best moves to equalize.  23...Bxd5!  24.Rxd5  Qf6!  The only move that saves the game. Black now has used the fact that the a1-rook is not protected, twice.  25.Rad1  Ne5  The only move that saves the knight, but it works!  26.Rd6  Qe7  27.Nf4  White finally uses the h3-knight.  27...Kh8=  The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I believe that Black has to make quite obvious defending moves to hold the position together, which puts pressure on White as the material still favors Black. }
