1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. Be3
{ It is a logical developing move that wants to make use of the queen standing on b6, as d5 will come with a tempo. }
7... e6
{ This move has two ideas, one is to stop White from playing Nd5, and the second is that d5 can be answered with ...Bc5. }
8. d5
{ There was one game played for this line, but from two particularly good grandmasters. Yilmaz, M - Andersen, M. I know that both are very good theoreticians, therefore this line can be especially important to remember. }
8... Bc5 { Black plans to exchange to good e3-bishop. } 9. Bxc5 Qxc5 10. Nf3
{ This position may seem harmless at first sight, as Black is still a pawn up and White has no real threat, but that is not the case. Now, the move Nf3 has a very nice idea, which is that White threatens with Qd4. After Qd4, exchanging queens would result in the loss of the b5-pawn. Therefore, Black has to be careful here. }
10... a6 { Black stabilizes their queenside. } 11. dxe6 Bxe6
