[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 3.e4 b5 6.Nc3 7.b3"]
[Black "7.b3 e6 8.bxc4 Bb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. b3
{ White simply wants to get the material back. It is a typical way to break up the Black pawn structure on the queenside. However, this gives Black time to develop its pieces. }
7... e6
{ Black ignores the hanging c4-pawn and rather prepares to develop pieces. } 8.
bxc4 Bb4 9. Qb3
{ This is a move that definitely deserves attention. It was employed by Super GM David Navara. I think this move's idea is quite clear for now, as it protects the c3-knight and questions the b4-bishop.   9.Bb2  It's not ideal to defend the knight from b2, as it does not unpin the knight  9...Nf6!  10.e5  Ne4⩱  Black would have the initiative. }
9... bxc4 { The best way to keep the b4-bishop on the board. } 10. Bxc4 Nc6
{ An important move that not only puts pressure on the d4-pawn but also threatens ...Na5. }
11. Ne2 { White has no other move than to protect the d4-pawn. } 11... Na5
{ Black tries to get rid of the c4-bishop. If Black could get the bishop pair here, then there would be no question of which side is better and why. }
12. Qa2
{ David Navara decided to keep the equal material, but it was a mistake! }
12... Nxc4 13. Qxc4 a5
{ An important move which gives the c8-bishop a square on a6. Black was better in the game of Navara, D - Xiong, J 2021. }
