bxc4 Bb4 9. Bd2 bxc4
{ Black has to remove one pawn from the powerful White center, otherwise, c5 would come with force. }
10. Na4
{ No one has ever played this in a classical game, but I believe it is worth mentioning. This move kind of leads to a forced variation. Note that the knight on a4 could look a little misplaced, but in certain positions, it threatens Nb6 winning the rook on a8. Therefore, Black should always keep an eye on that idea. }
10... Qb7 11. Bxc4
{ White disregards the fact that the e4-pawn is hanging, in the hope that it will get enough compensation in exchange. }
11... Qxe4+ 12. Ne2
{ White has nearly finished developing, hence Black should be careful here. }
12... Bxd2+
{ Black should not be greedy with  12...Qxg2  , because that could give White the chance to get a great deal of attack after  13.Rg1  . }
13. Qxd2 Nf6 { Black has to develop as fast as possible. } 14. Nc3
{ White decides it's time to improve the a4-knight. It also gives the tempting opportunity for Black to take on g2, but I think it's better to avoid that.   14.O-O?!  O-O  15.Nac3  Qc6⩱  Black would win a tempo compared to the game, because in the game @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/p4ppp/4pn2/8/2BPq3/2N5/3QNPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qc6  is not possible due to  15.Bb5  . }
14... Qb7
{ 14...Qxg2  would only cause unnecessary problems for Black. After  15.Rg1  Qxh2  16.Rxg7  White would have enough compensation for the material. Thus, I think the main move @@StartBracket@@14...Qb7@@EndBracket@@ is more in the spirit of the QGA opening. }
15. O-O O-O 16. d5
{ White has to create counterplay to compensate for the pawn. } 16... a5
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. However, I prefer Black here, as Black is still a pawn up, and White is not threatening anything dangerous at the moment. The moves that I would suggest considering in this position are ...Qc7, ...Bd7, ...Na6. }
