{ Black ignores the hanging c4-pawn and rather prepares to develop pieces. } 8.
bxc4 Bb4 9. Bd2 bxc4
{ Black has to remove one pawn from the powerful White center, otherwise, c5 would come with force. }
10. Bxc4
{ White simply captures the pawn back. Now the material is equal, however, the following moves will show that Black has no development disadvantage anymore. }
10... Ne7
{ Simply continuing the development, and also threatening ...Qxd4. Now White has two ways to develop the g1- knight, either to f3 or e2. }
11. Nf3
{ Some people would argue that the knight on f3 is more healthy than the knight on e2, but both moves have their advantages/ disadvantages. }
11... O-O 12. O-O a5
{ It is almost always good to place the pawn on a5, as it not only supports the b4-square but also gives space for moves like ...Ba6. }
13. Na4
{ Blockading the a5-pawn with the knight is naturally a good way to play, but it gives no more than equality for White. }
13... Qd6 14. e5
{ White wants to grab the momentum and start attacking with Ng5-Qh5, but it does not really work out. }
14... Qd8
{ Black is totally fine here. ...Nbc6 is next if White does not do anything concrete. }
