{ Some people would argue that the knight on f3 is more healthy than the knight on e2, but both moves have their advantages/ disadvantages. }
11... O-O 12. O-O a5
{ It is almost always good to place the pawn on a5, as it not only supports the b4-square but also gives space for moves like ...Ba6. }
13. Re1
{ White delays Na4, and also prepares another typical idea with d5. Black has to be careful here regarding piece development. }
13... Nd7
{ A very important move! White's main idea is to break in the center with d5, thus the only good square to develop the b8-knight is to d7. }
14. d5
{ White has the better center, therefore using that center makes a lot of sense. }
14... Nc5
{ There are several ways to play this middlegame with Black, but I believe this is the very best. Black does not need to hurry with ...exd5, since that would only open the file for the e1-rook. }
15. Na4
{ White decides to exchange the strong c5-knight, which will result in a very solid position for both sides. }
15... Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Bxd2 17. Nxd2 Rd8
{ Bringing the rook into play. The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I think Black should not have to worry about much, since this is a very stable position. Next is ...exd5 and then ...Bd7-Nf5. }
