[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 3.e4 b5 6.Nc3 7.b3"]
[Black "7.b3 e6 8.bxc4 Bb4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. b3
{ White simply wants to get the material back. It is a typical way to break up the Black pawn structure on the queenside. However, this gives Black time to develop its pieces. }
7... e6
{ Black ignores the hanging c4-pawn and rather prepares to develop pieces. } 8.
bxc4 Bb4 9. Bd2 bxc4
{ Black has to remove one pawn from the powerful White center, otherwise, c5 would come with force. }
10. Bxc4
{ White simply captures the pawn back. Now the material is equal, however, the following moves will show that Black has no development disadvantage anymore. }
10... Ne7
{ Simply continuing the development, and also threatening ...Qxd4. Now White has two ways to develop the g1- knight, either to f3 or e2. }
11. Nb5
{ I think it is worth mentioning this novelty. This idea is similar to  11.Na4  , meaning that White wants to get rid of the dark-squared bishops. }
11... Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Bb7
{ Black immediately highlights the fact that the e4-pawn is not protected anymore. }
13. Nc3
{ White achieved the plan of exchanging the bishops, and now retreats to stabilize the center.  13.Ne2!?  A tricky move! Do not fall for the trap. ...Bxe4 would not work because of Qf4, which is attacking the bishop and also supporting Nc7.  13...O-O!  14.Nbc3  a5!  15.O-O  Rd8  16.Rfb1  Qc7=  Black is fine here, as White cannot really use their space advantage. }
13... O-O 14. Nf3 Rc8 { Black is bringing the rook into play with a tempo. }
15. Bd3 Ba6
{ As I mentioned earlier, it is in Black's favor to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. O-O
{ Now both sides finished have developing, therefore, it's time to make middlegame plans. }
17... Nb4
{ This is the ideal place for the knight. Black will stabilize the knight on b4 with the move a5, hence White will not have an open b-file for its rooks. }
18. Na4
{ White places the knight on a4 with tempo, which is the right way to stop Black's a-pawn. }
18... Qd6 19. Nc5 a5
{ The position is equal with chances for both sides. I believe that since Black has achieved what was wanted with Nb4-a5, there is nothing to worry about. It is a slow position, meaning that both sides have to be patient. Ideas for Black are moves like ...h6 to open the back rank, and then ...Nec6 to put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
