{ Black has to play the move a5, otherwise, the position would become unpleasant and unstable. As in other lines, it is important to support the b4-square. Now, White has several alternatives. I will cover all the moves that I think are worth covering. }
13. Na4
{ A very human move. You may have heard of the principle that the best piece to blockade a passed pawn is the knight. Now White wants to follow that principle. }
13... Qc6
{ Black responds to losing a tempo by winning a tempo. Now White has to be creative. }
14. d5
{ A very creative move that unbalances the position. At first, it may look like a blunder, but Qxc4 would result in a slightly worse game after ...Nb6.   14.Bd3  Ba6=  White does not really have a plan which could be dangerous for Black after exchanging the bishops. }
14... exd5 15. exd5 Qxc4
{ I believe this is not the only way to equalize, but I think it is the best move. Now the following couple of moves are forced. }
16. Nb6 Qa6 17. Bxb4
{ 17.Nxa8  I believe that not a lot of humans would go for this as it will result in losing material.  17...Bxd2  18.Qxd2  Qxa8  19.Rxa5?!  Qb7⩱  Black is slightly better, as Black should be the only side who can win this. }
17... Qxb6 18. Bxe7 Re8
{ Now the complications are over, and it has resulted in an opposite-colored bishops position. As opposite-colored bishop positions often are, this position is equal. }
19. d6 { White tries to get some space advantage. } 19... Nc6 20. Nf4
{ Bringing the knight into play; it is planning to go to d5. } 20... Nxe7 21.
dxe7 Bb7
{ The position is equal, as the most likely result is that Black will win the e-pawn but lose the a-pawn in exchange. Next is either ...Qf6, or ...Qc6 depending on White's move. }
