{ This move has been quite fashionable lately. Its main idea is to stop Black from playing c5. Fortunately, Black has quite an ideal setup that fits in with our repertoire. }
3... e6 { A simple move which prepares the move c5. } 4. Bg5
{ This move avoids the mainlines, and White simply wants to play Nbd2-e3-Bd3.   4.Bf4  White could transpose to the London System.  4...c5  5.e3  . }
4... h6
{ Immediately questioning the bishop's place on g5. Now White has to decide whether to keep the bishop or not. }
5. Bxf6
{ White decides to take to lure the Black queen out and potentially win some tempi. }
5... Qxf6
{ Black has the bishop pair which is very useful, however, White has a good plan which can slightly cause concerns for Black. }
6. Nbd2
{ This move grants the only plan that could cause problems in Black's position. Now Black has to come up with an idea against the White plan with e4. }
6... c5
{ An important move which immediately highlights the fact that Black has the dark-squared bishop and White does not. Opening the center could be beneficial for Black. }
7. e3
{ White could choose this solid setup, which makes a very stable pawn structure. However, this leads to a comfortable position for Black. }
7... Nc6 { Stopping White from playing Ne5-f4. } 8. Bd3 Bd6
{ I think Black is slightly better because of the bishop pair, however, White has a very stable position and that makes Black's job difficult to prove an advantage. }
