[Black "6.O-O a6 7.Re1 Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3
{ This move is considered to be the mainline of the Queen's Gambit Accepted opening.  If I would have to explain the difference between  3.e4  and  3.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@  3.e3  same@@EndBracket@@, then I would say that  3.Nf3  is the more classical, positional approach, and  3.e4  is the more modern, engine based theory.  Now,  3.Nf3  is on the board, and White simply wants to develop with e3-Bxc4-O-O and have a solid positional middlegame. }
3... Nf6 { The next few moves for Black are simple: ...e6,...c5,...a6. } 4. e3
{ 4.Nc3  a6  Transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.c4  dxc4  4.Nc3  a6  as seen here. }
4... e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6
{ Up to this point there were no real alternatives for any colors. So now we have reached the initial position of this line. Here White can choose from several options. Most of the alternatives are solid but some of them are very forced. Generally speaking, Black wants to play healthy, positional moves like ...Nc6, ...cxd4, ...Be7, ...O-O and then possibly play against the isolated d4-pawn. }
7. Re1
{ A prophylactic move. I believe that this move has two main purposes. One is that White waits for Black to play ...cxd4 and then after exd4, the rook on e1 will have an open file, and the second is that sometimes White can play e4. Note that this move is not very common, but it has been used by some super grandmasters, so I believe it is worth mentioning. }
7... Nc6
{ Simply developing the knight to c6, which is usually the right square for the b8-knight. }
8. Nc3 { White develops its knight as well, so it can support the center. }
8... b5
{ Playing for concrete ideas. The more solid choice is  8...Be7  , but I think the move that I'm recommending gives Black a more clear solution to equalize. The move ...b5 has advantages and disadvantages as well. The advantage is that b5 comes with a tempo, and then Black can develop the c8-bishop to the long diagonal. The disadvantage of this move is that White can always play a4 to break the harmony of the Black queenside pawns. }
9. Bd3 Bb7
{ The bishop found its best square on the board. A typical move. White wants to eventually take on c5 and play b4-Bb2. }
10. a4 { White intends to break Black's nice pawn structure on the queenside. }
10... b4
{ The a4-b4 moves are very typical in this opening. Black has to keep the a-file closed, plus it comes with a tempo. }
11. Ne4
{ Again, the e4-square is pivotal. Black has to take control over the e4-square, otherwise, problems could occur. ...Nxe4 is usually not a good idea since, after Bxe4, the e4-bishop would be powerful. }
11... Na5
{ A very important move. Targeting the e4-square! The knight on a5 is a very useful piece. It sometimes allows Black to play ...c4, and also White will always have to watch out for the b3-square. }
12. Nxc5 { Accepting the pawn sacrifice. } 12... Bxc5 13. dxc5 O-O
{ Now the position is fairly complicated. White has won a pawn and also got the bishop pair. But what has Black got? Black has space advantage and better-placed pieces which are more flexible than White's. I believe that Black has full compensation here. A simple plan is to play ...Rc8 and take the c5-pawn, but obviously White cannot let that happen. }
14. Qc2
{ It is not easy to develop the White pieces. Qc2 protects the c5-pawn and also planning to develop the bishop to d2.   14.e4?!  It would not work out for tactical reasons.  14...Bxe4↑  . }
14... Bxf3
{ Giving up the bishop, but damaging the White pawn structure on the kingside. }
15. gxf3 Nd7
{ A key move! It opens the way for the d8-queen, so it can go to h4 or g5, and it also puts pressure on the c5-pawn. }
16. Bd2
{ Developing and targeting the b4-pawn.  16.Bxh7+?  White does not have time to grab the h7-pawn.  16...Kh8  17.Be4  Rc8-+  White is way behind in development and therefore the position is hopeless. }
16... Qh4
{ Making the White king a little uncomfortable, and the queen also protects the b4-pawn. }
17. Rac1 { Here White also wants to see where the Black compensation is. }
17... Ne5
{ Black brings an additional piece into the attack against the white king. }
18. Be2 Rad8
{ Putting pressure on the d2-bishop. If we compare this position to @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/3n1ppp/p3p3/n1P5/Pp5q/3BPP2/1PQB1P1P/R3R1K1 w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Red1  then we can see that the rook was on d1, so the d2-bishop was defended, therefore here Black uses the fact that d2-bishop is shaky. }
19. Red1 f5
{ Now that White has double defended the d2-bishop, it is time to make other threats. }
20. Be1 Rd3
{ An incredibly unique move. This move basically leads to a forced draw. } 21.
Rxd3 Rf6
{ White has to make a couple of good moves to make the draw here. I believe that Black is the only one who can win this position. The attack is quite simple. }
*

