[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) 2.Bg5 The Hodgson Attack"]
[Black "4.e3 Nf5 5.Bg3 h5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This is called the Hodgson Attack. White's basic idea is to stop the black knight from developing to f6 without worrying about damaging the pawn structure. Luckily, Black has a solution. }
2... f6
{ Normally, it is not ideal to play with the f-pawn early on in the opening since it could weaken the king's safety, but in this case, it's coming with a tempo and we will use this tempo to our advantage. }
3. Bh4 { A bad place for the bishop. } 3... Nh6
{ A very nice developing move that goes after the bishop on h4. } 4. e3 Nf5 5.
Bg3 h5 6. Be2
{ This move may look scary at first sight, but there is a quite simple solution. }
6... h4 7. Bh5+ Kd7
{ Black does not have to worry about their king being on d7 since White's bishop is in trouble. }
8. Bg4 e6 9. Bf4 g5 10. e4 { The only way to save the bishop. } 10... dxe4 11.
Bc1
{ 11.Bd2  Ke7  12.Nc3  Qxd4-+  with precise play, Black has a winning advantage. }
11... Ke8 { Black is winning, thanks to their material and space advantage. } *

