1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This is called the Hodgson Attack. White's basic idea is to stop the black knight from developing to f6 without worrying about damaging the pawn structure. Luckily, Black has a solution. }
2... f6
{ Normally, it is not ideal to play with the f-pawn early on in the opening since it could weaken the king's safety, but in this case, it's coming with a tempo and we will use this tempo to our advantage. }
3. Bh4 { A bad place for the bishop. } 3... Nh6
{ A very nice developing move that goes after the bishop on h4. } 4. f3
{ A very logical move, which gives a place for the bishop on f2. However, Black now can grab the momentum and play aggressively. }
4... c5 5. dxc5 e6
{ The most played move is  5...e5  which is logical to take control of the center, but in this specific position, it's better to protect our d5-pawn, and threaten to capture the c5-pawn. }
6. Bf2 Nd7 7. b4
{ Defending the pawn with b4 is not a good idea, since Black can employ a fairly typical plan to get it back. }
7... a5 8. c3 axb4 9. cxb4 b6
{ Now the position is more open which is bad news for White since Black's pieces are more developed. }
10. cxb6 Bxb4+ { Next is ...Nxb6-Nc4, everything is dangerous for White. } *

