[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) 2.Bg5 The Hodgson Attack"]
[Black "3.Bf4 Nc6 4.Nf3 g5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This is called the Hodgson Attack. White's basic idea is to stop the black knight from developing to f6 without worrying about damaging the pawn structure. Luckily, Black has a solution. }
2... f6
{ Normally, it is not ideal to play with the f-pawn early on in the opening since it could weaken the king's safety, but in this case, it's coming with a tempo and we will use this tempo to our advantage. }
3. Bf4
{ I believe that placing the bishop on f4 is more natural than placing it on h4. Black now has a nice plan to employ. }
3... Nc6 { Threatening to breakthrough in the center with ...e5. } 4. Nf3 g5
{ This may seem like a rather unusual move in the opening, but the idea is to make use of Black's pawn on f6 by pushing the g-pawn further to g4 with a tempo, and also gaining space on the kingside. }
5. Bg3
{ The bishop is keeping eye on the center, so Black cannot really play ...e5. }
5... g4 6. Nh4 e5
{ Black simply takes the center here. Now White has to create counterplay, otherwise Black would have a comfortable position. }
7. dxe5 fxe5 8. e4
{ The best and only move for White. This move weakens the strong Black center and stops the ...Be7 threat. }
8... Nf6
{ The best way to defend the center. All other moves would cause problems for Black. }
9. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black decides to offer a trade of queens. It makes the position less complicated for both sides. }
10. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ This endgame is equal and offers chances for both sides. Next is ...Nf4, ...Bd7, and ...O-O-O. Note that as long as the white knight stays on h4, Black stands better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) 2.Bg5 The Hodgson Attack"]
[Black "3.Bf4 Nc6 4.Nf3 g5 #2 | Alternative 6...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This is called the Hodgson Attack. White's basic idea is to stop the black knight from developing to f6 without worrying about damaging the pawn structure. Luckily, Black has a solution. }
2... f6
{ Normally, it is not ideal to play with the f-pawn early on in the opening since it could weaken the king's safety, but in this case, it's coming with a tempo and we will use this tempo to our advantage. }
3. Bf4
{ I believe that placing the bishop on f4 is more natural than placing it on h4. Black now has a nice plan to employ. }
3... Nc6 { Threatening to breakthrough in the center with ...e5. } 4. Nf3 g5
{ This may seem like a rather unusual move in the opening, but the idea is to make use of Black's pawn on f6 by pushing the g-pawn further to g4 with a tempo, and also gaining space on the kingside. }
5. Bg3
{ The bishop is keeping eye on the center, so Black cannot really play ...e5. }
5... g4 6. Nh4 f5
{ The idea of advancing the pawns is quite simple - Black is threatening to play ...e5 and win a piece with ...f4 or ...Be7. This forces White to find the only move which can equalize! }
7. c4
{ White has no other way than to try to create counterplay in the center.   7.e3?!  A logical move preventing Black from playing ...e5-f4, this fails to concrete moves like  7...e5!  8.dxe5  Be7∓  There is no way to defend the knight on h4. }
7... e6 8. Nc3
{ White decides to sacrifice the h4-knight but plans to get compensation in the center. }
8... f4
{ As I mentioned earlier one of Black's main ideas is to take advantage of the badly placed h4-knight. }
9. Bxf4 Qxh4 10. cxd5
{ White takes Black's important center pawn which will give a great deal of compensation. }
10... exd5 11. Nxd5 Qd8 { The best move, it sets a trap. } 12. Nxc7+
{ This would fail to an immediate tactic. Better is  12.e4  which gives White some compensation. White controls the whole center, and that promises sufficient compensation for the rest of the game. The position is complicated and White has to make a couple of accurate moves to get full credit for their strong center. Personally, I would suggest not going for this position with Black, because this can be dangerous. However, if you are someone who likes complicated, sharp positions, then this line is for you. }
12... Qxc7 13. Bxc7 Bb4+
{ Black is winning here thanks to the material advantage. } *

