[White "21) 3.e3 - 6.Qe2 & 3.Nf3 7.b3"]
[Black "3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3
{ A solid move. White simply wants to play Bb2-Nbd2 to finish the development. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black's play is also slow. There are other alternatives for Black on the 7th move, but I believe the move that I'm recommending is the easiest way to equalize. Black's plan is simple - ...Be7, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...O-O. }
8. Bb2 Be7 9. Nbd2 b6
{ Black has to develop its queenside first and then castle. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5
{ We can see that the position is very symmetrical, but it can sometimes be tricky. Here White is the one trying to prove that their position is better. The good news for Black is that the following moves/plans are rather simple. }
11. Qe2
{ There are two squares where the White queen usually belongs in these structures. First is on e2 as in the text move, where the white queen and the c4-bishop put pressure on the a6-pawn. The second place is on b1/a1. White can sometimes employ a creative plan with Rc1-Qc2-Qb1 and then after Bd3, the queen and the bishops would put pressure on the Black kingside. }
11... Bb7 12. a3 { A typical move that intends to win space with b4. } 12...
O-O
{ Now that Black has finished developing on the queenside, it is time to castle. }
13. b4 Be7
{ This is the solid setup that usually works the best for Black. There are no weaknesses in Black's position, and therefore it is easy to play. }
14. Bd3 b5
{ It makes Black's job easier, bettering their pieces since the a6-pawn is no longer under attack. }
15. e4
{ I think that this is the most ambitious move that White can employ. It essentially blocks the b7-bishop and takes the d5-square away from the f6-knight. However, Black still has zero problems. }
15... Rc8 16. Rfd1 Qc7
{ Now it is very important to remember this plan. A very common way to improve the queen and Black's position, in general, is to put the queen on b8/a8. Thus, ...Rc8-Qc7-Qb8 is a very useful idea to remember. }
17. Rac1 Qb8
{ The position is balanced. Next is to exchange the rooks on c1, followed by ...Rc8. }
