1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. b3
{ A solid move. White simply wants to play Bb2-Nbd2 to finish the development. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black's play is also slow. There are other alternatives for Black on the 7th move, but I believe the move that I'm recommending is the easiest way to equalize. Black's plan is simple - ...Be7, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...O-O. }
8. Bb2 Be7 9. Nbd2 b6
{ Black has to develop its queenside first and then castle. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5
{ We can see that the position is very symmetrical, but it can sometimes be tricky. Here White is the one trying to prove that their position is better. The good news for Black is that the following moves/plans are rather simple. }
11. Bd3
{ The bishop on d3 is usually where the light square bishop belongs for White. It is eyeing Black's kingside and also threatens to play Ne4. }
11... Bb7 { Simply developing and stopping White from playing Ne4. } 12. e4
{ An ambitious move. It takes away the d5-square from Black and it's blocking the b7-bishop's way. Luckily, Black's position is very stable therefore Black is fine. }
12... O-O
{ Finally, the king is castled. Black now needs to simply finish developing. }
