[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Be2"]
[Black " 6.O-O a6 7.Be2 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Be2
{ The main idea of this move is to stop Black from playing ...b5 with a tempo. Now, If Black would play ...b5, then White could always answer with a4 to weaken the Black pawn structure on the queenside. }
7... cxd4
{ Black aims to play a simple position. After this exchange, the pawn structure will become quite symmetrical. }
8. exd4
{ An ambitious move. White decides to go for the isolated pawn structure, which makes the position less symmetrical. }
8... Nc6
{ Developing the knight to its right square, so later on it can go to b4 and then to d5. }
9. Nc3 Be7 { Simply preparing to castle. } 10. Be3
{ Now White is more or less done with development and intends to play Ne5 to bother the c6-knight. However, White is only able to play Ne5 because the d4-pawn is now protected by the e3-bishop. Therefore, Black has to use the momentum and target the e3-bishop. }
10... Ng4 { Chasing the bishop away, so the d4-pawn will be less protected. }
11. Bf4 Nf6
{ The moves Ng4-Nf6 may look a little bit odd at first, but I think it is the best way to play for Black. Now White cannot play ...Ne5 because of the hanging d4-pawn, and otherwise White does not have much to play for. }
12. Rc1 O-O
{ Finally, Black can castle in peace, since there is no Ne5 coming. } 13. a3
{ A typical move to stop Black from playing ...Nb4. } 13... b6
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I think these isolated pawn positions are quite easy for Black to play. Next is ...Bb7-Rc8 and then perhaps b5-b4 could be unpleasant for White. }
