1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Be2
{ The main idea of this move is to stop Black from playing ...b5 with a tempo. Now, If Black would play ...b5, then White could always answer with a4 to weaken the Black pawn structure on the queenside. }
7... cxd4
{ Black aims to play a simple position. After this exchange, the pawn structure will become quite symmetrical. }
8. Nxd4
{ After this, we transition into a dry, rather uneventful position. The only question is whether White can find a maneuver/plan to put pressure on Black or not. }
8... Be7
{ The only job that Black has in this position is to finish development and put their pieces on healthy squares. }
9. b3
{ I think this is the best plan that White can come up with. White wants to finish development with Bb2-Nd2. }
9... Bd7
{ An important move. Black prepares to play ...Nc6 to exchange the best piece that White has - the centralized d4-knight. }
10. Bb2 O-O { Black finally castles. Next is developing the b8-knight. } 11.
Bf3 { White tries to stop Nc6 and also attacks the b7-pawn. } 11... e5
{ A very important move which highlights why playing Bf3 is inaccurate. } 12.
Nc2 e4 { Closing the f3-bishop's diagonal. } 13. Be2 Qa5
{ Black has space advantage here, therefore I believe that Black has more chances to get an advantage. The next moves ...Rd8-Qg5 will put pressure on White. }
