[Black " 6.O-O a6 7.Be2 cxd4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Be2
{ The main idea of this move is to stop Black from playing ...b5 with a tempo. Now, If Black would play ...b5, then White could always answer with a4 to weaken the Black pawn structure on the queenside. }
7... cxd4
{ Black aims to play a simple position. After this exchange, the pawn structure will become quite symmetrical. }
8. Nxd4
{ After this, we transition into a dry, rather uneventful position. The only question is whether White can find a maneuver/plan to put pressure on Black or not. }
8... Be7
{ The only job that Black has in this position is to finish development and put their pieces on healthy squares. }
9. b3
{ I think this is the best plan that White can come up with. White wants to finish development with Bb2-Nd2. }
9... Bd7
{ An important move. Black prepares to play ...Nc6 to exchange the best piece that White has - the centralized d4-knight. }
10. Bb2 O-O { Black finally castles. Next is developing the b8-knight. } 11.
Nd2 { White finished its light piece development and plans to play Bf3. } 11...
Nc6
{ This move is the reason why 9...Bd7 is an important move. Now Black can develop to c6 without damaging their pawn structure. The exchange of the knights is in Black's favor, since the b8-knight was definitely not worth as much as the d4-knight. }
12. Bf3
{ The most challenging move. The bishop on f3 is very well placed as it puts pressure on the Black queenside. }
12... Rc8 { Simply developing the rook and protecting the c6-knight. } 13. Nc4
{ White has ideally placed all its pieces, and therefore I believe that there is some pressure on Black. }
13... b5
{ There are other alternatives for Black on the 13th move, but I think this is the most direct way to equalize. The following moves lead to an endgame. }
14. Nxc6
{ White is forced to trade pieces, as  14.Nd2  is not really an option to consider. }
14... Bxc6 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8
{ Most people go for  15...Bxd8  which I believe is slightly inaccurate. The move that I'm recommending leads to a slightly unpleasant endgame, but I think Black can equalize with some accurate moves. }
16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Bxc6 Rxb6
{ Now we have reached an endgame where White has the bishop pair, hence the pressure. However, the pawn structure is very symmetrical and there are not so many pieces on the board. Black has to play some good moves to fully equalize, but I believe it is not a very difficult position to play. }
18. Rac1 Rbb8
{ Important to retreat the rook, because it was misplaced on b6. Black intends to play ...Nd5. }
19. Bf3 { White makes space for the c1-rook on c6. } 19... Nd5
{ This is the ideal place for the knight. Now, Rc6 would be met by ...Nb4. }
20. Be5 Rbc8
{ I think Black has fully equalized here. The queenside pawns are not under pressure, and Black is planning to play ...Ba3 to take over the c-file. }
