[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.e4"]
[Black "6.O-O a6 7.e4 b5 8.Bd3 Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. e4
{ A very sharp move! White is sacrificing a pawn to get compensation in exchange. This is a very crucial line as the following positions will not be 'typical' Queen's Gambit Accepted positions, but rather a sharp, theoretical battle. There are two options for Black here.  7...b5  or  7...Nxe4  . All the other Black moves would lead to a worse position, as White would have a great chance to attack in the center. }
7... b5
{ I am recommending this move over  7...Nxe4  because I think  7...b5  is the best, most straightforward way to equalize. }
8. Bd3
{ I believe this is not the most critical move, but a very serious one. Oftentimes, the d3-square is the appropriate square to place the bishop because it supports the e4-pawn and the attack against the kingside. }
8... Bb7 9. e5
{ This is the most played move, but I think it does not create issues for Black. }
9... Nd5
{ Black finds a very lovely square for the knight on d5. Usually, the d5-knight is a very useful piece in these positions, as White cannot chase it away with a pawn anymore. }
10. Nc3
{ A logical developing move. Usually, the knight wants to go on e4 and put pressure on the black kingside. }
10... cxd4 { Immediately forcing White to act in the center. } 11. Nxd5
{ 11.Nxd4?!  This move leads to a position where White would have a slightly bad pawn structure.  11...Nxc3!  Damaging the white pawn structure.  12.bxc3  Qd5⩱  Double attacking the e5 and g2-pawns. }
11... Qxd5
{ The queen and the bishops are very powerful on the long diagonal. } 12. Re1
{ Usually, the rook stands well on the e-file, as it protects the e5-pawn and also helps White to play Be4 sometimes. }
12... Nc6
{ Developing the knight on its correct square. It puts pressure on the e5-pawn, and it also protects the d4-pawn. }
13. Bd2
{ White is a pawn down, however, Black has some problems with development, therefore I believe White has sufficient compensation here. Van Foreest, J. - Dominguez Perez, L. chess24.com INT 2021. }
13... Be7
{ I think Black should concentrate on finishing its kingside development. Dominguez played  13...Nb4  which turned out to be slightly risky. }
14. Re4
{ White often transfers the rook to g4 in these structures, so it can put pressure on the Black kingside. }
14... O-O
{ I believe that the Black king is safe on the kingside, as there are no direct threats towards it. }
15. Qe2 h5
{ An important defensive move! It stops White from playing Rg4 and therefore the rook can't put pressure on the black king. The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. White has compensation for the pawn, however, there are no direct threats against Black here. Next is ...Rac8 and perhaps doubling on the c-file with ...Rc7-Rfc8. }
