{ Black finds a very lovely square for the knight on d5. Usually, the d5-knight is a very useful piece in these positions, as White cannot chase it away with a pawn anymore. }
10. a4
{ White tries to weaken the Black queenside. If Black were to just push the pawn to b4, then the c4 push would never be possible again. Therefore, Black has to play accurately here. }
10... c4
{ This is the right way to fix the pawns. Now the d5-knight is even more excellent, as it often can support the queenside pawns. Black is controlling the light squares very well. }
11. Be4 h6
{ An important move which stops White from using the g5-square. The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I personally like Black in the long run as the d5-knight is a very powerful piece. Next is ...Bb4, ...Nc6. I would also suggest delaying castling for Black, as long as you see fit because then White cannot attack the black king on the kingside. }
