[Black "6.O-O a6 7.e4 b5 8.Be2 Nxe4 #1 |Informational 10...Nxd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. e4
{ A very sharp move! White is sacrificing a pawn to get compensation in exchange. This is a very crucial line as the following positions will not be 'typical' Queen's Gambit Accepted positions, but rather a sharp, theoretical battle. There are two options for Black here.  7...b5  or  7...Nxe4  . All the other Black moves would lead to a worse position, as White would have a great chance to attack in the center. }
7... b5
{ I am recommending this move over  7...Nxe4  because I think  7...b5  is the best, most straightforward way to equalize. }
8. Be2
{ The best move, as it not only prepares to play a4 and weaken the Black pawns on the queenside, but it also steps out of the c4 move that Black often uses, like against  8.Bb3  or  8.Bd3  . }
8... Nxe4 { Black finally accepts the pawn sacrifice. } 9. a4
{ This is the only way for White to get compensation for the pawn - weakening the Black queenside and then relying on the development advantage. }
9... b4
{ Now Black has no other choice than to play ...b4, since the move ...c4 would not come with a tempo, therefore White could simply take on b5. }
10. Nbd2
{ We can see that White has nearly finished developing their pieces, whereas most of Black's pieces are standing on their initial posts. Therefore, White has some compensation here. Black needs to play accurate moves to not get a worse position. }
10... Nxd2
{ This move is too careless, as it would remove the only piece that was developed for Black, and also helps White to develop their dark-squared bishop. }
11. Bxd2 cxd4 { Now Black is two pawns up, but still not developed. } 12. Rc1
{ Controlling the c-file } 12... Bb7 13. Nxd4
{ A very nice tactical resource! White has more than enough compensation for the one pawn. Can you find the move that gives White an advantage after ...Qxd4? }
13... Qxd4 14. Rc7
{ Attacking the b7-bishop. If it moves then the c8-square will not be covered, so White can play Rc8. }
14... Ra7 15. Qc1
{ A very nice move that threatens Rxb7-Rc8 and also Be3. We can see that White is a piece and a pawn down, but the black pieces are not in play as White's are. }
15... Bd6 16. Rxb7 Rxb7 17. Qc8+ Ke7 18. Qxb7+ Nd7 19. Rd1
{ The position is winning for White thanks to the bishop pair. } *

