[Black "6.O-O a6 7.e4 b5 8.Be2 Nxe4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. e4
{ A very sharp move! White is sacrificing a pawn to get compensation in exchange. This is a very crucial line as the following positions will not be 'typical' Queen's Gambit Accepted positions, but rather a sharp, theoretical battle. There are two options for Black here.  7...b5  or  7...Nxe4  . All the other Black moves would lead to a worse position, as White would have a great chance to attack in the center. }
7... b5
{ I am recommending this move over  7...Nxe4  because I think  7...b5  is the best, most straightforward way to equalize. }
8. Be2
{ The best move, as it not only prepares to play a4 and weaken the Black pawns on the queenside, but it also steps out of the c4 move that Black often uses, like against  8.Bb3  or  8.Bd3  . }
8... Nxe4 { Black finally accepts the pawn sacrifice. } 9. a4
{ This is the only way for White to get compensation for the pawn - weakening the Black queenside and then relying on the development advantage. }
9... b4
{ Now Black has no other choice than to play ...b4, since the move ...c4 would not come with a tempo, therefore White could simply take on b5. }
10. Nbd2
{ We can see that White has nearly finished developing their pieces, whereas most of Black's pieces are standing on their initial posts. Therefore, White has some compensation here. Black needs to play accurate moves to not get a worse position. }
10... Bb7 { Developing a piece and defending the e4-knight. } 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12.
Be3
{ This move was played by three good grandmasters, and all games ended in a draw. The following moves are kind of forced for both sides. }
12... cxd4 { White was threatening dxc5, therefore Black has to take on d4. }
13. Nxd4 Nc6
{ The best move, as it intends to exchange pieces. Black is still a pawn up, therefore exchanging some pieces would benefit the side which has the material advantage. }
14. Bf3
{ The only way to put pressure on Black, otherwise the compensation would evaporate. }
14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nxd4 { The only move not to lose. } 16. Bxd4 Qd5
{ Now we have reached this position, where White has to decide which direction to go. Black is a pawn up, but a bit behind in development. The good news for Black is that pieces were exchanged, therefore the position is not as complicated. }
17. Qe3
{ Keeping the queens on the board. Now White wants to play Rfd1/Rhd1 and ask questions regarding Black's development. }
17... Be7
{ This is the key move of the whole variation. If not for this move, Black would be in trouble. It is not a good idea to take the g7-pawn immediately. }
18. Rfd1
{ It is logical to win a tempo with Rfd1. Black's next move is almost forced, as the g7-pawn is hanging, which would cause serious issues. }
18... Qg5
{ Again, an important move to remember. This is the only way to equalize with Black. Now White has no better option than to go for the endgame. }
19. Qxg5 Bxg5 20. Bxg7 Rg8 21. Be5
{ We have reached an endgame where White is seemingly slightly better, but I believe with a couple of accurate moves, the position is equal. }
21... Rc8 22. Rd6 { Putting pressure on the a6-pawn. } 22... f6
{ Chasing the bishop away from its nice e5-spot. } 23. f4
{ This move would lead to an equal rook endgame. } 23... fxe5 24. fxg5 Rxg5 25.
Rxe6+ Kd7 26. Rxa6 Rc2 27. g3 Rxb2 { With an equal position. } *

