[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.a4"]
[Black "7.a4 cxd4 8.exd4 Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. a4
{ This move used to be the mainline of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Its main idea is to stop Black from playing ...b5-Bb7. However, it also weakens the b4-square, which will be very important for the rest of the game. Black can use the b4-square, like with ...Nc6-Nb4, and White will not be able to chase it away with a3. }
7... cxd4
{ Black immediately wants to fix the pawn structure. White is now left with no real option other than exd4. }
8. exd4
{ 8.Nxd4  It is not logical to combine a4 and Nxd4 because, in these symmetrical pawn structure positions, squares are important, and here the b4-square is weakened.  8...Bd7=  There is nothing that White can show in this position. Next is ...Nc6, ...Be7, and castles. Black is totally fine. }
8... Nc6
{ It is better to develop the knight to c6 than to d7 because it can go to b4/a5. }
9. Nc3 Be7
{ A simple developing move, which prepares castling. Now we have reached the initial position of this isolated pawn structure. White has a couple of ways to play this, but I believe it is not hard to equalize with Black here. Side note: If we combine this position with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  e6  6.e3  c5  7.Bxc4  cxd4  8.exd4  Nc6  9.O-O  Be7  then we can see that Black has an extra a6 move included in our position, which is a very useful move. It covers the b5-square and that can be crucial in certain lines. }
10. d5
{ White tries to highlight the fact the Black has not yet castled, and therefore, opening the position is a good idea. However, it promises nothing more than equality for White. }
10... exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 { It is necessary to remove the strong d5-knight. }
12. Bxd5 O-O
{ The Black king is safe now, and White only has a d5-bishop, which is not enough for an advantage. }
13. Qb3 Na5
{ This is a very typical move in these positions. Winning a tempo, and chasing the queen to a worse square. }
14. Qa2 Nc6
{ Again, this move pair is very common. Now Black threatens ...Nb4, and there is only one good way to stop it. }
15. Rd1
{ This move sets up a threat Bxf7, therefore ...Nb4 would not work here. However, Black can use the momentum and highlight that the d1-rook is not under protection. }
15... Be6
{ Black is exchanging the d5-bishop for the c8-bishop, which solves all the problems. White will not have anything to play for after the bishops are exchanged. Next is ...Bxd5 and if Rxd5, then ...Qe8 is a decent response. }
*

