[White "24) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.a4"]
[Black "7.a4 cxd4 8.exd4 Nc6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. a4
{ This move used to be the mainline of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Its main idea is to stop Black from playing ...b5-Bb7. However, it also weakens the b4-square, which will be very important for the rest of the game. Black can use the b4-square, like with ...Nc6-Nb4, and White will not be able to chase it away with a3. }
7... cxd4
{ Black immediately wants to fix the pawn structure. White is now left with no real option other than exd4. }
8. exd4
{ 8.Nxd4  It is not logical to combine a4 and Nxd4 because, in these symmetrical pawn structure positions, squares are important, and here the b4-square is weakened.  8...Bd7=  There is nothing that White can show in this position. Next is ...Nc6, ...Be7, and castles. Black is totally fine. }
8... Nc6
{ It is better to develop the knight to c6 than to d7 because it can go to b4/a5. }
9. Nc3 Be7
{ A simple developing move, which prepares castling. Now we have reached the initial position of this isolated pawn structure. White has a couple of ways to play this, but I believe it is not hard to equalize with Black here. Side note: If we combine this position with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  e6  6.e3  c5  7.Bxc4  cxd4  8.exd4  Nc6  9.O-O  Be7  then we can see that Black has an extra a6 move included in our position, which is a very useful move. It covers the b5-square and that can be crucial in certain lines. }
10. Be3
{ This is the main move of the whole line. White defends the d4-pawn and prepares the attacking plan of Qe2-Rad1-Ne5-f4-f5. Black has to come up with a counter-plan that is good enough to equalize. }
10... O-O { Black has to castle to get the king to safety. } 11. Qe2
{ White continues with their plan with Rad1-Ne5-f4-f5. } 11... Na5
{ My recommendation is a very rare move. The move Na5 may look a little bit odd, since it only chases the bishop to a more scary square on d3, but it has its own purpose. After Na5, White cannot really play for d5 in a good way. The following moves will show that Black has its prophylactic plan. }
12. Bd3
{ White places its bishop on a rather dangerous square from the Black perspective, as it is eyeing the kingside. Now Black has to show its hand. }
12... Nc6
{ Black simply retreats the knight to c6, so it can go to b4 and win a tempo. You may ask the question, 'why did Black not play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/8/P1BP4/2N1BN2/1P2QPPP/R4RK1 b - - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nb4  ?' The answer is that after  11...Nb4  , White could immediately play  12.Ne5  which would lead to a little bit of a worse position for Black. Here @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/p1n1pn2/8/P1BP4/2N1BN2/1P2QPPP/R4RK1 b - - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Na5  12.Bd3  Nc6  @@EndBracket@@, White cannot play Ne5 because of the hanging d-pawn, and Black is threatening to play ...Nb4 with a tempo. }
13. Rad1 { White prepares Ne5. } 13... Nb4 14. Bb1
{ The bishop on b1 finds a nice place, the only problem is that it does not support the d5-breakthrough which oftentimes is White's idea . }
14... Bd7
{ Finally developing the last minor piece. Note that usually in these isolated pawn positions, the light-squared @@StartBracket@@c8@@EndBracket@@ bishop is difficult to develop. It is always a struggle to get it into play, but once it does, Black has pretty much solved all their problems. }
15. Ne5 Nbd5
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I believe that Black will have to find some accurate defensive moves in the near future, but it should not be so difficult. Sometimes a good defensive move in such positions is ...g6, blocking the b1-bishop's way @@StartBracket@@you have to watch out for Bh6 then@@EndBracket@@. Black is threatening Nxc3-Bxa4 to win a pawn. ...Rc8 is also a good move to include. Note that you should always watch out for the black kingside as White could put some pressure on the pawns there. However, Black's position can be very resourceful if all the pieces come into play. }
