[Black " 7.Bd3 Nbd7 8.e4 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Bd3
{ This is kind of an old move. There was some theoretical battle between Kramnik - Kasparov in the early 2000's in this line, but I believe Kramnik did not find an advantage with this move. The main idea of this move is to step out of the b7-b5 tempo, and it also prepares e4. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black decides to develop the b8-knight to d7 instead of c6. The reason behind this is that later when Black plays ...b5 and ...Bb7 the diagonal will be open for the b7-bishop. I think that the knight is more flexible on d7 than on c6, and therefore it is the right square for the knight. }
8. e4
{ White immediately cuts to the chase with the plan of e4-e5. It is a common idea in the QGA opening. White basically wants to put long-term pressure on the black kingside.   8.Qe2  b5  We would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qe2  b5  . }
8... cxd4 9. e5 Nd5
{ The knight on d5 stands very well, and it can not be chased away by a pawn. }
10. Re1 { Defending the e5-pawn, so the next move Nxd4 is possible. } 10... Nc5
{ Both knights are very well placed on d5 and c5. They are controlling a lot of squares. }
11. Nxd4 b5
{ The position is equal with chances for both sides. I think that Black has a fairly easy position thanks to the knights on d5 and c5. Next is ...Bb7, ...Rc8 and perhaps ...g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O is a smart way to finish the development. }
