[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Bd3
{ This is kind of an old move. There was some theoretical battle between Kramnik - Kasparov in the early 2000's in this line, but I believe Kramnik did not find an advantage with this move. The main idea of this move is to step out of the b7-b5 tempo, and it also prepares e4. }
7... Nbd7
{ Black decides to develop the b8-knight to d7 instead of c6. The reason behind this is that later when Black plays ...b5 and ...Bb7 the diagonal will be open for the b7-bishop. I think that the knight is more flexible on d7 than on c6, and therefore it is the right square for the knight. }
8. Re1
{ I think this move's idea is pretty clear, as White wants to push their e-pawn to e4-e5. }
8... Be7 { Black simply develops, waiting for White to start their plan. } 9.
e4
{ There are no other real alternatives for White here other than the obvious e4. Any other move would not create threats towards Black. }
9... b5
{ A novelty! No one played this move before, because it looks a little bit scary, as it gives White the opportunity to open the position with d5 before Black could even castle. However, the concrete moves confirm that Black has nothing to be afraid of here. }
10. a4 { White tries to damage the Black pawn structure. } 10... c4
{ It is almost always better to push the c-pawn after the move a4 when you can win a tempo. This move also keeps the Black pawn structure healthier than the move 11...b4. }
11. Bf1
{ A comfortable square for the bishop, however White stutters here as the bishop went from c4 to d3 and then from d3 to f1, which is not ideal. }
11... Bb7
{ Putting the bishop on the long diagonal to put pressure on the e4-pawn and also after axb5, the rook on a8 is protected. }
12. Nc3 O-O
{ I believe that this is the safest way to equalize. After  12...b4  , White would play  13.e5  which would lead to complications. }
13. axb5
{ Any other move would give Black an advantage. White has to play direct moves here otherwise Black would come out in favor. }
13... axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8
{ The queen and the bishop are very strong on the long diagonal. } 15. e5
{ White simply wants to win a pawn here with Nxb5 next move. } 15... Bxf3
{ The only way to equalize is to give up the bishop but damage the white pawn structure. }
16. gxf3 Nd5
{ The d5-knight stands very well, as it controls a lot of squares. } 17. Nxb5
{ White takes the pawn in the hope of an advantage. } 17... Bb4
{ I think Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn. White's pawn structure is damaged on the kingside, and Black has a very lovely d5-knight. Next is ...Rb8, ...Qa5 trying to put pressure on the queenside. }
