[White "27) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Nbd2"]
[Black " 6.O-O a6 7.Nbd2 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nbd2
{ A rare move. First, this move could look a little unusual, as White usually develops the b1-knight to c3 in the Queens Gambit Accepted opening. White sometimes develops the knight to d2 when it chooses the b3-Bb2 setup so that the knight would not stand in the b2-bishop's way. However, starting immediately with Nbd2 is a little tricky. White has not yet decided which direction to go for - b3-Bb2, or perhaps e4-cxd4-e5 and then Ne4. }
7... cxd4
{ Black immediately cuts to the chase with ...cxd4. I think this is the best move because it fixes the center. Black leaves White no other option than Nxd4 which will result in a solid kind of symmetrical pawn structure. There are other alternatives for Black on the 7th move like  7...Nbd7  or  7...Nc6  , but I believe that the move I'm recommending is the best. }
8. Nxd4
{ 8.exd4  would not be a good idea since the knight is already developed to d2, which is a bad square for the knight in an isolated pawn position. }
8... Bc5
{ Black immediately highlights the unprotected d4-knight. Usually, the d2-knight would stand on c3, and in that case, the move ...Bc5 would be less effective than now. }
9. N2b3
{ It looks like White wins a tempo now, but in reality, the b3-knight is misplaced. }
9... Bd6
{ Black has achieved what they wanted. The move ...Bc5 tempted the d2-knight to go to a worse place. }
10. Bd2
{ White now completes the development of their minor pieces, however, the squares are not ideal for them. The b3-knight is out of play and the c4-bishop is not doing anything now.   10.Qe2  The typical developing move with the queen would fail to an immediate tactic here.  10...e5!  11.Nf3  b5-+  Black is winning a piece here since Bd3 would be met by ...e4. }
10... O-O { Black castles and prepares to finish development. } 11. Rc1
{ A logical square for the rook, as it is controlling the c-file. } 11... b6
{ This move not only helps in the development of Black's queenside pieces, but also takes away the a5-square from the knight. Also, Black has a creative plan in mind with ...Ra7-Rc7 to develop the rook in a faster way. }
12. Qf3 { Stopping Black from developing their bishop to the long diagonal. }
12... Ra7 13. Rfd1 { White logically brings the rook into the game. } 13... Rc7
{ The position is equal with chances for both sides, but I prefer Black in the long run. The white pieces are a little bit awkwardly placed, the knight on b3 still has no real purpose, and the bishop on d2 seems to find no good diagonal. Note that delaying the b8-knight's development is not necessarily a bad idea since it guards the a6-pawn and the c6-square. Black's next moves are ...Bb7, ...Qc8, ...Rd8. }
