{ Black prefers to exchange some pieces so that the d4-pawn will be worth taking.  15...Rxd4?!  Taking the pawn would only help White in this position.  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.Qc2=∞  I think White has more than enough compensation for the pawn here with having the bishop pair. }
16. Nxf6+
{ White is forced to take otherwise the d4-pawn would eventually fall. } 16...
Qxf6 17. Bxb7 Rxb7
{ I think it is pretty clear that positionally Black is doing very well here, the only problem is the b8-knight and its development. }
18. Rc1
{ Logically placing the rook on the open c-file.  18.d5??  Would fail to an immediate tactical reason.  18...b4-+  Trapping the bishop. }
18... h6
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I think that if Black is able to solve the problem with its b8-knight, then the Black position would become so stable that losing the game would be hard to imagine. Note that Black should always watch out for the d5 breakthrough. }
