[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Nbd2"]
[Black " 6.O-O a6 7.Nbd2 cxd4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nbd2
{ A rare move. First, this move could look a little unusual, as White usually develops the b1-knight to c3 in the Queens Gambit Accepted opening. White sometimes develops the knight to d2 when it chooses the b3-Bb2 setup so that the knight would not stand in the b2-bishop's way. However, starting immediately with Nbd2 is a little tricky. White has not yet decided which direction to go for - b3-Bb2, or perhaps e4-cxd4-e5 and then Ne4. }
7... cxd4
{ Black immediately cuts to the chase with ...cxd4. I think this is the best move because it fixes the center. Black leaves White no other option than Nxd4 which will result in a solid kind of symmetrical pawn structure. There are other alternatives for Black on the 7th move like  7...Nbd7  or  7...Nc6  , but I believe that the move I'm recommending is the best. }
8. Nxd4
{ 8.exd4  would not be a good idea since the knight is already developed to d2, which is a bad square for the knight in an isolated pawn position. }
8... Bc5
{ Black immediately highlights the unprotected d4-knight. Usually, the d2-knight would stand on c3, and in that case, the move ...Bc5 would be less effective than now. }
9. b3
{ This is one of the core ideas of the 7. Nbd2 line. White seems to sacrifice a pawn on d4 @@StartBracket@@but it is not good the accept this sacrifice@@EndBracket@@. If Black just simply ignores the d4 knight then White would go Bb2-Rc1 and claim that the bishop on c5 is misplaced. }
9... Bxd4 { The best move, which leads to a quite complicated position. } 10.
exd4 O-O
{ Now we have reached a rather unusual situation. White has the typical isolated pawn, but their pieces are unusually placed. The knight on d2 usually stands on c3 in the isolated pawn structure positions to sometimes help d5-breakthrough, but here it has another purpose  @@StartBracket@@the mainline will show what that is@@EndBracket@@. The bishop on c1 will develop either to b2 or a3 which is very unusual with having an isolated pawn. However, Black had to give up the bishop pair to reach this position, and that is what makes the position complex. }
11. Ba3
{ I believe this move is the right path for White, as here Black has to make a couple of good moves to keep their position together. }
11... Re8
{ Now the a3-bishop looks a little lost, as it seems that White has no follow-up, but here White can show the purpose of the d2-knight. }
12. Bd3
{ This is the critical move of the line. I think the bishop is standing better on d3 than on e2, because it is preparing Ne4/Nc4, and also White can use Re1 more conveniently. }
12... Nc6
{ I think this is the best move. There was a game between two super grandmasters Le, Quang Liem - Magnus, Carlsen Rapid 2022, where Magnus went  12...Bd7  a novelty, but I believe Black's position would have been dangerous after  13.Nc4  Bc6  14.Rc1  .   12...Qxd4  Taking the pawn immediately will most likely transfer to the mainlines, but White has extra options compared to the move after  12...Nc6  , so I think  12...Qxd4  is slightly less accurate.  13.Nc4  Nc6  . }
13. Nc4
{ White has to grab the momentum and play Nc4 since Black could not prevent it with @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/1p3ppp/p3pn2/8/3P4/BP1B4/P2N1PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 4 12@@EndFEN@@  12...b5  because of  13.Ne4  . }
13... Qxd4
{ Black is forced to take the pawn because Nd6 would come with too many threats. }
14. Bb2
{ White uses the long diagonal to get good compensation for the pawn. It is logical because this move comes with a tempo as well.  14.Qe2  This move is too slow and is not really threatening with anything concrete.  14...e5⩱  Black is better, thanks to the material advantage. Next is ...Bg4 developing with a tempo. }
14... Qh4
{ Black has to keep defending the f6-knight, otherwise White could destroy Black's safe king with Bxd6. }
15. g3 { It is logical to keep chasing the queen to a worse square. } 15... Qh6
{ Now the position may look a little shaky for Black, but Black is still a pawn up and White does not have a concrete way to win the material back. }
16. Re1
{ White decides to take it slow, and just play for long-term positional compensation. }
16... Rd8 { Pinning the d3-bishop and getting out of the Nd6 tempo. } 17. h4
{ This move is trying to highlight the misplaced queen on h6, as Qh3 is no longer possible for Black. }
17... b5
{ An important move. Black has to play forcefully, otherwise, the two bishops will overrule the material advantage. The next couple of moves are forced for both sides. }
18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Nxc8 Rbxc8
{ The position is equal with chances for both sides. I believe that exchanging the c8-bishop for the c4- knight definitely benefits Black. However White still has enough compensation for equality because of the bishop pair and the awkwardly placed queen on h6. If White plays  20.Rc1  , then  20...e5  is a good move to close the b2-bishop's diagonal. }
*

