{ As in the line of @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/1p3ppp/p1n1pn2/8/2Nq4/BP1B4/P4PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Bb2  , Black places their queen on the h-file. }
16. Nd6
{ White has to play concrete moves otherwise the compensation would evaporate. }
16... Rd8 17. Qc5
{ A good move and its main idea is to step out of the Nd4 tempo. } 17... h6
{ A very useful waiting move. Black opens the final rank, which can be beneficial later in the game. }
18. Bc4
{ Now White wants to do the same as after @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/1p3ppp/p1nN1n2/4p3/7q/BP1B4/P1Q2PPP/3R1RK1 w - - 4 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Bc4  , ...Nd4 will not come with tempo. }
18... Be6
{ Black is forced to defend the f7-pawn. The following moves are quite logical and forced for both colors. }
19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Nxb7
{ Taking a pawn, and equalizing the material. The position may look rather unpleasant for Black here, as it seems that the position is collapsing because of the weak pawns, but no! Black can now start an attack against the white king! }
20... Nd4
{ Bringing the knight into the attack, disregarding the d8-rook. Black's attack is coming very fast with ...Ne2-Ng4, and White has no real defense against that. }
21. Nxd8
{ White's best option is to take the material and hope that the kingside holds together. }
21... Ne2+ 22. Kh1 Ng4
{ The queen and the knights are very well coordinated with each other against the white king. The threat is clear, Qxh2. }
23. Qf8+ Kh7 24. h3
{ It seems that White has everything figured out, and Black is losing here. However, here comes the brilliant move on which this whole line is based. }
24... Qg3 25. fxg3 Nxg3+ 26. Kg1 Ne2+ { Repetition. } *

