[White "28) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Nc3"]
[Black "7.Nc3 b5 8.Bb3 Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3
{ This move also leads to one of the mainlines in the QGA. Other than developing a piece, White wants to eventually use the c3-knight to help the e4/d5 breakthrough in the center. }
7... b5
{ As often, Black wins a tempo like this, to help develop their pieces on the queenside. }
8. Bb3
{ I don't prefer the b3-square for White in these structures, because I believe it has relatively zero purpose in most middlegame positions. }
8... Bb7 9. Re1
{ I think the combination of Bb3 and Re1 is kind of unusual here.  9.Qe2  Transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qe2  b5  8.Bb3  Bb7  9.Nc3  seen here. }
9... Nc6
{ This is one of those few positions where I would recommend developing the knight to c6 so White cannot play e4. I think Black already has a pleasant position here. Next is ...Bd6, ...O-O. }
