1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3
{ This move also leads to one of the mainlines in the QGA. Other than developing a piece, White wants to eventually use the c3-knight to help the e4/d5 breakthrough in the center. }
7... b5
{ As often, Black wins a tempo like this, to help develop their pieces on the queenside. }
8. Bb3
{ I don't prefer the b3-square for White in these structures, because I believe it has relatively zero purpose in most middlegame positions. }
8... Bb7 9. e4
{ This is the best option for White here. It is a pawn sacrifice or rather a trap. Usually in the QGA when White plays e4, Black should rather avoid grabbing the e4-pawn because that would give White a great deal of attack. }
9... cxd4
{ As I mentioned in other lines that when White takes the center, it is a good idea to exchange one of the white central pawns. }
10. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Again, Black has to choose development over the e4-pawn. I suggest this move over  10...Nbd7  @@StartBracket@@which is also a very playable move@@EndBracket@@ because now the position gets forced. White has to create some kind of a play, but it's not easy. }
11. Nxc6 { This exchange leads to a quite drawish endgame. } 11... Qxd1
{ The easiest way to equalize is to exchange the queens. } 12. Rxd1 Bxc6 13. f3
{ Now White has a very stable position, however with the queens traded off the board, Black has to be totally fine here. }
13... Bc5+ { Developing with a tempo. } 14. Kf1 Ke7
{ This endgame is equal with relatively low chances for both sides. I think the move  15.e5  would only make a permanent weakness for White after  15...Nd7  16.Bg5  Ke8  , therefore I would not be afraid of that. Next is ...Rhc8. }
