Bxe5 Qxe5
{ Now, the knight on g5 is under attack, and if White decides to retreat it, then Black would have a comfortable position after ...Qe7. }
19. Bf3
{ The best move for White, opting for the exchange of the strong b7-bishop that is ruling the long diagonal, just like Black did with the white bishop on b2. }
19... Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Qe7 { Black has to keep protecting the c5-pawn. } 21. Qc4
Rfc8
{ The position is balanced with chances for both sides. White nicely set up a blockade against the Black queenside pawns, however, Black still has play on the queenside. For example, Ne4-Nc3 is a common idea, where the knight would find an excellent place. If the c4-queen moves, later on, Black oftentimes has an idea of sacrificing a pawn with c5-c4, forcing White to take with bxc4, and then the strong b4 passed pawn would give compensation for the pawn. }
