17... Qxf6 18. Rac1
{ White's plan is quite simple with Nd2-Bf3-Nc4. Note that if White could exchange its e2-bishop to the b7-bishop then the light squares would sometimes become vulnerable for Black. }
18... Rad8 { Developing the rook on the open file. } 19. Nd2
{ White continues with the plan of Bf3-Nc4. } 19... Be7
{ The bishop stands well on e7, as it keeps protecting the c5-pawn, and also opens the d-file for the rook. }
20. Nc4
{ This is the right square for the knight, as there is no way to chase it away from c4. However, now the c5-pawn is not under pressure anymore.   20.Bf3  A logical move, since White wants to play for the light squares, however, Black can have the chance to look for counterplay.  20...Bxf3!  This is one of those positions where exchanging the bishops is good for Black, because of concrete reasons.  21.Nxf3  Rxd1+!  22.Rxd1  Qc3=  The queen finds an excellent place on c3. The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. The black queenside pawns can be dangerous. }
20... g6
{ Opening the final rank for the king. The position is balanced with chances for both sides. I believe that despite the strong c4-knight which blocks the Black queenside pawns, the position is fine for Black, because of the bishop pair and the c3-square. Black can often use the c3-square for their queen later on. Next is ...Rxd1-Rd8 exchanging the rooks. }
