10. Nxd5 Bb7 { Placing the bishop on the long diagonal with tempo. } 11. Nxf6+
{ White has to take and start opening the position more. } 11... Qxf6
{ It is important not to trade queens with  11...Nxf6  because after  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.a4  Black would be underdeveloped, and therefore White would have the advantage. }
12. a4
{ This is in the spirit of the position. White goes for weakening Black's queenside. }
12... b4
{ The only way to a balanced middlegame. Black has to keep the queenside closed here. Unfortunately, Black is not able to hold their nice pawn structure on the queenside because of concrete reasons.  12...Qc6  If Black were to defend b5 via ...Qc6, it would not work out well, because of the development disadvantage.  13.axb5  axb5  14.Rxa8+  Bxa8  15.Qd3±  Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. The position is too open, and therefore Black is worse. }
13. Qc2
{ A solid approach. This move has two ideas, one is that it prepares the move e4 and the second is that b3-Bb2 is going to be a serious possibility from now on. There was a game between Gledura, B - Bacrot, E, European Team 2021, where I successfully won the game. Super GM Wesley, So introduced me to this move, as he won a very nice game in 2018. }
13... Bd6
{ This is a very logical developing move. The black bishops are now eyeing the white king, which is ideal. }
14. Rd1
{ Initially, when I prepared this line with the white side, this Rd1 move was my idea. Now White puts pressure on the d6-bishop and the d7-knight. }
14... Qe7
{ Black has to retreat the queen, so their pieces are defended against the Qd2/Qd3 threats. ...Qe7 also steps out of the b2-Bb2 tempo. }
15. b3
{ White is simply planning to develop the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal. }
15... Nf6
{ Black has to first get one of their pieces out of the d-file, so White cannot put more pressure on them with moves like Qd2/Qd3. }
16. Bb2 { White simply develops the bishop on the long diagonal. } 16... O-O
{ Black finally castles. Now we have reached a quite interesting middlegame position, where White has several ways to go. In general, the white pawn structure is better than Black's because the queenside pawns are fixed and White has a lovely c4-square, however, Black compensates for that with their nice bishops on d6 and b7. }
17. Bc4
{ A nice place for the bishop. We can see that both White bishops are pretty well placed, as they are eyeing the Black kingside. However the bishop leaves the white kingside, therefore it can become vulnerable. }
17... Rad8
{ Black logically develops the rook to the d-file. Sooner or later, the black pieces could create an attack against the white king. Therefore, White has to solve their kingside issues. }
18. Qe2
{ A logical move that attacks the a6-pawn, and protects the f3-knight as well.   18.Ng5  This ambitious move would fail to an immediate tactic.  18...Bxh2+!  19.Kxh2  Ng4+!  Highlighting the fact that the g5-knight is undefended.  20.Kg3  Qxg5-+  . }
18... a5
{ Black simply moves the a-pawn and plans to play ...Ne4 next. Since the queen is no longer eyeing the Black king from c2, there is no Ng5 mate threat. }
