[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3
{ This move also leads to one of the mainlines in the QGA. Other than developing a piece, White wants to eventually use the c3-knight to help the e4/d5 breakthrough in the center. }
7... b5
{ As often, Black wins a tempo like this, to help develop their pieces on the queenside. }
8. Be2
{ I believe this is the best place for the bishop. I think this position requires some explanation. If you study the QGA middlegame positions carefully, you will notice that White frequently takes on c5 and exchanges the queens to have a safe and slightly more comfortable endgame. Now if Black plays  8...Bb7  or  8...Nc6  , White has the opportunity to go for an endgame again with  9.dxc5  , and in that endgame, the b7-b5 move would be a little bit premature here, as it would let White weaken the queenside with a4 later on. You will especially understand my point here when you go through the 7.dxc5 line, and compare those endgame positions with the one here. }
8... Nbd7
{ A very important move, as here White does not have the opportunity to exchange the queens with dxc5. Note that this position could occur with the move order of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  Nbd7  8.Nc3  b5  . }
9. d5
{ This is the critical move of the whole line. White unbalances the central pawns and tries to open the position, as it favors White because of the development advantage. }
9... exd5
{ Black has to take, otherwise White would damage the Black pawn structure with dxe6. }
10. Nxd5 Bb7 { Placing the bishop on the long diagonal with tempo. } 11. Nxf6+
{ White has to take and start opening the position more. } 11... Qxf6
