12... b4
{ The only way to a balanced middlegame. Black has to keep the queenside closed here. Unfortunately, Black is not able to hold their nice pawn structure on the queenside because of concrete reasons.  12...Qc6  If Black were to defend b5 via ...Qc6, it would not work out well, because of the development disadvantage.  13.axb5  axb5  14.Rxa8+  Bxa8  15.Qd3±  Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. The position is too open, and therefore Black is worse. }
13. e4
{ A creative move. White intends to open the position. It is not a pawn sacrifice, as after  13...Bxe4  14.Re1  would create serious issues for Black. }
13... h6
{ Black has to stop White from playing Bg5, which would come with a tempo. }
14. Bc4
{ Super GM Vladimir, Kramnik has employed this move a few years ago, therefore I think it is worth knowing how to handle this. White's idea is to play Bd5. }
14... Bd6
{ The right square for the bishop, as it covers the d7-knight, so on the next move, Black can castle. }
15. Bd5
{ White intends to exchange the light-squared bishops and weaken the light squares in Black's position. }
15... Bxd5
{ This is the only way to get an advantage, all the other moves would lead to a worse position for Black. Super GM Sergey Karjakin has played  15...O-O-O?!  , which resulted in a very sharp middlegame. }
16. Qxd5 O-O
{ Black can castle! This is the key move. I believe Kramnik relied on Karjakin not knowing that castling is possible, because of  17.Rd1  seems to win a piece, but it's not! }
17. Rd1 Ne5
{ The position is winning for Black! The d6-bishop is not under attack because  18.Qxd6  would lose to  18...Rad8  , winning the d1-rook. }
