[White "28) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Nc3"]
[Black "8.Be2 Nbd7 9.d5 exd5 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Nc3
{ This move also leads to one of the mainlines in the QGA. Other than developing a piece, White wants to eventually use the c3-knight to help the e4/d5 breakthrough in the center. }
7... b5
{ As often, Black wins a tempo like this, to help develop their pieces on the queenside. }
8. Be2
{ I believe this is the best place for the bishop. I think this position requires some explanation. If you study the QGA middlegame positions carefully, you will notice that White frequently takes on c5 and exchanges the queens to have a safe and slightly more comfortable endgame. Now if Black plays  8...Bb7  or  8...Nc6  , White has the opportunity to go for an endgame again with  9.dxc5  , and in that endgame, the b7-b5 move would be a little bit premature here, as it would let White weaken the queenside with a4 later on. You will especially understand my point here when you go through the 7.dxc5 line, and compare those endgame positions with the one here. }
8... Nbd7
{ A very important move, as here White does not have the opportunity to exchange the queens with dxc5. Note that this position could occur with the move order of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Be2  Nbd7  8.Nc3  b5  . }
9. d5
{ This is the critical move of the whole line. White unbalances the central pawns and tries to open the position, as it favors White because of the development advantage. }
9... exd5
{ Black has to take, otherwise White would damage the Black pawn structure with dxe6. }
10. Nxd5 Bb7 { Placing the bishop on the long diagonal with tempo. } 11. Nxf6+
{ White has to take and start opening the position more. } 11... Qxf6
{ It is important not to trade queens with  11...Nxf6  because after  12.Qxd8  Rxd8  13.a4  Black would be underdeveloped, and therefore White would have the advantage. }
12. a4
{ This is in the spirit of the position. White goes for weakening Black's queenside. }
12... b4
{ The only way to a balanced middlegame. Black has to keep the queenside closed here. Unfortunately, Black is not able to hold their nice pawn structure on the queenside because of concrete reasons.  12...Qc6  If Black were to defend b5 via ...Qc6, it would not work out well, because of the development disadvantage.  13.axb5  axb5  14.Rxa8+  Bxa8  15.Qd3±  Putting pressure on the b5-pawn. The position is too open, and therefore Black is worse. }
13. e4
{ A creative move. White intends to open the position. It is not a pawn sacrifice, as after  13...Bxe4  14.Re1  would create serious issues for Black. }
13... h6
{ Black has to stop White from playing Bg5, which would come with a tempo. }
14. Ra2
{ This move looks a little slow, but it is kind of a logical move. What wants to develop its pieces in a slightly unique way with b3-Rd2, where the rook would put pressure on the d-file. }
14... O-O-O
{ Black goes for long castles here. It is quite an unusual way to handle this position, however, here it works out well because the a2-rook is slightly awkwardly placed. }
15. b3
{ White continues with the plan of developing the rook to the d-file, therefore Black has to handle that. }
15... Bd6
{ The best square for the bishop, as it usually is in this line. Now the bishop is eyeing the white king. }
16. Be3 Rhe8 { Bringing the last piece into play, attacking the e4-pawn. } 17.
Nd2
{ 17.Rd2  This logical move would not work out so well.  17...Bc7⩱  Black simply gets out of the d-file, and now White has difficulties protecting the e4-pawn. }
17... Bc7
{ The bishop stands better on c7, as later when Black moves its d7-knight, the d-file will be open for its d8-rook. }
18. Qc2 Kb8
{ Getting out of the c-file. Black has a very good position and is better. The a2-rook is misplaced. Next is ...g5! which starts a nice attack against the white king. }
