[Black " 7.Qe2 b5 8.Bd3 Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2
{ This move gives space for the f1-rook to d1, and it also helps White to play e4 in certain positions. }
7... b5
{ Black immediately uses the momentum and wins a tempo which helps in developing their pieces with Bb7-Nbd7. }
8. Bd3
{ The d3-square is usually better for the bishop in the QGA than the b3-square, however, the bishop on the d-file will block the file for the d1-rook later on, which is not ideal. }
8... Nbd7
{ Not the most common move, but I think the most logical. I think it is better to start with ...Nbd7 rather than ...Bb7 because White cannot really play dxc5-Rd1, since Nxc5 would target the d3-bishop right away. }
9. Nc3
{ Now we officially transposed to The Slav defense, but fortunately this line is a good line for Black. @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nf3  Nf6  4.Nc3  e6  5.e3  Nbd7  6.Bd3  dxc4  7.Bxc4  b5  8.Bd3  a6  9.O-O  c5  10.Qe2  .@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bb7 { Simply placing the bishop on the long diagonal, where it belongs. }
10. Rd1
{ I think this is the only move that puts pressure on Black, as it prepares the breakthrough in the center with e4. }
10... Qc7
{ Black steps out of the d1-rook's radar. The black queen usually stands very well on the h2-b8 diagonal in these middlegames. }
11. e4
{ White has to continue with the plan in the center, otherwise Black would have a comfortable position with simply finishing developing. }
11... cxd4
{ It is important to remove one of White's central pawns because White was planning to go d5 or e5. }
12. Nxd4 Bd6
{ The position is slightly better for Black. The harmony between the black pieces is great. Next is ...Qb8, ...O-O. Note that White sometimes threatens Bxb5-axb5-Ndxb5 double attacking the d6-bishop and the queen. Therefore, it is often smart to step out of that tactic with ...Qb8. }
