[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Qe2"]
[Black " 7.Qe2 b5 8.Bd3 Nbd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2
{ This move gives space for the f1-rook to d1, and it also helps White to play e4 in certain positions. }
7... b5
{ Black immediately uses the momentum and wins a tempo which helps in developing their pieces with Bb7-Nbd7. }
8. Bd3
{ The d3-square is usually better for the bishop in the QGA than the b3-square, however, the bishop on the d-file will block the file for the d1-rook later on, which is not ideal. }
8... Nbd7
{ Not the most common move, but I think the most logical. I think it is better to start with ...Nbd7 rather than ...Bb7 because White cannot really play dxc5-Rd1, since Nxc5 would target the d3-bishop right away. }
9. Rd1
{ White here continues its plan by placing the rook on the d-file, so it can later put pressure on Black. }
9... Bb7 10. dxc5
{ White logically opens the d-file, as the d1-rook faces the d8-queen.  10.a4  This move would not be appropriate here, as it lets Black close the position with  10...c4!  11.Bc2  Be7=  Black has a fairly comfortable position. Next is ...O-O and start putting pressure on the queenside. }
10... Bxc5
{ Unfortunately, Black could not take on c5 with the d7-knight because of an immediate tactic with Bxb5. However, Black's position remains healthy nevertheless. }
11. a4
{ White wants to weaken the black queenside pawn structure, which is a very common idea in this opening. }
11... bxa4
{ The best move! Black has another option with  11...b4  , however that would give up the very important c4-square, thus White could use that with Nbd2-Nc4, and later go b3-Bb2, which would be unpleasant to face for Black. }
12. Rxa4 O-O
{ Black focuses on finishing development rather than losing a tempo by protecting the a6-pawn. }
13. Bxa6
{ If White decides not to grab the hanging pawn, then it can hope for nothing better than equality. }
13... Bc6
{ Black has to keep the pieces on the board and try to create compensation against the awkwardly placed a6-bishop and a4-rook. }
14. Ra1
{ 14.Rh4!?  The white rook wanders to unusual places on the h-file. Black now has the chance to damage the white pawn structure with  14...Bxf3!  giving up the bishop pair but weakens the white king.  15.gxf3  Qb6=∞  At first sight, it could seem that Black does not have sufficient compensation, however, the more you look, the clearer it becomes that Black in fact has. The h4-rook is misplaced, just the a6-bishop. White's kingside pawn structure is damaged, and the b1-c1 pieces are not developed, whereas all Black's pieces are in play. Next is ...Ne5. }
14... Qb8
{ Black has more than enough compensation here, as the a6-bishop is pinned and the Black pieces are very well placed and in harmony. }
