[White "29) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.Qe2"]
[Black " 7.Qe2 b5 8.Bd3 Nbd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2
{ This move gives space for the f1-rook to d1, and it also helps White to play e4 in certain positions. }
7... b5
{ Black immediately uses the momentum and wins a tempo which helps in developing their pieces with Bb7-Nbd7. }
8. Bd3
{ The d3-square is usually better for the bishop in the QGA than the b3-square, however, the bishop on the d-file will block the file for the d1-rook later on, which is not ideal. }
8... Nbd7
{ Not the most common move, but I think the most logical. I think it is better to start with ...Nbd7 rather than ...Bb7 because White cannot really play dxc5-Rd1, since Nxc5 would target the d3-bishop right away. }
9. a4
{ The most played move and for a good reason. White tries to make the black queenside pawns vulnerable. }
9... c4
{ Again, Black has to keep the queenside pawn structure healthy, and this move keeps it healthy. The move  9...b4  would give up the c4-square, therefore White could play  10.Nbd2  , planning Nc4, which would give a nice outpost for the knight. }
10. Bc2 Bb7 11. b3
{ A fairly typical move that intends to explode the whole queenside pawn structure. Therefore Black has to make some accurate moves to get a balanced middlegame. }
11... cxb3
{ There is nothing better than to make concrete, forced moves here. } 12. Bxb3
Be7
{ Black disregards the 'hanging' b5-pawn and rather develops. Development is very important for Black here, as White has already put their king to safety, therefore there is no time for Black to keep delaying castling their king. }
13. axb5
{ I think there is no other way to make the position complicated other than this forcing move. If White disregards the complications arising with this move, then Black would simply finish development with ...O-O and would have a comfortable middlegame. }
13... axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8
{ Now we understand that the b5-pawn was not really hanging, as 14. Rxa8 was forced, therefore the f3-knight will hang as well. }
15. Qxb5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qxf3
{ Black comes out fine from the complications, as the white king is vulnerable. Black's position is very stable. Next is ...O-O or ...Qh3. }
