[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. Qe2
{ This move gives space for the f1-rook to d1, and it also helps White to play e4 in certain positions. }
7... b5
{ Black immediately uses the momentum and wins a tempo which helps in developing their pieces with Bb7-Nbd7. }
8. Bd3
{ The d3-square is usually better for the bishop in the QGA than the b3-square, however, the bishop on the d-file will block the file for the d1-rook later on, which is not ideal. }
8... Nbd7
{ Not the most common move, but I think the most logical. I think it is better to start with ...Nbd7 rather than ...Bb7 because White cannot really play dxc5-Rd1, since Nxc5 would target the d3-bishop right away. }
9. a4
{ The most played move and for a good reason. White tries to make the black queenside pawns vulnerable. }
9... c4
{ Again, Black has to keep the queenside pawn structure healthy, and this move keeps it healthy. The move  9...b4  would give up the c4-square, therefore White could play  10.Nbd2  , planning Nc4, which would give a nice outpost for the knight. }
10. Bc2 Bb7 11. e4
{ This is a critical move. White takes the center, and thus keeps the pressure on Black. }
11... Be7
{ A simple but important move. Black must finish their kingside development as soon as possible, otherwise White's developed pieces would cause problems for Black. }
12. Rd1 O-O
{ Black finally castles. Now White has to come up with a creative plan otherwise the healthy Black position will rule. }
13. Ng5
{ This is the only move that makes Black solve real issues. It threatens e5 to win the h7-pawn.   13.Nbd2  This simple developing move would not put any pressure on Black.  13...Qc7=  The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. Black's position is very healthy, and stable. Next is ...Rac8, ...b4. }
13... h6 14. Nh3
{ The maneuver Ng5-Nh3 may look slightly odd, however, it has its own idea. White plans to play e5, and after ...Nd5, Qe4 would come with a mate threat. Also, the move ...h6 is generally not ideal for Black as the c1-bishop could sometimes be sacrificed there. }
14... Qb6
{ Black has to act quickly. This queen-developing move has an important part in Black's defense. }
15. e5
{ White has to continue the attack, otherwise, the plan of Ng5-Nh3 would be useless. }
15... Qc6
{ A very important in-between move. As it is quite clear, putting the queen on the long diagonal was the idea of the move ...Qb6. It creates counterplay, and now Black is the one attacking the white king! }
16. Nf4 Nd5
{ There is a huge difference between the moves 15...Nd5 and 16...Nd5. Black now again threatens ...Nxf4-Qxg2, therefore White has only one way to play this position. }
17. Qe4 f5
{ This is the only move that saves Black, but it does! The following couple of moves are quite forced for both sides. }
18. exf6 N7xf6 19. Qxe6+
{ White has no better move than to exchange the queens and win the pawn. }
19... Qxe6 20. Nxe6 Rfb8
{ A very important final move. All the black pieces are in play, and therefore Black has enough compensation for equality. The d5-knight is very well placed, blocking the isolated d4-pawn. Additionally, the white queenside is undeveloped, therefore the powerful pawns on c4-b5-a6 give back serious play. Next is ...b4-Bc6. }
