{ This move gives space for the f1-rook to d1, and it also helps White to play e4 in certain positions. }
7... b5
{ Black immediately uses the momentum and wins a tempo which helps in developing their pieces with Bb7-Nbd7. }
8. Bb3
{ I believe this move fits the 7. Qe2 line more than Bd3, as it will not block the d-file for the rook later on. However, the a2-g8 diagonal is usually not useful for the bishop. }
8... Bb7 9. Rd1
{ 9.a4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bb3  b5  8.a4  Bb7  9.Qe2  . }
9... Nbd7
{ Black chooses the typical setup. Black's plan is quite simple with ...Bd6, ...O-O. }
10. Nc3
{ This is the mainline of the 7. Qe2 line. White prepares the move e4 as in most lines. Note that the idea behind delaying the move e4 for White is that if Black takes  10...cxd4  now, then White could take back with  11.exd4!  and get an advantage. }
10... Bd6
{ This is by the far not the most common move, but I believe it's the best. It limits White's options, as White has no better plan than to try to unbalance the center with e4. }
11. e4
{ White takes over the center now, and that means that Black has to get rid of one of the central pawns. }
11... cxd4 12. Rxd4
{ The rook immediately puts pressure on the pieces standing on the file d-file, therefore Black has to find the only move which does not give White an advantage. }
12... Bc5
{ A natural but important move. This is the only move that saves Black from trouble, as it comes with a tempo. }
13. Rd1
{ I believe that it's clear that Rxd4-Rd1 should not be good for White, as to keep moving with the same piece in the opening is usually bad. }
13... Ng4
{ Immediately attacking the f2-pawn. The knight on g4 is often a very powerful piece as it not only attacks the f2-pawn but also will find a nice place on e5 later on. }
14. Bg5
{ This is a logical developing move that attacks the queen. However, there, the f2-pawn is not protected now, and Black can make use of that. }
14... Nxf2
{ A very important move. All the other alternatives would lead to a worse position for Black but this. This is a queen sacrifice but Black will get a great deal of compensation for the exchange. }
15. Bxd8 Nxd1+ 16. Kf1 Ne3+ 17. Ke1 Rxd8
{ This position is sort of forced after 14. Bg5. Now the material is very unbalanced, but I think it favors Black. The knight on e3 is rather an asset than a weakness. The bishop pair, especially the c5-bishop is very powerful. The White king on e1 is questionable. I think that Black has more than enough compensation here. Note that the next few couples of moves could determine the whole outcome of the game, therefore they will probably require some accurate calculation. Next is ...O-O or ...Ng4, however, White has a lot of ways to play, therefore it is hard to suggest a fixed move for Black here. What I would suggest is to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. }
