13. Rd3
{ This is a slightly unusual square for the rook, but its idea is that after developing the c1 bishop, the rook from a1 can go to d1 and put even more pressure on the d-file. }
13... Qc7
{ Usually, the queens stand well on the h2-b8 diagonal, as I mentioned in some other lines as well.   13...Ng4  This tempting move does not work out as well as it promises, because White has a creative way to play.  14.Bg5  Qb6  15.Nd5→  This is a very strong move, which makes chaos in the center, therefore I would not recommend going for this. }
14. e5
{ White has to make concrete moves, otherwise Black would be better after completing development. }
14... Ng4 { Putting pressure on the f2-pawn. } 15. Ne4
{ This is White's idea. First, it could seem that White blunders as  15...Bxe4  is possible, but that would run into a trap because  16.Qxe4  would be a double attack on the g4-knight and  a8  rook. }
15... Ndxe5
{ The only move that makes the position complicated, but balanced. Now White has to show where the compensation for the pawn is. }
16. Bf4
{ Pinning the knight, which can be very unpleasant for Black. Fortunately, there is a way to step out of this pin. }
16... Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Qc6
{ Black has successfully stepped out of the f4-bishop's pin by counter-attacking the e4-queen. Now again, White has to prove that there is compensation for the pawn. }
18. Qxc6+ Nxc6 19. Rc3
{ White has to keep attacking the black pieces, otherwise, the material unbalance would favor Black. }
19... Bxf2+ { The only move, but winning another pawn. } 20. Kf1
{ Now White not only threatens to take the c6-knight but also threatens h3, winning one of the pieces. Luckily, Black has a tactical resource that helps to save the material. The following moves are forced for both colors. }
20... Na5 21. h3 Nf6
{ A very important move that works out well for Black. If it was not for this move then White would simply be winning. }
22. Kxf2 Ne4+ { A double attack which wins material. } 23. Ke2 Nxc3+ 24. bxc3
Rc8
{ This endgame is roughly equal with chances for both sides. Personally, I like Black here since there are two pawns and a rook against the light pieces, however, the white bishop pair can be powerful. Note that if you can exchange one of the bishops that would benefit Black. Next is ...O-O, ...Rfd8. }
