[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30) 3.Nf3  Nf6 4.e3 7.dxc5"]
[Black "7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ We have arrived at the endgame line. White's intention is to play a solid, long game and try to claim that the upcoming endgame is better for them. This line has been quite popular amongst super GMs, therefore a lot of people started to go for this endgame. However, I believe that if Black makes a couple of accurate moves, the endgame should be equal. }
7... Bxc5
{ I recommend this move over  7...Qxd1  because I believe that bringing the white rook to d1 is not ideal. I would rather have White trade queens, because in an endgame the fact that Black will not be able to castle is not very important, since the king on e7 will be perfectly safe. }
8. Qxd8+
{ 8.Qe2  Nbd7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.Qe2  a6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  Nbd7  seen here. }
8... Kxd8
{ Now White has a couple of possibilities. The only thing that is certain for White is to move the c4-bishop, as Black threatens to play ...b5-Bb7, which would significantly help Black's position. Generally speaking, Black wants to place their pieces like ...Ke7-Nbd7-b5/b6 and Bb7. White has to create an unbalanced game, otherwise, the position would be too drawish. }
9. b3
{ A solid approach. White simply wants to develop with Bb2-Nbd2. However, I think it is too slow to create problems for Black. }
9... Ke7
{ Black has to get the king away from the d-file, and then start developing minor pieces. }
10. Bb2 Nbd7
{ The knight finds a nice, flexible place on d7. Next is to develop the c8-bishop. }
11. Nbd2
{ White continues the development and gets ready to bring the rooks into the game. }
11... b6
{ It is better to be solid here with b6, rather than to go b5, which would slightly backfire for Black in the future, as White could always bother the b5-pawn with a4. }
12. Rfd1 { The most natural move is placing the rook on the half-open d-file. }
12... Bb7
{ Simply continuing the development and getting ready to bring rooks into play with Rac8-Rfd8. }
13. Be2
{ The bishop on c4 was not ideal for White, as it had no real purpose. Now the bishop on e2 can sometimes go to f3 later on. It also prepares the plan of Ne1-Nd3 to target the c5-bishop. }
13... Rhc8
{ I think this is the most accurate move. White is planning to transfer its knight to d3 via e1, and bother the c5-bishop, therefore playing Kf8-Be7 is the best to save the bishop pair. }
14. Ne1
{ This is a very common maneuver in these types of endgames. Transferring the knight to d3 is a very smart way to make the position unsymmetrical. }
14... Kf8
{ This is the idea behind @@StartFEN@@r6r/1b1nkppp/pp2pn2/2b5/8/1P2PN2/PB1NBPPP/R2R2K1 b - - 3 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rhc8  , if Black were to play  13...Rac8  14.Ne1  Kf8  , then the h8-rook would be left out. }
15. Nd3 Be7
{ Black saves its bishop pair, and keeps the position balanced. I think White has not achieved what they wanted. If White plays Rac1, then trading the rook would make the position even more drawish. }
*

