{ A logical move that steps out of the b7-b5 tempo. If Black would want to develop with  9...b5  , @@StartBracket@@ planning 10...Bb7@@EndBracket@@ then  10.a4  would weaken the Black queenside.   @@StartFEN@@rnbk3r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2b5/2B5/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNB2RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5   9.Nbd2  Ke7  10.Be2  .  9...Ke7  10.Be2  . }
9... Ke7
{ Black has to first put their king on e7 so White can no longer play Rd1 with a tempo, and then start developing their queenside pieces. }
10. Nbd2
{ This is definitely one of the mainlines of the whole 7.dxc5 line. White intends to either develop with b3-Bb2 or Nb3-Bd2. }
10... Bd7
{ Now, Black has to change their development routine. Usually, I would suggest developing with ...b6-Bb7-Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@which I think would be slightly inaccurate@@EndBracket@@, however here ...Bd7 has a specific reason. Black oftentimes wants to exchange the light-squared bishops via b5. }
11. Nb3
{ The knight's intention is to chase the bishop away and later possibly go  Na5  to bother the b7-pawn.  11.Nc4  Bb5  12.b3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn5r/1p1bkppp/p3pn2/2b5/8/4PN2/PP1NBPPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.b3  Bb5  12.Nc4  seen here. }
11... Bb6 { The bishop controls both the a5/c5 squares. } 12. Bd2
{ White not only develops its piece but only sets up a serious threat with Bb4. }
12... Nc6
{ Black must control the b4-square, so that White cannot play Bb4 which would create unpleasantness in Black's positions. }
13. Rfc1
{ This move makes sense for White, as it gives the opportunity for the d2-bishop to hide on e1 after Ne4.  13.Rac1  This simply developing move would be pointless because of Black's response  13...Ne4=  Targeting the dark-squared bishop. }
13... Ne4
{ It is beneficial for Black to win a tempo on the d2-bishop, as the e4-knight controls a lot of squares in the center. }
14. Be1 Rhc8
{ The position is very solid for both sides, and I believe it should end in a draw. The e4-knight sometimes finds a nice square on d6. }
