{  } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ We have arrived at the endgame line. White's intention is to play a solid, long game and try to claim that the upcoming endgame is better for them. This line has been quite popular amongst super GMs, therefore a lot of people started to go for this endgame. However, I believe that if Black makes a couple of accurate moves, the endgame should be equal. }
7... Bxc5
{ I recommend this move over  7...Qxd1  because I believe that bringing the white rook to d1 is not ideal. I would rather have White trade queens, because in an endgame the fact that Black will not be able to castle is not very important, since the king on e7 will be perfectly safe. }
8. Qxd8+
{ 8.Qe2  Nbd7  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/8/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.Qe2  a6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.O-O  Nbd7  seen here. }
8... Kxd8
{ Now White has a couple of possibilities. The only thing that is certain for White is to move the c4-bishop, as Black threatens to play ...b5-Bb7, which would significantly help Black's position. Generally speaking, Black wants to place their pieces like ...Ke7-Nbd7-b5/b6 and Bb7. White has to create an unbalanced game, otherwise, the position would be too drawish. }
9. Be2
{ A logical move that steps out of the b7-b5 tempo. If Black would want to develop with  9...b5  , @@StartBracket@@ planning 10...Bb7@@EndBracket@@ then  10.a4  would weaken the Black queenside.   @@StartFEN@@rnbk3r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2b5/2B5/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNB2RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne5   9.Nbd2  Ke7  10.Be2  .  9...Ke7  10.Be2  . }
9... Ke7
{ Black has to first put their king on e7 so White can no longer play Rd1 with a tempo, and then start developing their queenside pieces. }
10. Nbd2
{ This is definitely one of the mainlines of the whole 7.dxc5 line. White intends to either develop with b3-Bb2 or Nb3-Bd2. }
10... Bd7
{ Now, Black has to change their development routine. Usually, I would suggest developing with ...b6-Bb7-Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@which I think would be slightly inaccurate@@EndBracket@@, however here ...Bd7 has a specific reason. Black oftentimes wants to exchange the light-squared bishops via b5. }
11. Nb3
{ The knight's intention is to chase the bishop away and later possibly go  Na5  to bother the b7-pawn.  11.Nc4  Bb5  12.b3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rn5r/1p1bkppp/p3pn2/2b5/8/4PN2/PP1NBPPP/R1B2RK1 w - - 4 11@@EndFEN@@  11.b3  Bb5  12.Nc4  seen here. }
11... Bb6 { The bishop controls both the a5/c5 squares. } 12. Bd2
{ White not only develops its piece but only sets up a serious threat with Bb4. }
12... Nc6
{ Black must control the b4-square, so that White cannot play Bb4 which would create unpleasantness in Black's positions. }
13. Bc3
{ White places its bishop on the long diagonal, and therefore the f6-knight cannot move. Black must solve that issue. }
13... Rhg8
{ The key move. Black protects the g7-pawn, so the f6-knight can move. Next is either ...Ne4 or ...Nd5 targeting the c3-bishop. }
14. Rfd1 Ne4
{ Black solved their problem with the g7-pawn and now chases the c3-bishop away. }
15. Be1 Rgd8
{ The position is very solid for both sides, and therefore the game should end in a draw. Next is ...Be8, and start exchanging the pieces. }
