[Round "?"]
[White "31) 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 7.a3"]
[Black "7.a3 b5 8.Bd3 Bb7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. a3
{ The main idea of this move is that White wants to play dxc5 and after ...Bxc5, b4 would win a tempo. Some strong grandmasters have used this specific line, but I believe that if Black knows how to react, then it is quite easy to get equality. }
7... b5
{ This is the typical move to help Black's development ...b5 and ...Bb7 } 8.
Bd3
{ It is a little bit unusual to combine a3 and Bd3 - it is not in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. On the other hand, White places their bishop on d3  @@StartBracket@@which is a very decent square for the bishop@@EndBracket@@ and plans dxc5-Bxc5-b4. }
8... Bb7 9. dxc5 { White has to stick to their plan. } 9... Bxc5 10. b4 Bd6
{ It is better to put the bishop on d6 than on e7, so it's eyeing the white kingside. }
11. Bb2 O-O
{ This position is exactly symmetrical, but this one extra tempo does not really make a difference. }
12. Qe2 Nbd7 13. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Both sides have finished developing. The position is equal and Black simply has to copy White here. }
