1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. a3
{ The main idea of this move is that White wants to play dxc5 and after ...Bxc5, b4 would win a tempo. Some strong grandmasters have used this specific line, but I believe that if Black knows how to react, then it is quite easy to get equality. }
7... b5
{ This is the typical move to help Black's development ...b5 and ...Bb7 } 8.
Ba2
{ White uses the new square to hide their bishop. It is a rather unusual spot for the bishop as it is pointing towards the f7-e6 pawns, which are not under any pressure. }
8... Bb7
{ Simply developing. The b7-bishop is much better than the bishop on a2. } 9.
Nc3 Nbd7
{ The right square for the knight, as it keeps Black's position flexible. } 10.
Qe2 { White is creating space for the rook on d1. } 10... Bd6
{ It is better to put the bishop on d6, so both bishops are eyeing the white kingside. }
11. Rd1 O-O
{ The position is roughly equal with chances for both sides. I think that Black's position is slightly easier to play as the bishops are much better placed than White's. Next is ...Rc8, ...Qc7, ...Rfd8, ...Qb8. }
