[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "So Wesley vs. Dominguez Perez,  Berlin FIDE GP, 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ A very important game in a very important event. Both players were fighting for the first place in their groups so they could qualify for the Candidate's tournament. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. b3
{ This is one of the mainlines of this fresh ...Qb6 idea, and it is worth knowing. There is a more detailed explanation of this line. }
7... e6 8. bxc4 Bb4 9. Bd2 bxc4 10. Nf3 Ne7 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. O-O a5 13. d5
{ An interesting move. I believe that Wesley had this idea before this game, but I don't think it is dangerous. Black has to play a couple of accurate moves and the position will soon be equal.   13.Na4  Is covered in the 7.b3 chapter.   13.Re1  Is covered in the same 7.b3 chapter. }
13... Ba6
{ Dominguez plays the best move, and it shows how well prepared he is. } 14.
Na4 Qd8
{ The best square for the queen as it steps out of all kinds of danger. The next moves are logical for both sides. }
15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. dxe6 Rxe6 17. Bxb4 axb4 18. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ We arrived at this endgame where Black is completely fine. This shows how good the Queen's Gambit Accepted is since even at a very high level, there is nothing serious that White could show. }
19. Nc5 { Transferring the knight to b3, as it is the best blockading piece. }
19... Rc6 20. Rfc1 Rdc8
{ Simply planning to trade the pieces to secure the draw. } 21. Nb3 Rxc1+ 22.
Rxc1 Rxc1+ 23. Nxc1 f5
{ The best move, as it gives space for the king on f7 and also trades of one of the pawns. }
24. exf5 Nxf5
{ The only side that can win this position is Black. However, the material is too low for any other result than a draw. }
25. Kf1 Nc6 26. Ke2 Kf7 { Briging the king closer to the center. } 27. Kd3 Nd6
{ Controlling the d4-c4 squares, so the king cannot attack the b4-pawn. } 28.
Ne2 Kf6 29. Ned4 Nxd4
{ Trading off one of the knights makes the position even more drawish. } 30.
Nxd4 Nf5 { Offering another knight trade. } 31. Nf3
{ The best choice for White is to keep the knights on the board, as the pawn endgame could be dangerous because of the passed pawn on b4. }
31... Nd6 32. Nd4 Nf5 33. Nf3 Nd6 34. Nd4
{ A very solid and sound game. This was a high-class preparation from Dominguez. I believe that he did not face any problems in this game, against a very powerful player, Wesley So. }
