1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qa4+
{ This sideline is covered more thoroughly in this course3.Nf3 4.Qa4. Dominguez is very well prepared against this rather unusual sideline. }
4... Nc6 5. Qxc4 e5 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Bf4 c6 9. e3 g5
{ A useful move that gives space for Black on the kingside. } 10. Bg3 Qa5+ 11.
Nd2 Be6 12. Qc2 O-O-O { This is where I end my analysis in chapter 11. } 13.
O-O-O
{ As scary as it looks, this is the best way for white to play. The attack on the White queenside is not as dangerous as it looks. }
13... Bb4
{ Black brings another piece into the attack on the queenside, hence White has to be careful here. }
14. a3 Bxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Bb3
{ A very important and nice move. Black is trying to shed light on the White king on c1 and White's underdevelopment. }
16. Qf5+
{ 16.Rxd8+??  Would be a serious error.  16...Rxd8  17.Qxb3  Qe1+  18.Kc2  Rd2+  19.Kc3  Qc1+  20.Kb4  Rxb2-+ }
16... Be6 17. Qc2 Bb3 18. Qc3
{ Richard decides to continue the game. I believe this move required a lot of calculation beforehand, since the next following moves are very forced. }
18... Qxc3+ 19. bxc3 Rxd2 20. Kxd2 Rd8+ 21. Ke2
{ The only move that saves the game, otherwise, White would be lost. } 21...
Rd5 { Black has to target the e5-pawn. } 22. h4
{ White's best plan is to open the h-file for its rook. } 22... Bc4+ 23. Kf3
Nxe5+ 24. Bxe5 Bxf1
{ An important in-between move, so Black does not lose a piece! } 25. Bd4 Rf5+
{ Again, an accurate move. Black otherwise would face unpleasantness because of its scattered pawn structure. }
26. Kg3 gxh4+ 27. Rxh4 Rg5+
{ Forcing White to go for a drawish opposite bishops endgame. } 28. Rg4 Rxg4+
29. Kxg4 Bxg2 30. Bxa7
{ The rest of the game is a simple draw. There is nothing that either side can do because of the opposite-colored bishops. }
30... b5 31. Kg5 Kd7 32. Kh6 Be4 33. f3 Bxf3 34. Kxh7 Ke6 35. Kg7 f5 36. Kf8
Kd5 37. Ke7 Kc4 38. Kd6 Kxc3 39. Bb6 Kb3 40. Bc5 Be4 41. Ke5 Kc4 42. Kd6 Kb3
