[Black "Radjabov Teimour vs. Ding Liren, FIDE World Cup, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5
{ This is a different opening, however, we will transfer to the QGA. } 5. e3
{ 5.cxd5  is the critical line.  5.e3  is a more solid approach. } 5... dxc4 6.
Bxc4 a6 { We have a nice QGA setup. } 7. O-O
{ Now we have transposed to the 7.Nc3 chapter you will find more explanation about the opening details there. }
7... b5 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. d5 exd5 10. Nxd5 Bb7 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. a4 b4 13. e4 h6
14. Qc2 Bd6 15. Be3 O-O 16. Nd2 Bf4 17. Bxf4 Qxf4
{ This is the point where I end my analysis in the 7.Nc3 chapter. Black equalized, however, I believe that this middlegame pawn structure is worth analyzing. Let's see how Ding Liren played here. }
18. f3
{ This is the ideal pawn setup which makes to b7 bishop less effective. On the other hand, the dark squares are going to be slightly weak for White. }
18... Rfd8 { Placing the rook on the open file is a healthy developing move. }
19. Nc4
{ The knight finds a very nice spot on c4. If Black does not react accordingly then the knights will overpower Black. }
19... Ne5
{ The best is to immediately trade the knights since the c4 knight is better than the d7.   19...a5!?  This is the other possibility, however, I prefer how Ding played. }
20. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ Now that Black managed to exchange the knights there is nothing to worry about anymore. }
21. Rac1 Rac8 22. Bc4 a5
{ Fixing the pawns favors Black. White will not be able to attack the a5-pawn with its c4-bishop, whereas Black could attack the a4-pawn with its b7-bishop. }
23. Rfd1 Rd4
{ A very nice principled move. Black is trying to put pressure on White here, as the dark squares are weak in White's position. }
24. b3 Rcd8 25. Rxd4
{ White has to start making forced moves not to get in trouble. } 25... cxd4
26. Qd3 h5
{ Black intends to win space on the kingside by pushing its pawn to h4. } 27.
Rd1
{ White is setting a trap here. The threat is Bd5-Bxd5-Qxd4! pinning the bishop. }
27... Rd7
{ Now Bd5 does not work anymore.  27...h4?  28.Bd5!  Bxd5  29.Qxd4  Qxd4+  30.Rxd4  . }
28. Bb5 Rd8 29. Bc4 Rd7 30. Bb5 Rd8
{ A very high-class game from both sides. Healthy, logical moves. This is how I imagine playing the QGA from the Black side. }
