[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Shirov Alexei vs. Vitiugov Nikita, Sochi, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ This is the Slav Defense, however, a few moves later we will transpose to the QGA. }
3. Nc3 dxc4 4. e4 b5
{ We transposed to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  dxc4  3.e4  b5  4.a4  c6  5.Nc3  . You will find my explanation about this line with much more details here. }
5. a4 b4 6. Na2 { I think it is bad to place the knight on a2 in general. }
6... Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bxc4 e6 9. Nf3 a5
{ 9...Be7  I recommend this move in my course over  9...a5  because  9...Be7  stops white from playing Ng5 like in the game. }
10. Ng5 { Now white can start putting pressure on the Black kingside. } 10...
Ba6 { Exchanging the light-squared bishops benefits Black. } 11. Qh5 Qd7 12. b3
{ 12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.Bd2  c5  Black is slightly better. } 12... h6
{ It is generally good to play h6 in these positions, so White cannot take on h7. }
13. O-O Bxc4 14. bxc4 Nb6
{ Two pawns are under attack, and that gives Black an advantage. } 15. c5
{ The best possibility for White. } 15... Nxa4 16. Be3
{ The White central pawns restrict the Black pieces, therefore, White has some compensation for the pawn. }
16... b3 { Black is winning a piece here. } 17. Ne4 bxa2 18. Qe2 Qd5
{ The only move that keeps the advantage. } 19. f3
{ The only problem that Black is facing here is the a4-knight. White is trying to trap the knight after playing Rxa2. }
19... Qb3 20. Rxa2 Nc3
{ It seems like Black solves its issues with the knight, however, White can keep the game going. }
21. Qd3 Qxa2 22. Nxc3
{ Now Black is a full rook up, however, White has some compensation because the queen on a2 is in trouble. }
22... Qa3 23. Rb1 { Next is Bc1 which will trap the queen. } 23... Bxc5
{ The best move. Black has to give up some material to save the queen on a3. }
24. Bc1
{ 24.dxc5?  After this, the queen on a3 would not be in trouble anymore.  24...O-O  25.Bc1  Qxc5+-+ }
24... Bxd4+
{ 24...Qb4!  Giving up the queen would have been the better option.  25.Rxb4  Bxb4  26.Ne4  Nd7∓  Black is significantly better, however, there is still some work to be done. }
25. Qxd4 Qe7 26. Ne4 { The knight on e4 gives White a great deal of attack. }
26... Nd7
{ 26...O-O  27.Nf6+!  I believe that this is what Vitiugov missed when he decided the go for 24...Bxd4. Here White has a dangerous attack against the g8-king. }
27. Rb7 { Pinning the knight. } 27... Rd8
{ 27...O-O !  Giving up the d7-knight would have been better since the king on g8 would be safe.  28.Rxd7  Qb4⩱  After exchanging the queens, Black will have a relatively safe, slightly better endgame. }
28. Nd6+ Kf8 29. Ba3
{ All the White pieces are in play therefore the attack against the Black king on f8 is dangerous. }
29... Kg8 30. h4
{ A very important move, which gains space for White on the kingside. } 30...
f6 31. Qe4 { 31.exf6  Qxf6  32.Qe4  Would have been slightly more accurate. }
31... fxe5
{ 31...f5!  32.Qxc6  Nxe5  33.Qc5  Rd7!  34.Rb8+  Kh7  35.Rxh8+  Kxh8  36.Qxe5  Qf6-+  Black is winning here. }
32. Qxc6 Qxh4 33. Nf5 { Secures the draw. } 33... exf5 34. Qe6+ Kh7 35. Qxf5+
Kg8 36. Qe6+ Kh7 37. Qf5+ Kg8 { A very interesting game from both sides. } *

