8... b3
{ Black chases the queen away, as after Qc3, ...Nd5 would come with tempo. } 9.
Qd1 Nd5 10. Na3 e6
{ A stable move but not the best.  10...Nb4!  This move would give Black bigger advantage than the game, as White can't capture the c4-pawn.  11.e6  Qd5-+  . }
11. Nxc4 Nb4 12. Qxb3 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qe4 14. O-O-O
{ It is unusual that White goes long castle in the QGA, but this is one of those few positions. The White king is vulnerable on the queenside. }
14... Nd7
{ Black has a simple plan with ...Rb8 to attack the White queenside. } 15. Nf3
Rb8 16. Ng5
{ 16.Bxa7  Grabbing the pawn would have been the best defense, however, White's position remains dangerous.  16...Nc5  17.Bxc5  Bxc5→  . }
16... Qg6 { White has too many problems here. The queenside is too weak. } 17.
Nd6+ Bxd6 18. exd6 Bxf1 19. Rhxf1 O-O
{ Black finally castles and has a free attack against the White king on c1. }
20. h4 Ne5
{ Another piece joins the attack. The rest of the game is an easy win for Black. }
21. Kd2 Nd5 22. Qc2 Rxb2 23. Qxb2 Nc4+ 24. Kc1 Nxb2
{ A very convincing game by Vitiugov. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Greenfeld Alon vs. Nguyen Thai Dai Van, Tornelo INT, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 b5 4. a4 c6 5. axb5 cxb5 6. Nc3
{ This is one of the most critical lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. } 6...
Qb6
{ I recommend this fresh idea in my course. I explain this move in great detail here. I first saw this idea from Nguyen, and he also wrote a New In Chess article about this line. }
7. Nd5 Qb7 8. Bf4 e5 9. Bxe5 Nd7 10. Nf3
{ An immediate mistake. Giving up the dark-squared bishop is a bad idea. You will find other possibilities in chapter 17. }
10... Ngf6
{ 10...Nxe5  This would be very good for Black as well.  11.Nxe5  Nf6∓  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pq3ppp/8/1p1Nn3/2pPP3/5N2/1P3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.dxe5  Ne7∓ }
11. Bxf6
{ 11.Nc7+  Going for the material would be bad for White for tactical reasons.  11...Kd8  12.Nxa8  Bb4+!  13.Nd2  Nxe5  14.dxe5  Nxe4-+  . }
11... Nxf6 12. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Black definitely won the opening battle. The bishop pair is very powerful in this position. }
13. Be2 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 O-O
{ The king is totally safe on the kingside, whereas the king on f1 is questionable. }
15. d5 { Not the best move in an anyway hard position. } 15... Re8
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 16. Nd4 { 16.Qc2  Qe7-+  . } 16... Rxe4 17. Nc6 a5
{ Simply defending the b4-bishop, and stopping White from playing Bf3 due to Re1. }
18. f3 Re8 19. Qd4 Bf8
{ Again the best move. Black is transferring the bishop to the long diagonal. The rest of the game goes easy for Black. }
20. Qxf6 Bg7 21. Qg5 h6 22. Qh4 a4 23. Rd1 Bf5
{ The position is completely lost, White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Leko Peter vs. Ponomariov Ruslan, Dortmund, 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O c5 7. dxc5
{ This endgame line is very popular. People like to play this with White because there is relatively no chance of losing. However, if Black plays some accurate moves, then equality should not be a question. You will find a great deal of explanation here. }
7... Bxc5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Ne5 Ke7 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 Ra7
{ I believe this is slightly inaccurate.  11...b6  I recommend this move in my course. The idea is that Black wants to develop its bishop either to b7 or with a5-Ba6.  12.Nc3  a5!  See my analyses here. }
12. Nbd2 { 12.Bd2⩲  This would be worth considering. } 12... b5 13. Na5 Rc7 14.
a4
{ White intends to create weaknesses on the Black queenside.   14.Ndb3  Bd6  15.a4  bxa4  16.Rxa4  Nc5  Black would be more or less fine. }
14... bxa4 15. Ndc4 { Preventing ...Nb6.  15.Rxa4  Nb6  . } 15... Nb8
{ A very nice move, as it gives space for the bishop on d7. } 16. Rxa4 Bd7 17.
Ra1 Bb5
{ The bishop finds a very nice square on b5, as it solves the often weak a6-pawn problem. }
18. b3 Ne4 19. Bb2 f6 { Closing the long diagonal. } 20. Bf3 Ng5 21. Be2 Rd8
{ Black equalized without a question. } 22. Rfc1 Bb4
{ The knights are stuck on their squares, as the Black bishops put pressure on them. }
23. Bf1 Nd7 { 23...Ne4  It was about time to bring the knight back to action. }
24. Ba3 Bc5
{ 24...Bxa3?!  Trading the bishops this way would be a mistake.  25.Nxa3  Rxc1  26.Rxc1±  . }
25. Bxc5+ Nxc5 26. Na3 { 26.Nb6  Bxf1  27.Kxf1  Rb8  28.Na4  Rbc8=  . } 26...
Bxf1 27. Kxf1 Rdc8 { Stabilizing on the c-file. } 28. f3 Nf7
{ Placing the knight on a better square, as it was useless on g5. } 29. Rc3 Nd7
30. Rxc7 Rxc7 31. N3c4 Nfe5
{ Trading one more piece. The rest of the game goes pretty smoothly for both sides. }
32. Ke2 Nxc4 33. Nxc4 Nc5 34. Na5 Nb7 35. Nxb7 Rxb7 36. Rxa6 Rxb3 37. Ra7+ Kf8
38. Kf2
{ A high class game. I believe that this game proves that @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2BP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.dxc5  is not a dangerous line if Black knows how to react against it, as Ponomariov did. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Cramling Pia vs. Kortschnoj Viktor, Roquebrune, 1998"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. e4
{ A pawn sacrifice. This is a very ambitious move, White wants to get a good attack in the center. }
7... b5
{ This is a more stable approach than ...Nxe4. Black wants to develop its pieces immediately.   7...Nxe4  8.Qe2   8.d5!?  8...Nf6  9.d5  Nxd5  10.Rd1  White gets a great deal of attack. }
8. Bd3 { Other moves are covered in great detail in this chapter. } 8... cxd4
{ 8...Bb7  I recommend this move in my course. It is better to develop and attack the e4-pawn. }
9. a4 { White's intention is to weaken the Black queenside. } 9... bxa4 10. e5
{ 10.Qxa4+  Bd7  11.Qxd4  Nc6  12.Qe3  Nb4=  Black would be fine. } 10... Nd5
11. Qxa4+ Bd7 12. Qxd4 Nb4
{ Going after the light-squared bishop.   12...Nc6  13.Qe4⩲  White would have serious pressure on the Black kingside. }
13. Bg5
{ A tempting move, but not the best.   13.Be2!  Keeping the bishop would give White an advantage.  13...Nc2  14.Qe4±  . }
13... Be7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Be4 N8c6
{ 15...Bc6  Would have been better to face the e4-bishop. } 16. Qe3 O-O 17.
Nbd2 { 17.Nc3  The knight would be better placed on c3 than on d2. } 17... Rab8
18. Nb3 { An interesting move with the plan of Nc5. } 18... Rfd8
{ Black finally achieved the ideal setup. Black's position is very stable with the plan of ...Be8. }
19. Nc5 a5 20. Rfd1 Be8 { Now Black takes over the driver's seat. } 21. h3 h6
{ Freeing the back-rank, and covering the g5-square. } 22. Rxd8 Qxd8 23. Qc3
Qb6
{ 23...Nd5  The rook would put more pressure on White, as the b-file is now open. }
24. Nb3
{ A very important defending move. This move intends to put pressure on the a5-pawn. }
24... Ne7
{ 24...Rd8⩱  Placing the rook on the open file would promise a slight advantage for Black. }
25. Nxa5 Nbd5 26. Qd4
{ 26.Qe1⩲  I believe this move was missed by both players. Now Black cannot win the b2-pawn back, since it would lose material.  26...Qxb2??  27.Rb1+-  . }
26... Qxb2
{ The position will become very drawish after the queen trade. The rest of the game went smoothly for both sides. }
27. Qxb2 Rxb2 28. Nc4 Rb8 29. Nd6 Nc3 30. Bd3 Ba4 31. Ra3 Rb3 32. Rxb3 Bxb3 33.
Nd4 Ba4 34. f4 Ncd5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Praggnanandhaa Rameshbabu vs. Carlsen Magnus, Wijk aan Zee, 2022 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ A slightly different move order. We will eventually transfer to QGA. } 3. Nf3
dxc4 4. e3 a6 5. Bxc4 Nf6 6. O-O c5 7. b3
{ A solid move. White intends to develop with Bb2-Nbd2. } 7... b6
{ 7...Nbd7  I recommend this move in my course. I believe it gives more flexibility than 7...b6, since after ...Nbd7, Black could still play ...b5. You will find my analyses about this line here. }
8. Ba3
{ A very interesting idea. It is a rather unusual way to put pressure on Black in the QGA. I believe this was prepared by Praggnanandhaa, and perhaps not by Magnus. }
8... Nbd7 9. d5 { A very important breakthrough in the center. } 9... exd5 10.
Bxd5 Rb8
{ 10...Nxd5?!  This exchange would give White too much activity and space.  11.Qxd5  Ra7  12.Bb2±  . }
11. Bb2 Be7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Qc2
{ White has won the opening battle, however, the position is very rich with chances for both sides. }
13... b5 { Trying to gain more space on the queenside. } 14. Rfd1
{ 14.Rad1  Perhaps would have been slightly more accurate. } 14... Qc7 15. a4
{ 15.Rac1  Nb6  16.Be4⩲  White is slightly better. } 15... h6
{ A safe, prophylactic move.  15...b4!  16.Ne2  Nxd5  17.Rxd5  c4!  I believe that this idea was missed by both players. It is pawn sacrifice but it is very beneficial for Black.   17...Bb7  18.Nf4!  Bxd5  19.Nxd5  Qd8  20.Rd1=∞  With great compensation.  18.bxc4  b3  19.Qd1  Bf6↑  Black has a very nice compensation for the pawn here, as the b3-pawn is powerful and the c4-pawn is very weak. }
16. axb5 axb5 17. Qe2 Qb6
{ This is still a very rich position, as White has a lot of possibilities. However, the d5-bishop seems awkward. }
18. e4 Re8 { The best move. The rook belongs on the e-file. } 19. Qd2
{ 19.e5  Bf8  20.Ba8=  It is very hard to find a move like this. White's main idea is to give space for the c3-knight on d5. }
19... Bf8
{ Black is better now, as there are no e5 possibilities for White here, and eventually, the d5-bishop will have disadvantages. }
20. Qf4 b4 { Magnus plays the best move here. } 21. Na4 Nxd5
{ A very important in-between move otherwise White would retreat its bishop to c4. }
22. Rxd5 Qe6 { 22...Qb7!  This would have been the best move, ...Ra8 is next. }
23. Rad1
{ 23.Nxc5!  This was Praggnanadhaa's last hope.  23...Bxc5  24.Rxc5  Nxc5  25.Qxb8  Qxb3  26.Bd4!  Nxe4  27.h3  White has some chances to hold. }
23... Ra8 24. Qc1 Qxe4 { Now Black is completely winning. } 25. h3
{ 25.Rxd7  Bxd7  26.Rxd7  Rad8  27.Rxd8  Rxd8-+  This position would be hopeless for White because of its badly placed pieces. }
25... Ra7 26. Qd2 Qg6 27. Nh4 Qe6 28. Nf5 c4
{ 28...Bb7!  29.Nxh6+  Qxh6  30.Qxh6  Bxd5-+  A very important in-between move. It is probably unnecessary to sacrifice a queen, however, it might be the best. }
29. Qd4
{ 29.Bxg7!  Bxg7  30.Nxg7  Kxg7  31.Rd6  White would have some attack, however the position would remain bad.  31...Qe7  32.Qxh6+  Kg8  33.R1d4  Nf8∓  . }
29... Nf6 { Now white has no more attacking ideas. } 30. Nb6 c3
{ Closing the long diagonal. The rest of the game requires no explanation, Magnus plays perfectly. }
31. Nxc8 Qxd5 32. Qxd5 Nxd5 33. Nxa7 cxb2 34. Rb1 Re2
{ A very interesting game from both sides. I believe that this game shows how good the Queen's Gambit Accepted is if the World Champion plays it in classical games. }
*

